<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blues' Tony Twist Hurt in Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- St. Louis Blues enforcer Tony Twist was  
hospitalized in intensive care following a motorcycle accident, the 
Blues said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened shortly after 10 p.m. Monday in Creve  
Coeur, a suburb of St. Louis. Police said a car pulled from a 
parking lot in front of Twist's motorcycle, which struck the side 
of the car, ejecting Twist. 
</P>
<P>
	No charges have been filed, Capt. Dale Bailey said. The driver  
of the car was also hurt. His condition was not immediately known. 
</P>
<P>
	Twist was taken to St. John's Mercy Medical Center in suburban  
St. Louis. The Blues said he would be transferred later today to 
Barnes-Jewish Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	A St. John's spokeswoman said Twist's family asked that no  
details of his condition be released. 
</P>
<P>
	Blues team doctors were with Twist, considered one of the NHL's  
best fighters. He is one of St. Louis' most popular sports figures, 
largely because he has long been active in community and charitable 
organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	Twist became an unrestricted free agent after the 1998-99  
season, and has not signed with any team. In 63 games last season 
for St. Louis, Twist had two goals and eight points while 
accumulating 149 penalty minutes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
