<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 10, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Gunman Shoots 5 at Jewish Center  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A man with a high-powered gun burst into a  
Jewish community center today and sprayed the lobby with 20 to 30 
shots, wounding five people, including three boys attending day 
camp, and then walked away. Police searched the surrounding 
suburban neighborhood for the man, described as a bald white male 
around 40 years old. The motive was not known. The most seriously 
injured was a 5-year-old boy who was in critical but stable 
condition. Two 6-year-old boys, a 16-year-old girl and a 
68-year-old woman were in stable condition, officials said. ``Once 
again our, our nation has been shaken and our hearts torn by gun 
violence,'' said President Clinton. 

</P>
<P>
	Tensions High Between Pakistan, India  
</P>
<P>
	LAKHPAT, India (AP) -- Tensions reignited between the world's  
newest nuclear powers today after India shot down a Pakistani 
reconnaissance plane and Pakistan threatened to retaliate. Pakistan 
said the attack killed 16 of its servicemen. The two countries 
disputed where the plane was shot down and on whose territory its 
wreckage landed. The clash dispelled any immediate hope of moving 
relations between the two powers back onto a peaceful track. India 
and Pakistan have fought three wars since they gained independence 
from Britain in 1947. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Gore Campaign Together  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Inseparable was one label for President  
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore today. They scheduled four 
fund-raising events, three meals, a tour and a roundtable together. 
Last weekend, Clinton and Gore paired up for the first time on the 
Campaign 2000 trail, picking up at least $250,000 in Arkansas and 
trying to put to rest lingering reports of dissension between the 
two men. They have several additional joint fund-raisers planned. 

</P>
<P>
	US, S. Korea Plan Military Exercise  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The United States and South Korea said  
today they will conduct a joint military exercise next week amid 
rising tensions with North Korea and fears that the isolated nation 
will test a new ballistic missile. This week, North Korea accused 
the United States of conspiring to start a war on the Korean 
peninsula by insisting the communist country put off the test 
missile launch. North Korea today also threatened ``merciless 
retaliation'' if Japan tries anything provocative. 

</P>
<P>
	Eclipse Chasers Gather in Turkey  
</P>
<P>
	HARPUT, Turkey (AP) -- A 4,000-year-old outpost on the old Silk  
Road was transformed into a bustling tourist center today as 
scientists and eclipse chasers from around the world came in search 
of a front row seat for the last total eclipse of the millennium. 
Once a main stop on the Silk Route, the remote southeastern village 
of Harput has only 150 residents and rarely sees any tourists. But 
more than 1,000 people have descended this week on Harput, which 
gets some of the best visibility in Europe and lies on the eclipse 
line that runs around the globe. The eclipse will take place 
tomorrow at 2:36 p.m. local time, and will last for two minutes. 

</P>
<P>
	GM Plans 'Web Car' for 2000  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. plans to offer  
voice-activated Internet access in a car by the end of next year as 
part of a campaign announced today. GM has formed an independent 
unit called ``e-GM'' to expand its global electronic commerce 
activities. Within five years, in-car services such as Internet 
access and CD-quality satellite radio broadcasts could generate 
revenues for GM in the range of $4 billion to $6 billion annually, 
said Ron Zarrella, president of GM's North American operations. 

</P>
<P>
	Mid-Night Sleeping Pill Developed  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Insomniacs may soon have a sleeping pill they  
can take in the middle of the night with less fear of being groggy 
in the morning. American Home Products hopes to win U.S. government 
approval later this year for Sonata, a drug that wears off faster 
than existing medicines. Sleep experts say the pill is a 
significant improvement because of the new flexibility it gives 
people who have trouble sacking out. Sonata's effects last just 
four hours. Other pills last eight hours or more. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Falls 52.55; Nasdaq Drops 28.87  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks continued their slide today as investors  
remained unsettled by growing expectations that the Federal Reserve 
will raise interest rates at least once more this year. The Dow 
Jones industrial average fell 52.55 to 10,655.15. Declining issues 
on the New York Stock Exchange led advancers 2,317-768. The Nasdaq 
was down 28.87 to 2,490.11 

</P>
<P>
	D-Backs Match '98 Win Total  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Arizona Diamondbacks matched last year's  
total with their 65th win, beating the Chicago Cubs 3-1 today 
behind Steve Finley's 22nd homer. Arizona (65-49), which began the 
day 5 1/2 games ahead of second-place San Francisco in the NL West, 
has won four straight and 16 of 20. The Diamondbacks finished last 
with a 65-97 record last year in their inaugural season. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
