<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. Settles With Sweepstake Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Ed McMahon and Dick Clark didn't deliver  
the check, but North Carolina came out a million-dollar winner 
against the American Family Publishers sweepstakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will pay the state $1 million to settle a contempt  
of court case involving deceptive mailings, Attorney General Mike 
Easley said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal court order in 1993 barred the company from sending  
misleading promotions into the state. But the company sent new 
mailings in late 1997 and 1998 that indicated the recipient was one 
of two people with the winning number. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whoever returns it first wins it all!'' the mailing said.  
</P>
<P>
	A line of tiny type at the top of the envelope said, ``If you  
have the winning number, please be advised ....'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They thought they had cured the problem with this little trick  
up here,'' Easley said, pointing to the tiny type. ``We told them 
not to use deceptive mailings in North Carolina. They obviously did 
not take our warning seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 mailing led to an agreement between the company and 32  
states to stop some sweepstakes promotion tactics. 
</P>
<P>
	Since North Carolina already had a court order barring such  
tactics, the company was found in civil contempt for violating the 
order. 
</P>
<P>
	The state will get $200,000 to cover its court and investigation  
costs. The rest of the money will be split between public schools 
and people who purchased numerous magazines from the company, 
Easley said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 07:50:22 </DATE_TIME>
