<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Gov't OKs Economy Boost Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand's cabinet approved a  
multibillion-dollar economic stimulus package on Tuesday that looks 
to boost growth by easing a credit crunch, aiding prospective 
homeowners and cutting production costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The measures are the second major economic stimulus package in  
the past four months designed to lift Thailand out of its waning 
economic crisis and boost growth beyond a predicted 1 percent this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new package, more than $2 billion will be injected  
into the private sector to ease the credit crunch. Banks have been 
reluctant to lend to Thai companies since a financial crash two 
years ago because non-performing loans account for almost half of 
total credit. 
</P>
<P>
	Production costs in key export and other sectors will be reduced  
through cuts in import duties. The government also will mobilize 
$500 million for small and medium-size businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this is not enough, we can mobilize up to $1 billion,''  
said Chuti Krairiksh, secretary to Finance Minister Tarrin 
Nimmanhaeminda. ``This is a considerable amount of funds, but it 
can't substitute for investment from the private sector.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chuti said the government will mobilize $1.25 billion from  
government and private banks to fund home loans for low-income wage 
earners and the middle classes. The government also will 
drastically cut the fee for transferal of land titles, Chuti said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those measures are designed to stimulate the moribund real  
estate sector, slumping badly after a property boom imploded along 
with the rest of the economy in mid-1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The Thai baht ended slightly stronger against the U.S. dollar in  
Tuesday's Asian spot trading, dealers said. Thai stock prices ended 
slightly lower, however, as the package failed to bolster 
confidence in a market which fears a hike in U.S. interest rates. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
