<DOCNO> APW19990810.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 15:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Partnerships Plan Uncertain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The nation's largest lawyers' group delayed  
consideration Tuesday of a proposal to allow clients one-stop 
shopping for legal, financial and other professional help. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue is the longstanding ban on lawyers forming partnerships  
with other professionals such as accountants, psychologists and 
social workers. Many in the American Bar Association want to 
consider dropping the ban amid increased competition from huge, 
multi-service international firms. 
</P>
<P>
	But the proposal drew opposition from other ABA members  
concerned that forming such partnerships would harm lawyers' 
professional standards and their ability to promise confidentiality 
and undivided loyalty to their clients. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a nightmare,'' said Philadelphia lawyer Lawrence J. Fox.  
He said he dreamed he was attending a conference of 
multi-profession partnerships and an award was being given to Rep. 
Tom DeLay, R-Texas, for his ``bringing together of extermination 
and legal services.'' DeLay formerly ran a Houston pest 
extermination company. 
</P>
<P>
	Outgoing ABA President Philip Anderson said lawyers cannot  
ignore the fact that the practice of law already is changing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The response of `I don't like it' is not going to make it go  
away,'' Anderson said. ``I don't like it either but it's here and 
it's going to stay here, and the question is what are we going to 
do about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone will write the rules,'' Anderson said. ``The lawyers  
should write the rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ABA's policy-making House of Delegates decided on a majority  
vote to delay the issue pending more study. Even if the proposal 
had passed, the ethics rule changes would have taken effect only 
after an additional ABA vote at a future meeting and then by 
authorities who regulate lawyers' ethics in each state. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed ethics changes would allow people to get legal help  
and accounting or financial planning advice all in one place. Or 
lawyers who practice family law could form partnerships with 
psychologists or social workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The decades-old rules barring lawyers from forming partnerships  
with non-lawyers were intended to protect lawyers' independent 
judgment, protect confidential client information and ensure 
lawyers' loyalty to their clients by avoiding conflicts of 
interest. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal would specify that legal ethics rules apply to all  
lawyers no matter where they work. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox said about 5,000 lawyers already are working for other  
companies on such matters as taxes or mergers and acquisitions. He 
said they are making the ``disingenuous argument that they are not 
practicing law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fox said another lawyer accused him of ``defending the buggy  
whip in the age of the automobile.'' But he said he wanted to 
``circle the wagons around loyalty to clients, confidentiality, 
client accountability and legal independence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sherwin P. Simmons of Miami, who chaired the ABA panel that made  
the proposal, said consumer groups' members want to get legal help 
through non-traditional means, such as at accounting firms. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can we do this in a way which will protect the public? So  
they'll know who's giving them advice and what to expect?'' Simmons 
said. ``We want to have another shot at this. We want to have more 
input from you,'' he told ABA delegates. 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons said he hopes the issue will be raised again when the  
bar association meets in New York next July. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on Tuesday, ABA delegates passed a resolution urging  
federal, state and local legislators to require police to keep 
statistics to help determine whether traffic stops and searches are 
being conducted for racially discriminatory reasons. A number of 
motorists say they have been stopped for no apparent reason other 
than ``driving while black.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The delegates also defeated a proposed ethics rule that would  
restrict lawyers from making political contributions aimed at 
getting government work, a practice known as ``pay to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Current legal ethics rules do not bar such contributions. Nor  
are they necessarily illegal bribery because lawyers usually don't 
make contributions in exchange for government jobs but to be 
included among those considered for such work. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 20:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
