<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blues Enforcer Twist in Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- St. Louis Blues enforcer Tony Twist, who  
recently led a motorcycle ride of 1,500 miles to raise money for 
charity, is hospitalized in intensive care following a cycling 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened shortly after 10 p.m. Monday in Creve  
Coeur, a suburb of St. Louis. Police said a car pulled out of a 
parking lot in front of Twist's motorcycle, which struck the side 
of the car. Twist was thrown from the motorcycle. 
</P>
<P>
	No charges have been filed, and none were likely, police Capt.  
Dale Bailey said Tuesday. The driver of the car was also hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``I found out this morning,'' said Larry Pleau, the Blues'  
general manager, from his offseason home in New Hampshire. ``Our 
concerns are for Tony's health. We're just hoping that everything 
is fine with him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues said they had no details about the accident or Twist's  
condition. A spokeswoman at St. John's Mercy Medical Center said 
Twist's family asked that no details of his condition be released. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital released a statement later Tuesday said that  
surgery to stabilize his fractured pelvis is scheduled for later 
this week. He also received a laceration to his knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Woodcock, the team's vice president for marketing and  
communication, said the Blues' team doctors were with Twist. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10-year NHL veteran recently completed his Iron Horse '99  
tour, a 1,500-mile motorcycle ride through several Western states. 
Former Denver Broncos quarterback John Elway and several NHL 
players joined Twist on the ride, which raised money for Head 
First, a charity that encourages children to wear a helmet when 
riding a bike or roller skating. 
</P>
<P>
	Twist's work with charity, and his standing as one of the NHL's  
top fighters, made him one of St. Louis' most popular sports 
figures. He and friend Kelly Chase, a longtime Blues teammate, are 
considered two of best enforcers in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	But the player whose primary mission is to fight is a dying  
breed since the league began cracking down on brawling. Twist 
became an unrestricted free agent in June after the 1998-99 season 
and has yet to sign with the Blues or a new team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've talked with Tony a couple of time during the summer,''  
Pleau said. ``The conversations are no different that those with 
any other player. I don't comment on what we've talked about, and 
at this time now it is an inappropriate time anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Post-Dispatch said Pleau told Twist on Monday, before his  
accident, that he no longer figured into the Blues' plans and would 
not be re-signed. Twist earned $650,000 last season and was seeking 
a new contract worth $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Twist was the Blues' ninth choice, and 177th selection overall,  
in the 1988 NHL entry draft. He played in 28 games for St. Louis 
during his first NHL season before spending the next four in 
Quebec. He returned to St. Louis as a free agent in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	In 63 games last season for St. Louis, Twist had two goals and  
eight points while accumulating 149 penalty minutes. In his 
445-game NHL career, Twist has 10 goals and 28 points, with 1,121 
penalty minutes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
