<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed lower Tuesday, led by  
declines in banking and technology shares. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies fell 4.36  
points, or 1.5 percent, to close at 291.98. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks and technology stocks fared worst, dropping 2.2 percent  
and 3 percent in their respective indexes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies in  
countries that joined the single currency, closed down 4.49 points 
at 304.08. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index fell 50.48 points to 3,535.10,  
while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed down 59.02 points at 3,491.39. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Energy index was the only sector that rose  
on the day, with a gain of 0.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The big losers in local markets were London, whose FTSE-100  
index of blue-chip shares fell 2.4 percent, and Helsinki's HEX 
index, which fell 4.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Energis led blue-chip fallers in London, sliding 11.5 percent.  
Telewest Communications closed down 8.8 percent, with analysts 
pointing to last week's disappointing first-half results. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, BP Amoco rose as much as 37 pence to 1225 pence,  
after the company said second-quarter profit rose to $1.23 billion, 
against $1.08 billion a year before. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it had laid off 12,500 people by the end of  
July and will lay off an additional 2,000 by the end of the year. 
It also doubled its target for annual merger cost savings to $4 
billion by 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Other gainers in the oil sector Tuesday were Elf-Aquitaine and  
TotalFina, whose shares rose for the second day amid speculation 
that a friendly merger is imminent. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankfurt's Xetra DAX fell 1.7 percent, with chemical companies  
leading the drop, and the Paris CAC-40 index closed down 1.1 
percent. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
