<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cancer Stamp Brings in About $4M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- About $4 million in profits from the Postal  
Service's special breast cancer stamp will be given to a new 
National Cancer Institute research program, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a year of sales, a special stamp that costs 7 cents more than  
regular postage raised $7.8 million to help research on breast 
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials were announcing today that more than half of those  
proceeds would fund the NCI's new ``Insight Awards to Stamp Out 
Breast Cancer,'' a program funding progressive pilot studies for 
extensive breast cancer research. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore, Postmaster General William Henderson and  
this year's Tour de France champion Lance Armstrong, a testicular 
cancer survivor, planned a White House ceremony today to highlight 
other new strides in cancer research. 
</P>
<P>
	On the second anniversary of the 1997 Cancer Genome Anatomy  
Project, Gore that said over 30,000 human genes that predispose 
people to cancer have been identified, more than double the 
original goal. Genome project researchers have additionally 
catalogued more than 66,400 genes in one or more cancers. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president, in a June speech as part of his presidential  
campaign, challenged scientists to identify every cancer-related 
gene by 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	NCI data released today also shows that 8.4 million Americans  
have survived cancer, with the five-year survival rate improving 
over the last decade from 65 percent to 74 percent for children 
with cancer. The adult survival rate improved from 51 percent to 
almost 60 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 23:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> QB Highlights Redskins Scrimmage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LATROBE, Pa. (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Steelers spent the offseason  
looking for an offense. If they've found it yet, they didn't 
display it in a practice with the Washington Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
	The Redskins spent the offseason looking for a deep-threat wide  
receiver. They might have found one in Albert Connell. 
</P>
<P>
	With both teams opening their exhibition schedules this weekend,  
they did not scrimmage Tuesday, as they did Saturday at the 
Redskins' camp in Frostburg, Md., but worked mostly on position 
drills and 7-on-7 passing. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the rain-splattered, 90-minute practice also was spent  
in goal-line drills, which featured brief skirmishes between 
Steelers nose tackle Anthony Dingle and Redskins tight end Stephen 
Alexander, and Redskins center Mark Fisher and Steelers linebacker 
Earl Holmes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was our third practice against them in a week, and it was  
a real intense session,'' Steelers coach Bill Cowher said. ``But I 
told the players that you don't want to let it become like Kansas 
City and New Orleans. If you do, the only other choice is to 
practice among yourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Chiefs and Saints fought so much Thursday in River Falls,  
Wis., that a scheduled Friday scrimmage was canceled. 
</P>
<P>
	Brad Johnson, the former Minnesota quarterback who is trying to  
upgrade the Redskins' deep passing game, consistently went long, 
mainly to Connell. 
</P>
<P>
	Statistics were not kept, but the Redskins went deep far more  
often than they did during last year's 6-10 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just trying to throw it up there and give our guys a  
chance to go get it,'' Johnson said. ``With Albert's speed, he is a 
deep threat. I think he's going to have a great year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Redskins coach Norv Turner said Connell has been a standout  
since training camp began. 
</P>
<P>
	``Albert made some big plays, and he's had good practices the  
last week,'' Turner said. ``We need to keep him going. Brad's 
throwing the ball exceptionally well, but there were a couple of 
things we missed. The bad thing is we still have a lot of work to 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So do the Steelers, who are less than two weeks into learning  
new offensive coordinator Kevin Gilbride's system. Kordell Stewart 
didn't throw deep that much, although he hit receivers Hines Ward 
and Will Blackwell for long completions. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart expects to play only the first quarter of Friday's  
exhibition game against the Chicago Bears. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Saturday's scrimmage in Frostburg, when Cowher was  
visibly displeased with rookie kickers Kris Brown and Matt 
Davenport, both were much more consistent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown made four of five field-goal attempts between the 30 and  
42 yard lines, missing from the 35. Davenport made three of four 
between the 30 and 38, missing his 30-yarder. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the Redskins' three kickers separated themselves. Brett  
Conway, Jeff Hall and Cary Blanchard each missed once as the 
Redskins also attempted nine field goals. 
</P>
<P>
	Redskins fullback Larry Centers provided one light moment,  
high-stepping his way into the end zone, then seeking out a TV 
photographer to flaunt the ball in front of his camera. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the final practice between the two, although they play  
an exhibition game Aug. 28 in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	``It breaks up training camp,'' Cowher said. ``As I told our  
players, it's much better than practicing against yourselves.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
