<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Appointee May Help With UAW </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp.'s appointment of Mark Hogan  
to run the automaker's electronic commerce operations may also 
serve to pave the way for smoother negotiations for a new national 
contract with the United Auto Workers union. 
</P>
<P>
	Until last spring, Hogan -- who had headed GM's small-car  
operations -- had been publicly promoting ``modular assembly'' as a 
way to drastically cut GM's manufacturing costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The method, already in use overseas, would allow GM to use fewer  
UAW workers and rely more on independent suppliers to do most 
subassembly work of major parts clusters, or modules. GM workers 
would install the modules along shorter assembly lines in smaller 
plants. 
</P>
<P>
	The UAW opposes modular assembly as a threat to job security.  
</P>
<P>
	At a union convention in May, President Stephen P. Yokich said  
the issue was dead and that Hogan should be fired. ``If they can't 
fire him, they should put a muzzle on him,'' Yokich said. 
</P>
<P>
	Muzzle him they did.  
</P>
<P>
	Until Tuesday, Hogan had been kept away from reporters and GM's  
top executives had avoided discussing modular assembly. Hogan had 
been scheduled to give a speech on modular assembly at an industry 
conference last week, but was pulled off the agenda after Yokich's 
outburst. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked Tuesday if he could even say ``modular assembly,''  
Hogan declined. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to be more flexible in the way we design, engineer  
and ultimately manufacture vehicles,'' he said. ``That's what it's 
all about and that's where we're heading.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GM president G. Richard Wagoner Jr. hinted that GM may still  
adopt modular methods using UAW workers, rather than nonunion 
suppliers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where you assemble those modules, frankly, is not critical to  
implement the strategy,'' he said. ``I think you'll see across our 
plants in the U.S. a lot of different ideas tried out, as we've 
done around the world. It's not clear that one method or another is 
going to be the winning strategy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wagoner insisted that Hogan's appointment to head the new  
e-commerce unit was not designed to get him out of Yokich's line of 
fire. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted somebody who had global expertise, somebody who's a  
broad thinker, somebody who's willing to look at things differently 
and push the needle, and somebody who's got a track record of great 
business results,'' Wagoner said. 
</P>
<P>
	GM is focused on rebuilding its relationship with the UAW after  
last year's devastating strikes that shut down the automaker's 
North American operations and seriously hurt its U.S. market share. 
</P>
<P>
	Harley Shaiken, a University of California-Berkeley labor  
professor who monitors UAW issues, said Hogan's move can only help. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether that was by design or default, it serves the purpose  
to soften one of the more contentious issues in the bargaining,'' 
Shaiken said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
