<HEADLINE> 4 Retailers Settle Sweatshop Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Four prominent retailers will pay for  
independent monitoring of Saipan's garment industry as part of a 
settlement of a federal class-action lawsuit brought to prevent 
worker abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Nordstrom Inc., J. Crew Group Inc., Cutter &AMP; Buck Inc. and  
Gymboree Corp. agreed to the oversight of their contractors with 
factories in the U.S. territory in an effort to comply with 
American labor laws and international human rights treaties. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one wants to destroy the garment industry in Saipan, but it  
should not come at the price of indentured servitude,'' plaintiffs' 
attorney William Lerach said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Christina Snyder still must approve the  
settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Three lawsuits filed Jan. 13 described approximately 32  
contractors in Saipan as ``America's worst sweatshop'' where there 
were beatings, forced abortions, vermin-infested quarters, barbed 
wire and armed guards. Employees worked 12 hours a day, seven days 
a week, the suits claim. 
</P>
<P>
	Abuses in Saipan, a 13-mile-long Western Pacific island in the  
Northern Marianas, had been documented previously, but the lawsuits 
were the first legal attempt to hold U.S. retailers accountable for 
alleged mistreatment of workers by subcontractors under the federal 
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Clothing made in the Saipan factories are stamped with ``Made in  
the USA'' tags, making it appear it was made in compliance with 
U.S. labor laws, the suits alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the settlement call for the companies to establish a  
$1.25 million fund to finance the independent monitoring program, 
provide money to the workers, create a public education campaign 
and pay attorneys' fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Nordstrom co-president Erik Nordstrom called the deal ``a  
positive step toward our goal of ensuring that the goods we 
contract to manufacture in Saipan are made in compliance with 
law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Cutter &AMP; Buck chairman Harvey Jones said his company already  
closely monitors its Saipan contractors, and called the firm's 
decision to settle ``a business decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Statements released by J. Crew and Gymboree stressed the  
companies have not admitted wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys also filed a letter of agreement in principle to  
settle with Polo Ralph Lauren Corp., Phillips-Van Heusen Corp., 
Donna Karan International Inc. and Chadwick's of Boston Ltd., who 
were to be named as defendants. 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles on Monday, attorneys for the lawsuit's 13  
remaining defendants argued the case should be shifted to Saipan 
for jurisdictional reasons. No ruling was made. 
</P>
<P>
	A related federal suit filed in Saipan targeting overtime pay  
was dismissed by a judge on Friday, Lerach said. A third suit, 
filed at state court in San Francisco against 18 retailers, will 
also be settled, he said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
