<HEADLINE> Blues' Twist Injured on Motorcycle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- St. Louis Blues enforcer Tony Twist, who  
recently led a motorcycle ride to raise money for charity, was 
hospitalized in intensive care Tuesday following a motorcycle 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
	St. John's Mercy Medical Center issued a statement Tuesday  
afternoon saying surgery to stabilize Twist's pelvis injury is 
scheduled for later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened Monday night in Creve Coeur, a suburb of  
St. Louis. Police said a car pulled out of a parking lot in front 
of Twist's motorcycle, and he struck the side of the car.. 
</P>
<P>
	No charges have been filed, and none were likely, police Capt.  
Dale Bailey said. The driver of the car was also hurt. His 
condition was not immediately known. 
</P>
<P>
	``I found out this morning,'' said Larry Pleau, the Blues'  
general manager. ``Our concerns are for Tony's health. We're just 
hoping that everything is fine with him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues said they had no details about Twist's condition.  
</P>
<P>
	Bailey said Twist was able to speak after the accident. The St.  
Louis Post-Dispatch reported on its Web site on Tuesday that Twist 
also sustained injuries to his knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Woodcock, the Blues' vice president for marketing and  
communication, said team doctors were with Twist. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10-year veteran had recently completed his Iron Horse '99  
tour, a 1,500-mile motorcycle ride through several Western states. 
Former Denver Broncos quarterback John Elway and several NHL 
players joined Twist on the ride, which raised money for Head 
First, a charity that encourages children to wear a helmet when 
riding a bike or roller skating. 
</P>
<P>
	Twist's work with charity, and his standing as one of the NHL's  
top fighters, made him one of St. Louis' most popular sports 
figures. He and friend Kelly Chase, a longtime Blues teammate, are 
considered two of best enforcers in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	Twist became an unrestricted free agent in June after the  
1998-99 season and has yet to sign with the Blues or a new team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've talked with Tony a couple of time during the summer,''  
Pleau said. ``The conversations are no different that those with 
any other player. I don't comment on what we've talked about, and 
at this time now it is an inappropriate time anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Post-Dispatch said Pleau told Twist on Monday, before his  
accident, that he no longer figured into the Blues' plans and would 
not be re-signed. Twist earned $650,000 last season and was seeking 
a new contract worth $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Twist was the Blues' ninth choice, and 177th selection overall,  
in the 1988 entry draft. He played in 28 games for St. Louis during 
his first season before spending the next four in Quebec. He 
returned to St. Louis as a free agent in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	In 63 games last season for St. Louis, Twist had two goals and  
eight points while accumulating 149 penalty minutes. In his 
445-game NHL career, Twist has scored 10 goals and 28 points while 
racking up 1,121 penalty minutes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
