<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Grand Slams in One Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	On a grand night for hitters, pitchers got slammed.  
</P>
<P>
	For the first time in 129 years of major league baseball, five  
grand slams were hit in one day. 
</P>
<P>
	Fernando Tatis of the St. Louis Cardinals and Jose Vidro of the  
Montreal Expos got it started Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Mike Lowell of the Florida Marlins connected, Bernie  
Williams of the New York Yankees followed and Jay Buhner of the 
Seattle Mariners set the record. 
</P>
<P>
	Buhner was unaware of the record.  
</P>
<P>
	``I did? That's cool. Right on!'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Four grand slams were hit in one day many times since major  
league baseball began in 1871, but never five. The last time four 
were hit was July 28, 1998, when Sammy Sosa, Gabe Alvarez, Darrin 
Jackson and Ray Lankford connected. 
</P>
<P>
	This has been a season of slams in the big leagues. The five  
raised the majors' total to 96 -- the record of 141 was set in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not necessarily the quality or lack of quality of  
pitching, it's the style,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``I 
think pitchers do not want the guy to hit the ball, so it's ball 
one, ball two and then you've got to come down the middle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After becoming the first player to hit two slams in the same  
inning on April 23 at Los Angeles, Tatis hit the third of his 
career on Billy Brewer's first pitch in the fourth inning during a 
12-6 win at Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	With three slams this year, Tatis tied Jim Bottomley (1925) and  
Keith Hernandez (1977) for the Cardinals' record. Tatis is 7-for-10 
with 22 RBIs when hitting with the bases loaded this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Vidro connected on his first pitch from Carlos Almanzar in the  
sixth inning of the Expos' 8-0 win over visiting San Diego. It was 
his first grand slam in the majors and Montreal's first since last 
Aug. 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell hit his first career grand slam on a 3-1 pitch in the  
eighth inning against San Francisco's John Johnstone, who had just 
relieved starter Livan Hernandez. The home run tied the score at 4, 
and Florida went on to beat the Giants 5-4. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams' sixth career slam came at Oakland on a full-count  
pitch by reliever Mike Oquist, capping an eight-run second inning 
that gave the New York Yankees an 8-0 lead in a 12-8 win over the 
Athletics. Williams started toward first after taking a 2-2 pitch 
for a ball, then returned to the plate as his teammates laughed in 
the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	Buhner, who had been 0-for-4 with the bases loaded this year,  
connected in the sixth inning at Safeco Field on a 3-1 pitch from 
John Snyder of the White Sox. The homer gave the Mariners a 6-3 
lead in a 6-4 win over Chicago, 
</P>
<P>
	The three grand slams in one day tied the AL record, last  
accomplished last Aug. 14. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been 57 slams in the AL this season and 39 in the NL.  
Both leagues set records in 1996, with 81 slams in the AL and 60 in 
the NL. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 21:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nebraska Grain Bins Full from 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- With reports of record-challenging harvests  
for both soybeans and corn expected from Nebraska fields this fall, 
farmers and elevator operators are trying to figure out where to 
put their crop. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is grain storage centers still have plenty of the  
1998 harvest on hand. 
</P>
<P>
	State agriculture officials said that never in history have  
Nebraska farmers moved toward a fall harvest with as many soybeans 
in their bins. And the corn picture isn't much better, where 
carryover from the 1998 crop is the highest since 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of the perils of farming, unfortunately,'' Ken  
Wurdeman from the Lincoln-based Nebraska Corn Board said Monday. 
``It's not like the auto industry, where you can just shut down an 
assembly line and quit making cars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the third straight year, grain supplies have outstripped  
demand. Farmers who can't afford to let acres sit idle are being 
forced to sell stored grain at prices below production cost to make 
room for the new crop. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like two harvests at one time or one on the heels of the  
other,'' said Pat Ptacek of the Nebraska Grain and Feed 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Valparaiso corn and soybean producer Gary Hellerich said dry  
conditions in eastern states have given a small boost to grain 
prices recently but not enough to make them profitable. 
</P>
<P>
	``Losses are just not as great as they were at an earlier  
time,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn producers waiting for prices to rise since November have  
gotten little reward for their patience. Soybean farmers saw their 
crop prices drop during the same period. 
</P>
<P>
	A primary factor: 55 million bushels of soybeans and nearly 500  
million bushels of corn in storage in the state as of June 1, 
according to the Nebraska Agricultural Statistics Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The soybean carryover amounts to about a third of the 1998 crop.  
It's up more than 17 million bushels from the same date last year 
and well above anything on record books. 
</P>
<P>
	The stored corn equivalent is about 40 percent of the 1998 crop.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 19:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jamal Delays Meeting With Falcons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- The Jamal Anderson Watch turned into a  
frenzy Tuesday. Too bad the All-Pro running back wasn't around. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, refusing to report to the Atlanta Falcons training  
camp until he receives a new contract, pushed back his face-to-face 
meeting with coach Dan Reeves and general manager Harold Richardson 
until Wednesday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of reporters converged on sleepy Furman University,  
hoping to get a glimpse of the man who played a key role in the 
Falcons' Super Bowl season. But the player's California-based 
agent, Jim Sims, said he had trouble getting a flight to 
Greenville, so the meeting was delayed 24 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson and Sims remained in Atlanta. At training camp,  
everyone had to settle for Morten Andersen. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, I'm not Jamal Anderson,'' the Falcons' kicker joked on his  
way to lunch. 
</P>
<P>
	Sims, reached in Atlanta late Tuesday, said he would ask the  
Falcons to trade Anderson if a deal can't be reached Wednesday. The 
agent first raised the trade possibility a couple of weeks ago when 
his client refused to report to training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I we don't get it done, I think from that point on we'll  
really have to push the trade option,'' Sims said. ``He's not 
retiring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As he did several weeks ago, Reeves flatly rejected the idea of  
trading Anderson. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll meet with them and he won't get traded,'' the coach  
vowed. 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves seemed perturbed by all the attention devoted to his star  
running back, who is refusing to play out the final year of his 
current contract for $2.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson wants a long-term deal that's in line with the NFL's  
other top runners after rushing for a franchise-record 1,846 yards 
and setting a league mark with 410 carries. 
</P>
<P>
	``They just want more publicity and y'all are doing a great job  
of giving it to them,'' Reeves groused to reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves, who has final say on contract matters, continued to draw  
a line in the sand at Anderson's demands. He said the running back 
should accept the Falcons' offer or live up to his contract and 
become a free agent at the end of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see anything being different just because we're  
meeting face to face ... instead of talking on the phone,'' Reeves 
said. ``We've stated our stance and that's not going to change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did concede a willingness to shift some money to earlier  
years in the contract. While the two sides have basically agreed on 
a new five-year deal worth $28 million to $30 million, Anderson is 
reportedly seeking around $13 million in the first three years and 
the Falcons have offered $11 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the Falcons have offered a $7 million signing bonus, while  
Anderson is seeking at least $7.5 million after initially asking 
for $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, who lives in Salt Lake City, arrived in Atlanta early  
Monday morning, putting him within a 2 1/2-hour drive of Greenville. 
He spent Tuesday meeting with Sims, going over figures and plotting 
strategy for the meeting with Reeves and Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	If a deal is reached Wednesday, Sims said his client could take  
part in practice that afternoon or, at the latest, Thursday 
morning. The Falcons play their first exhibition game Friday night 
against Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves seemed somewhat heartened that Anderson was at least  
making the effort to be at training camp, even if didn't plan on 
being in uniform right away. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's better than nothing,'' Reeves said. ``We'll sit down  
and talk and see what happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sims sparked the first face-to-face talks since training camp  
began on June 29 when he cut short a European vacation and sent a 
new proposal to Richardson on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There can't be a bigger commitment than going to training camp  
ready to go to work,'' Sims said. ``Hopefully, we'll get it done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, facing fines of $65,000 for skipping 13 workouts as of  
Tuesday, has been unwilling to take the field without a new 
contract since the Falcons can still retain his rights next season 
by designating him a franchise player. 
</P>
<P>
	Even in that situation, he would be assured of making at least  
the average salary of the top five players at his position. 
</P>
<P>
	While Anderson can't force the Falcons to trade him, Sims said  
it would be foolish to keep the player if negotiations reach a 
point where he no longer wants to play for the NFC champions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's only vindictive for a team not to go forward and try to  
entertain the trade option,'' Sims said, pointing out that the 
Falcons would be stuck with a $3.6 million salary cap cost whether 
Anderson plays or not. ``Then where we are going to be next year? 
Starting off at square one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Falcons went through another day of practice on a  
scorching 95-degree day, their thoughts far away from Anderson's 
contract impasse. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't think about Jamal until you asked me,'' linebacker  
Jessie Tuggle told a reporter. ``That's the truth. I want him out 
here as quick as possible, but I'll promise you I'm not losing any 
sleep over him.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
