<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Young Finally Back for 49ers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) -- The orders to Bryant Young were clear:  
Stay out of all team drills at the San Francisco 49ers' training 
camp. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, Tuesday was Young's first day back on the field since  
a frightening injury 8 1/2 months ago. San Francisco's star defensive 
tackle broke both bones in his lower right leg in a collision with 
teammate Ken Norton Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	``All he did was the individual work early in practice. We kept  
him out of everything else, but he looked good to me,'' 49ers coach 
Steve Mariucci said. ``He is so darn happy to be back in a 49ers 
helmet, and the whole team obviously is glad he's back. 
</P>
<P>
	``In fact, when we went to the two-minute drill, he ran into the  
defensive huddle, and I went, `What is he doing? because we told 
him he wasn't going to get involved. But he was just in there, 
breaking them down. He just wanted to get in there and be with his 
guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was the biggest step yet in the comeback of Young, who was  
activated from the physically-unable-to-perform list. The move 
allowed him to rejoin his teammates on the practice field after 
months of watching from afar as he conducted his rehabilitation 
workouts under the supervision of physical development coordinator 
Jerry Attaway. 
</P>
<P>
	Young remains on course for a return in San Francisco's  
regular-season opener at Jacksonville on Sept. 12 but is not 
expected to play in any exhibition games. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm letting them know how I feel and at the same time, they're  
being very cautious about letting me do too much too soon,'' Young 
said. ``This is where I am right now. But I was excited, anxious to 
get out there because this is the day I've been waiting for. It was 
what I thought about throughout my rehabilitation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teammates and coaches alike took time to welcome Young back and  
congratulate him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still have a lot of sharpening up to do,'' Young said. ``I'm  
going to use practice to my advantage to get ready for the 
season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young underwent three operations in the aftermath of the injury,  
which occurred last Nov. 30. Norton's helmet struck Young's leg as 
he braced to tackle Giants quarterback Kent Graham. 
</P>
<P>
	It took some two months for Young to again walk unassisted.  
</P>
<P>
	``But once I started walking again, the healing process took  
off,'' he said. ``I knew in my mind and my heart I would come 
back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young will be playing with a metal rod in his leg. It was  
inserted in the tibia, the weight-bearing bone, to stabilize 
Young's leg and promote healing. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Cincinnati tackle Tim Krumrie, who broke his leg playing  
against the 49ers in the January 1989 Super Bowl, and former San 
Francisco center-guard Jesse Sapolu, who also had a leg fracture 
early in his career, both came back to play with metal rods in 
their legs. 
</P>
<P>
	Mariucci said Young will be brought along gradually. He's  
expected to begin contact drills early next week but he'll be held 
out of the team's four exhibitions. The 49ers followed a similar 
regimen last year when Jerry Rice, coming off two serious knee 
injuries, prepared for the season without playing in any 
exhibitions. 
</P>
<P>
	Young said he's confident he'll be able to play at the same  
level as before the injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, I'm pretty close to 100 percent,'' Young said. ``I  
have no pain in my leg where I broke both bones. The one thing that 
slowed me down a bit was my knee, but we worked through that. I 
think I'm pretty much the same as before. I'm very thankful. I have 
a lot to be thankful for.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
