<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schoolmate Urges Trial As Adult </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The teen-ager who was the most seriously  
injured during a shooting rampage at Heritage High School testified 
today that she believes defendant T.J. Solomon should be tried as 
an adult. 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon should not be kept in the juvenile court system  
``because if he gets off as a juvenile, he could be out in a few 
months, and he doesn't need to be out,'' said 15-year-old Stephanie 
Laster. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephanie was one of six students shot May 20 at the school in  
Conyers, a suburb 20 miles east of Atlanta. She underwent two 
operations and was hospitalized for 12 days. Bullet fragments 
remain lodged in her hip and doctors aren't sure whether her 
ovaries have been damaged, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She was the final prosecution witness at a hearing to determine  
whether 15-year-old Solomon should be tried in Juvenile Court or 
Superior Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys were to present their case later today.  
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, a state investigator read a note found under  
Solomon's bed that referred to the Trench Coat Mafia, a group 
linked to the April 20 slayings at Columbine High School in 
Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Nicholson, an agent with the Georgia Bureau of  
Investigation, read the note, in which Solomon apparently wrote 
that he had been planning his attack for years. 
</P>
<P>
	``One big question I leave behind for you to find is why,'' the  
note said. ``But for the sake of my brothers and sisters related to 
the Trench Coat Mafia, those answers will have to remain out of the 
public eye.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Littleton, Colo., Dylan Klebold, 17, and Eric Harris, 18,  
killed 13 people and then themselves at Columbine High on April 20. 
They were members of the Trench Coat Mafia, a group of students who 
wore black coats and considered themselves campus outcasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholas said the note distanced its author from the Columbine  
massacre: ``This has nothing to do with Hitler,'' it said, ``and it 
is not because I was picked on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the back of the note, Nicholson said, Solomon wrote: ``I am  
laughing at the victims who are getting down on their knees 
screaming, `Please, dear God, please don't let this crooked ... 
(obscenity deleted) murder me.''' 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, immediately after the Heritage High shootings the  
gunman dropped to his knees and pointed a gun at his mouth. A short 
time later, after pointing his gun at an assistant principal, he 
surrendered with a tearful, ``Oh, my God, I'm so scared!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon faces 21 charges, including aggravated assault and  
weapons violations, in the rampage at the Heritage High commons 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	He could be sentenced to five years in detention if Judge  
William Schneider decides to keep the case in juvenile court. If 
convicted in Superior Court, Solomon could face 351 years in 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers spent much of Monday's session discussing Solomon's  
mental state. His attorney hoped to convince Schneider that the 
youth should be sent to a psychiatric hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson said the note also referred to bombs planted at  
Heritage High, although no bombs were found, and was accompanied by 
sheets of bomb-making instructions. 
</P>
<P>
	Classmate Teeunia Stroud testified that Solomon brought the  
instructions to school after the Columbine rampage, but she said 
she thought he was joking. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said that the kids at Columbine were aiming at certain  
people, and that slowed them down,'' said Miss Stroud, who ate 
lunch with Solomon. ``He said that if he ever shot up Heritage 
High, he would shoot everybody and not aim.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
