<HEADLINE> Title Fight Moved to Miami </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The Aug. 21 WBC super-lightweight title fight  
between Kostya Tszyu and Miguel Angel Gonzalez has been moved to 
South Florida after negotiations stalled in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	The bout, which will be telecast by Showtime Network, now will  
be held at Miccosukee Indian Gaming, just outside Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Miccosukees are always interested in doing a big fight,''  
said Dan Goosen, who is co-promoting the bout with Don King. ``And 
this is a big fight, wherever you put it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tszyu, born in Russia and now living in Australia, and Gonzalez  
will fight for a championship which has stood vacant for two years. 
Oscar de la Hoya won the belt by beating Gonzalez in January 1997, 
then moved up to the welterweight division without a title defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Tszyu (22-1-1, 18 knockouts) and Gonzalez (43-1-1, 33 KOs) had  
been scheduled to meet for the title three times previously, but 
each bout was canceled because of injuries or legal problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The Miccosukees became a late entrant as host when Goosen  
couldn't complete a deal to stage the bout at the Las Vegas Hilton. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dan talked to me and said the fight was available,'' said  
Miccosukee executive director Don Hazelton, who secured the 
approval of tribal chairman Billy Cypress. ``We've proven we can 
have big events. I wouldn't say we were lucky. Luck is when 
opportunity meets preparedness.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
