<HEADLINE> Salon.com Sees Surge in Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Online publisher Salon.com is seeing a  
surge in visitors and revenue as well as swelling losses, according 
to its first earnings report. The company went public in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The edgy cultural Web site reported 1.3 million visitors in the  
quarter ended June 30, compared with 567,000 visitors the year 
before. To get these new visitors, Salon.com spent big, incurring a 
loss of $4.6 million, compared to $1.4 million in second-quarter 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue increased from $408,000 to just over $1 million this  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Salon's stock closed Monday at $8.75 per share, well below its  
initial price of $10.50, and a high of $15.12. Salon's price 
decline follows a widespread Internet stock slump over the past 
several months. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a land grab out there,'' said Salon Chief Executive  
Officer Michael O'Donnell, attributing his company's losses to 
staff buildup and advertising. ``You have to spend to build a brand 
... It's what we have to do to reach critical mass.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
