<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 23:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants' Rookie Runner in Spotlight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- All halfback Sean Bennett wanted from the  
New York Giants was a chance. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the fourth-round draft pick out of Northwestern via a  
defunct program at Evansville is now the starter heading into 
Friday night's exhibition opener against Minnesota, after a run of 
injuries at the position. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest injury came late in Tuesday's practice at the  
University of Albany when Joe Montgomery, the second-round draft 
pick out of Ohio State, reinjured his right hamstring. 
</P>
<P>
	That put him on the shelf with starter Gary Brown (buttocks  
surgery), LeShon Johnson (thumb surgery) and free agent Raymond 
Priester (foot). 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, a 1,063-yard rusher who was injured in a motorcycle  
accident in June, and Johnson, who tore a ligament in his right 
thumb on Monday, are hoping to return next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, we're thin,'' coach Jim Fassel said of his halfback  
situation. ``The good news is we haven't lost anyone seriously. All 
these guys are coming back. The bad news is all these guys are 
losing practice time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Bennett, the injuries have turned into the chance of a  
lifetime. Fassel said it would not be surprising if he got as many 
as 20 carries on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	That's an unbelievable opportunity for a back who was somewhat  
of a sleeper in the draft. He set seven school records at 
Evansville, rushing for 2,856 yards, including 1,667 in his junior 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	After the school dropped its football program, Bennett  
transferred to Northwestern, where he got lost. The 6-foot-1, 
230-pound Bennett only carried 32 times in 12 games for 160 yards, 
playing mostly as a fullback. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a long road,'' Bennett said Tuesday between  
practices. ``I wasn't sure if I was going to be able to play. Now 
it's a great chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not only is Bennett going to carry the load at halfback, the  
Giants also plan to use him on the kickoff coverage and return 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Montgomery's injury might change those plans, and it might also  
force Fassel to take Tiki Barber, a starter early last year, out of 
his intended third-down role this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll get a few more carries, we'll work him in there,''  
Fassel said of Barber. ``That's all part of game planning. I've 
gone into a game with only four backs before, not in the preseason 
though.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Bennett and Barber, the Giants also have fullbacks  
Charles Way and Greg Comella. They could be featured in a one-back 
offense that uses two tight ends. 
</P>
<P>
	A north-south runner who has the quickness to get outside and  
the size to go inside, Bennett still will get the bulk of the work. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got here thinking I was going to be last on the depth chart  
and now with all the injuries, I've gotten a lot more reps than I 
otherwise would have had,'' he said. ``You can only learn so much 
from watching everyone else. Right now, I am reading the holes 
well, but I've still got a lot to learn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, who had a painful hematoma drained from his buttocks last  
weeks, said he is feeling better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm getting anxious,'' said Brown, who has yet to practice.  
``The doctors say let it heal up and don't rush it. If I rush it, 
the fluid is going to go right back in there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not known how long Johnson or Montgomery will be sidelined.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, who missed last season because of cancer, had surgery  
on his right thumb Tuesday, and a bone and ligament were pinned 
back in place. Fassel hopes to have Johnson back at practice Monday 
if there isn't too much pain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
