<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 06:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aluminum Merger May Be in the Works </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- Switzerland's biggest aluminum  
company, Alusuisse-Lonza, is in merger talks with two competitors 
that could result in creation of the world's largest aluminum 
concern. 
</P>
<P>
	Alusuisse-Lonza, also known as Algroup, said today it was in  
``advanced discussions'' with Alcan Aluminium of Montreal, Canada, 
and the French company Pechiney. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's No. 1 company is Alcoa Inc., headquartered in  
Pittsburgh, which had sales of $15.3 billion in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement from Algroup said it was not certain the talks  
would result in an agreement, and officials declined to give 
further information. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate statement, Pechiney confirmed it was in talks with  
the other two companies over ``a possible merger of their 
operations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in Algroup were up 4.6 percent in early trading on the  
Zurich stock exchange. Pechiney shares rose 2.5 percent on the 
Paris Bourse. 
</P>
<P>
	Last November, Algroup announced it was discussing a possible  
merger with the German industrial concern Viag. The talks came to 
an acrimonious end in March following a disagreement over a share 
swap arrangement. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada's Alcan is the world's second-largest producer of  
aluminum. It recorded sales of $7.8 billion last year. Pechiney, 
based in Paris, is the world's No. 4, with 1998 sales of $10.9 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Algroup, which nearly went broke in the 1980s after a series of  
disastrous forays into the United States, recorded sales of $6.4 
billion in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	If the merger goes through, the three companies would have a  
combined workforce of more than 100,000 and would overtake the U.S. 
aluminum giant Alcoa. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company also would have a large packaging business.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
