<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hargrove To Coach Portland WNBA Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Linda Hargrove, whose first job in women's  
professional basketball was cut short when the American Basketball 
League folded, will get a second chance as coach of Portland's WNBA 
franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove will be introduced as coach by Portland Trail Blazers  
president and general manager Bob Whitsitt at a news conference 
Tuesday, The Associated Press has learned. 
</P>
<P>
	The Trail Blazers, who own Portland's as-yet-unnamed WNBA  
franchise, would not confirm or deny Hargrove's hiring, as per club 
policy. A telephone call to Hargrove's home in Wichita, Kan., was 
not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	But a source who asked not to be identified said Hargrove had  
taken the job. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12-team WNBA, currently in its third season, announced in  
June it was expanding to 16 teams for the 2000 season. Other cities 
awarded franchises were Seattle, Indianapolis and Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove took over as coach of the Colorado Xplosion before the  
1998 ABL season. The team went 5-8 before the financially 
struggling league shut down Dec. 21, one-third of the way through 
its third season. Thirty-seven players from the league's nine teams 
were spread out to the WNBA. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove had replaced Sheryl Estes, who resigned to return to  
college coaching. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove was 429-248 as a college coach between 1972 and 1998.  
Her teams at Wichita State went 113-136 in nine seasons, and she 
was named Missouri Valley Conference coach of the year in 1993. In 
17 seasons at Cowley Community College in Arkansas City, Kan., she 
went 316-112 with four NCAA Tournament appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	She was an assistant for the 1992 U.S. women's national team  
that won the bronze medal at the Olympics in Barcelona, Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	She also had a 305-114-8 record as volleyball coach at Cowley,  
and her husband Ed was the softball coach for 14 years at the 
southeastern Kansas school. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers reportedly interviewed four people for the WNBA  
coaching job, including former Portland Power coach Linn Dunn and 
former Boston Celtics coach K.C. Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunn appeared to be a strong candidate, but she accepted the  
same position with the Seattle team on July 22. She was named ABL 
coach of the year in 1998 after leading the Power to a 27-17 
record, the best in the Western Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Like the other three expansion teams, Portland must sell 5,500  
season tickets by Oct. 15. So far, the Blazers have sold about 
1,650 tickets, a team official said Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
