<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Catfish Hunter Suffers Head Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Baseball Hall of Famer Jim ``Catfish''  
Hunter is unconscious and in critical condition in a 
neuro-intensive care unit after falling and hitting his head, a 
hospital spokesman said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 53-year-old Hunter fell Sunday while negotiating stairs at  
his home in Hertford, said Doug Boyd, a spokesman for Pitt County 
Memorial Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter was taken to a hospital in Edenton and transferred early  
Monday to Pitt, a hospital that serves the East Carolina University 
medical school. 
</P>
<P>
	Boyd said Hunter was awake Monday, but was unconscious Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Hunter's family has requested no further information be  
released, Boyd said. 
</P>
<P>
	The former major league pitcher was diagnosed in September with  
amyothropic lateral sclerosis, or ALS, a neurological disease that 
interferes with the signals the brain sends to the muscles. Over 
time, the muscles degenerate. The cause is unknown, and there's no 
cure. 
</P>
<P>
	ALS also is known as Lou Gehrig's disease.  
</P>
<P>
	Hunter pitched for 15 years, winning 224 games, including a  
perfect game. He received five World Series rings while playing for 
the Kansas City and Oakland Athletics and the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Boyd said Hunter hadn't undergone surgery.  
</P>
<P>
	``The specialists up there are trying to support him as best  
they can,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, residents of Hunter's hometown turned out for a ceremony  
to honor him and kick off a foundation to aid people who suffer 
from the disease. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
