<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Witness: Slain Soldier Was Taunted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT CAMPBELL, Ky. (AP) -- A platoon leader who served with a  
soldier beaten to death in an Army barracks testified today that 
rumors that the soldier was homosexual made him a frequent target 
of name-callers in his unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Sgt. Eric Dubielak testified that he knew Pfc. Barry Winchell as  
a gunner in his platoon and was aware of the rumors about his 
sexuality. Dubielak said the rumors started late last year and that 
soldiers in Winchell's own unit started calling him derogatory 
names almost daily. 
</P>
<P>
	And Dubielak and another soldier who testified today, Sgt.  
Michael Kleifgen, both said Winchell, 21, told them that he was not 
a homosexual. 
</P>
<P>
	The testimony at a hearing to determine whether there is enough  
evidence to send the case against Pvt. Calvin Glover to a general 
court-martial. 
</P>
<P>
	Glover, 18, was charged with premeditated murder in July's  
killing of Winchell in the hallway of Winchell's barracks at Fort 
Campbell. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, an Army private testified that Glover, while in  
custody, had admitted beating Winchell to death with a baseball 
bat. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfc. Ryan Futch, who had guarded Glover in custody, testified  
that Glover told him he had hit Winchell several times with the 
bat. Futch also said he overheard Glover make disparaging remarks 
about blacks and gays to another prisoner. 
</P>
<P>
	Several soldiers have said they believed the killing was a hate  
crime. 
</P>
<P>
	The Army has declined to comment on Winchell's sexuality. NBC  
reported Monday night that Winchell's mother and stepfather said if 
Winchell was gay, they were unaware of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is, he was murdered, and he was on an Army base,  
where we thought he was safe,'' said Pat Kutteles, his mother. 
</P>
<P>
	Winchell and Glover served in the 502nd Infantry Regiment's 2nd  
Battalion at the post. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Warrant Officer Alfred Brown testified that Winchell  
suffered massive head injuries when he was beaten with a blunt 
object after a party outside the barracks on July 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfc. Arthur Hoffman, a member of Winchell's company and a friend  
of the victim, described Glover as someone with an apparent 
drinking problem who often tried to pick fights. Hoffman said that 
on July 3, Winchell had gotten the better of Glover during a fight. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
