<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Visits New York City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton is winding up her  
monthlong series of ``listening tour'' events right on her likely 
rival's home turf. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady, who said the tour would help her decide whether  
to run for the U.S. Senate from New York in 2000 -- probably against 
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani -- was meeting potential voters today at a 
union building in Queens to discuss balancing work and family. Then 
she's going on vacation with her family. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, she visited a Brooklyn church, where the discussion  
centered on crumbling, overcrowded and violent schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your candidacy is a great opportunity to re-vision  
education,'' said the Rev. Emma Jordan-Simpson of Concord Baptist. 
``We'd like to spend time creating after-school programs and not 
chasing money to fund those programs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speakers welcomed Mrs. Clinton as ``our senator'' and  
``senator-to-be.'' She, in turn, brought greetings from Eleanor 
Roosevelt, who she said had also visited the Brooklyn neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	``As some of you know, I talk to her from time to time and she  
asked me to say hello,'' she joked, referring reports she had 
participated in seances with the former first lady. 
</P>
<P>
	On her first ``listening tour'' visit to the city, Mrs. Clinton  
started by doing the talking. 
</P>
<P>
	She said a $792 billion Republican tax-cut plan would only  
further jeopardize education programs affecting New York's public 
schoolchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	``The city alone could lose as many as 4,000 desperately needed  
teachers,'' she said. In schools such as Brooklyn's Midwood High 
School, built for about 3,000 students but serving about 4,100, she 
said a tax cut of that size would be ``an irresponsible, damaging 
plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 90-minute discussion focused almost entirely on education  
problems, especially those linked to crime and lack of funds to 
sustain after-school programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I look deep into the reservoir of your eyes, I feel you  
can make a difference,'' said Adelaide Sanford, an educator in the 
Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood, the latest stop in the first 
lady's summer-long ``listening tour'' of the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Engineer Ernest Greene, a parent and lifelong resident of the  
area, said basic skills are often badly taught in crumbling schools 
with problems like malfunctioning heating, plumbing and 
``nonexistent air-conditioning systems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton also criticized congressional Republicans who  
recently defeated gun-control legislation that she said could help 
diminish violence among youth. She claimed 13 young people are 
killed by firearms in America every day. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood is heavily minority and  
Democratic, an area likely to support her likely candidacy against 
the city's Republican mayor, Giuliani. Neither Mrs. Clinton nor 
Giuliani have formally said they're running. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady, a likely Democratic candidate in 2000 for the  
seat of retiring U.S. Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, started the 
invitation-only ``listening'' events in July. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
