<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ABA Head Decries Lack of Minorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Not enough members of racial and ethnic  
minorities are lawyers, the new president of the American Bar 
Association said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our society is increasingly racially and ethnically diverse,  
but our profession is not,'' William G. Paul of Oklahoma City said 
as he assumed leadership of the nation's largest lawyers' group. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty percent of Americans are members of racial or ethnic  
minorities, but the nation's lawyers are 92 percent white, Paul 
said. The legal profession's ethnic mix is expected to fall further 
behind in the next 50 years if current trends continue, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	``The legal profession must reflect the general society,''  
because it ``is the connecting link between the rule of law and the 
people,'' Paul said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even among lawyers, there is disagreement about fairness:  
overwhelmingly, black lawyers say the system is not fair, while 
white lawyers say that, for the most part, it is,'' Paul said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the ABA will work to encourage more members of minority  
groups to become lawyers and to spur the hiring of more minority 
people as law clerks to federal and state judges. Clerking for a 
judge can be an important career steppingstone for a young 
attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	The bar association will create a scholarship fund to help more  
racial and ethnic minorities go to law school, Paul said. More than 
$300,000 has been pledged to the fund, which has a goal of raising 
$1 million during the first year. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul said he will organize a group of law school deans to  
examine diversity in law schools by looking at admission tests and 
schools' efforts to retain minority students who enroll. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, corporate lawyers and private attorneys will be asked to  
study efforts around the country that have successfully boosted 
diversity in the profession, Paul said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 14:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Expos' Ballpark Plans Move Forward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- Negotiations are progressing on a deal between the  
Montreal Expos and the Canadian government that would allow the 
team to buy land for a downtown stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the first time since negotiations began, we are really on  
the same wavelength,'' Gord McIvor, a spokesman for the government 
agency. Canada Lands Corp., said Tuesday. ``It's the first time we 
can say there's been real progress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montreal, last in the major leagues in attendance with a 9,556  
average going into Tuesday night's game, has said it may have to 
explore moving unless it gets a new ballpark to replace Olympic 
Stadium, built for the 1976 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the land wasn't revealed Tuesday but Montreal La  
Presse reported last week that Expos chairman Jacques Menard's 
group hoped to purchase an area a block south of the Molson Centre, 
home of the NHL's Canadiens, for $16 million-$18 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Menard told radio station CKAC he expects to get the go-ahead  
soon from commissioner Bud Selig for a new ownership group. Menard 
says he is close to raising $50 million in local investment and is 
close to finalizing a $75 million investment from Jeffrey Loria, a 
New York art dealer. 
</P>
<P>
	Any sale would have to be approved by at least three-quarters of  
NL owners and a majority of AL owners. 
</P>
<P>
	``We met with the people from major league baseball two weeks  
ago in New York and they seemed satisfied with our plans,'' said 
Menard, adding that 19 versions of the plan were submitted before 
baseball officials agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	Menard heads a group of dissident members of the team's  
ownership consortium that resisted pressure to sell and move the 
31-year-old franchise, which might be pursued by groups in northern 
Virginia and Charlotte, N.C. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 10:23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Animation Business Moves Eastward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	POWELL, Ohio (AP) -- Peeking into Hugo Giraud's office cubicle, a  
visitor might think he's getting ready to attend a movie, not help 
make one. 
</P>
<P>
	Perched on a shelf are ``Star Wars'' and ``Austin Powers''  
action figures. Giraud, 26, wears a casual shirt, denim shorts, 
baseball cap and five o'clock shadow. 
</P>
<P>
	Giraud is one of the 25 employees of Character Builders, an  
independent animation studio that offers filmmakers and advertisers 
direction, production, character design and things much more 
technical. 
</P>
<P>
	Character Builders worked on the 1996 Warner Bros. movie ``Space  
Jam'' and Nickelodeon's popular animated cable TV series ``Ren and 
Stimpy.'' But while most of its clients are in Hollywood, the 
company's office sits on a wooded hillside in this small community 
just north of Columbus. The Ohio capital has become a training 
ground for film industry computer graphics innovators. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still amazing to us that we're in the Midwestern U.S.,''  
said co-founder and executive vice president Martin Fuller. ``But 
making a feature film has become so decentralized that we can play 
a significant role and still have the quality of life that having 
our families in Ohio gives us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Faxes, modems, teleconferencing and overnight delivery services  
are as important to the company as paper and pencils. 
</P>
<P>
	Character Builders was founded in 1986 by Jim Kammerud, a former  
editorial cartoonist in Virginia; Jeff Smith, who has since left 
the company to develop the comic book ``Bone''; and Fuller, an Ohio 
State University film school graduate. 
</P>
<P>
	The university has a unique program that combines computer  
science and graphics with engineering and the arts, said Wayne 
Carlson, director of Ohio State's Advanced Center for Computing in 
the Arts and Design. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I watch a movie, I spend more time watching the credits  
than the movie to gloat over the names of former students,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	One of them is Doug Roble, who earned a doctorate in computer  
science from Ohio State in 1993 and is now a software engineer with 
Digital Domain of Los Angeles, a company partly owned by James 
Cameron, the Oscar-winning director of ``Titanic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roble, 36, won a technical Academy Award this year for a program  
that allows filmmakers to easily integrate computer graphics with 
live action. It was used in ``Apollo 13,'' ``Titanic'' and 
``Armageddon,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to come to L.A. to make movies, it's just a fact. But  
you don't have to start in L.A. to make movies,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Light, who holds bachelor's and master's degrees from Ohio  
State in fine arts and art in cinema, respectively, is a supervisor 
for George Lucas' Industrial Light &AMP; Magic, which did the computer 
effects for ``Star Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Light specializes in motion capture, a process by which a  
computer records the movement of a performer in a special suit, 
enabling the creation of computer generated characters. 
</P>
<P>
	``It allows us to fill in the background of big battle scenes  
and make it believable,'' said Light, who taught and did research 
at Ohio State before joining ILM. Fuller was one of his students. 
</P>
<P>
	At Character Builders, animators and producers are always  
working, since a full-length animated feature film takes about two 
to three years to produce, and there are deadlines along the way, 
executive producer and general manager Leslie Hough said. 
</P>
<P>
	First, Character Builders is given a script, then animators draw  
each scene, all of which must be cut to proper length before 
animation can begin. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a live action film, you would go out and shoot each scene  
from a bunch of different angles and then when it's done you go 
edit all the pieces together,'' Hough said. ``In animation, it's so 
expensive and lengthy and tedious to process that before you really 
start animating you have to know exactly every shot in your film.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Space Jam'' was about two years of work for 13 minutes of  
movie, said production manager Samantha Tishkosf, who oversees the 
artists. 
</P>
<P>
	Character Builders is also looking to develop its own characters  
and working with Nickelodeon on turning ``Bone'' into an animated 
film, Hough said. 
</P>
<P>
	That leaves little time for joking around. The office may be  
casual, but animators often work alone in their cubicles -- 
headphones plugged into their favorite music their only way to 
break the silence. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, they say they enjoy working for a company that gives them  
a chance to develop their creativity, individuality and 
imagination. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody here all has the same opinion: `I can't believe  
they're paying me to do this,''' said Andy Friz, 29, an artist who 
helps the animators. ``One of these days they're going to find out 
and make me do real work. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 17:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Will Probe Columbine Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- A state commission will review the massacre at  
Columbine High School to assess how authorities responded and make 
recommendations about improvements, Gov. Bill Owens announced 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, which will be financed with a $68,800 federal grant,  
will be formed after Jefferson County sheriff's deputies complete 
their investigation into the shooting attack that left 15 dead, 
including the two gunmen. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all must work together to ensure that a tragedy like that  
which occurred at Columbine must never happen again,'' Owens said 
in a statement. Emergency response crews, law enforcement agencies 
and SWAT teams received some criticism in the aftermath of the 
tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal is not to criticize or blame but to learn lessons  
across the board,'' said Troy Eid, the governor's chief counsel. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, he said, ``some law enforcement agencies were not  
able to communicate with other law enforcement or emergency 
responders because different radios are tuned to different 
frequencies. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the types of things the panel will look into is whether  
a new system that allows everyone to communicate on the same 
channel would have been helpful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new panel, to be composed of 12 experts on law enforcement,  
school safety and public education, will also review the emergency 
medical response and evacuation protocols and techniques used at 
Columbine. 
</P>
<P>
	A report will be released to the public.  
</P>
<P>
	Owens announced plans to create the commission as Jefferson  
County school officials paid tribute to Dave Sanders, the only 
teacher killed April 20 when seniors Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan 
Klebold opened fire and hurled bombs in the school. Twelve students 
were killed and 23 others injured. 
</P>
<P>
	As gunfire and explosions echoed through the cafeteria, Sanders  
raced through Columbine's hallways, herding students to safety. 
Shot twice in the chest, he bled to death in a classroom several 
hours later. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 08:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
