<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Space Station Illnesses Downplayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Stale air may have caused headaches,  
nausea and dry, itchy eyes for astronauts visiting NASA's new space 
station, but the doctor who was there downplayed the seriousness of 
the ailments. 
</P>
<P>
	``Actually, it was no big deal,'' Dr. Daniel Barry said. ``I  
don't think we had any more nausea on this flight than you would 
typically have on a flight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barry says the symptoms were so fleeting, and so benign, that  
neither he nor his six crewmates reported their illnesses until a 
couple of weeks after they returned to Earth -- to the dismay of 
NASA, which now may never be able to diagnose the problem. The 
space agency is changing guidelines for future crews. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry says it's impossible to know whether the crew was sickened  
by stagnant air or chemical fumes inside the international space 
station as some reports suggest, or whether it was simply prolonged 
space motion sickness. His own stuffy nose and headaches, for 
example, were no worse than what he experienced on a previous 
flight. 
</P>
<P>
	Any indication by NASA officials or others that the crew was  
very sick is ``way overblown,'' Barry told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry insists he would have intervened if someone was really  
sick. The astronauts were warned before their May 27 launch about 
possible atmosphere problems aboard the space station, and so Barry 
kept close watch over his crewmates. 
</P>
<P>
	When ill, the astronauts simply retreated to the docked space  
shuttle Discovery and relaxed or had lunch, Barry said. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA is taking the matter seriously. A team has been appointed  
to evaluate the air inside the space station and help prevent 
future visitors from becoming ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Astronauts are not due back at the space station until December.  
The first permanent crew doesn't move in until March. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation is especially difficult because none of the  
astronauts were wearing medical sensors and none of them took air 
samples when they became ill. As a result, NASA has to rely on 
anecdotal information, said Jim Van Laak, deputy manager of space 
station operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Space flight can be quite uncomfortable for some people'' even  
under the best of circumstances, Van Laak said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA refuses to elaborate on the illnesses or identify who got  
sick, citing medical privacy. But in a seven-page internal report 
obtained and published last month by an independent Web site called 
NASA Watch, the space agency listed the medical problems and 
possible causes. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S., Russian and Canadian crew spent less than 3 1/2 days inside  
the station at the end of May and beginning of June, making repairs 
and stocking its two rooms with supplies. The station had been 
sealed since the last shuttle visit six months earlier; the first 
crew reported no health problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the Russian module containing air purifiers and other  
life-support equipment had yet to arrive -- its much-delayed launch 
is off until November -- systems aboard Discovery were used to 
cleanse the station atmosphere. 
</P>
<P>
	Air in the station was routed to the shuttle and back again, and  
it's possible a duct could have been blocked, Van Laak said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the astronauts used handheld fans and limited their  
time in the Russian control module Zarya -- one astronaut used a 
timer to alert her when to leave -- carbon dioxide still may have 
built up. Unlike on Earth, exhaled carbon dioxide does not float 
away in space. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry said he could tell the air was stale when all seven  
gathered for pictures in the U.S.-built chamber, Unity. In 
retrospect, he wishes he would have taken air samples then. 
</P>
<P>
	The crew collected air samples only twice, just as they were  
supposed to: when they entered and left the station. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA is requesting more air samples on future flights,  
especially when astronauts feel sick. Managers also are asking 
crews to promptly report any illnesses, and are considering 
individual carbon-dioxide monitors -- a recommendation from Barry. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
