<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Will Lloyd's of London Modernize? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Lloyd's of London denied a report Tuesday that its  
chief executive is considering a radical modernization that would 
turn the insurance market, structured on mutual ownership, into a 
profit-making company. 
</P>
<P>
	The Daily Telegraph reported that Nick Prettejohn, who became  
chief executive of Lloyd's three months ago, is considering 
transforming it into a company within three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a step would mean the abandonment of Lloyd's traditional  
mutual structure, a step known as demutualization. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our objective is to create a market in which businesses can  
thrive,'' Lloyd's said in a statement. ``To achieve this, we are 
looking at all sorts of ways in which we can modernize the way the 
market does business. However, demutualization is not currently 
being discussed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Britain's best-known insurance market -- which started in a  
coffee house run by Edward Lloyd -- has been owned for some 300 
years by the Lloyd's Society, which is made up of 4,900 Names, 
mostly private individuals, who provide the money for underwriting 
insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	The Telegraph cited unidentified sources at Lloyd's as saying a  
modernizing faction in the market was pressuring Prettejohn and 
that transforming Lloyd's into a private firm was his preferred 
option. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we have here now is a collection of international  
businesses which are a national asset and I don't think they should 
continue to be tarred by an antique brush,'' Prettejohn was quoted 
as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a modernization plan would come on the heels of a similar  
move by the London Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The management board of Britain's largest stock market said July  
30 that it plans to end the exchange's 240-year status as a 
member-owned organization and transform it into a company 
controlled by shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Lloyd's acknowledged the pressure for such a move, even while  
denying some of the details in the report. 
</P>
<P>
	``A number of people within the Lloyd's membership have  
suggested demutualization as an option worth examining, given the 
demutualization of a number of exchanges including the London Stock 
Exchange,'' Lloyd's said. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper said Prettejohn will present a plan next month  
that would include ways to loosen a requirement making those 
seeking insurance go through a Lloyd's broker. This proposed change 
would give overseas customers cheaper and easier access to 
insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	A Lloyd's spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
such a change could be one of the first steps taken to modernize 
the market. 
</P>
<P>
	The government must approve any radical change at Lloyd's.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
