<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Portland WNBA Team Picks Hargrove </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Eight months after Linda Hargrove's trip  
to Portland was canceled -- along with her job, her team and 
everything else in the American Basketball League -- she arrived in 
the city for a fresh start. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove was introduced as coach and general manager of the  
Portland Trail Blazers' expansion WNBA franchise Tuesday, returning 
to professional women's basketball for the first time since the ABL 
folded last December. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want the fans of the WNBA Portland franchise to be as proud  
of our team as you all are of the Blazers,'' Hargrove said at a 
news conference, dressed in a business suit of Blazers red, black 
and white. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove, a college coach for 26 years in Kansas, took over the  
ABL's Colorado Xplosion for the 1998 season. The team started 5-8, 
but had won three of four heading into Christmas break. Hargrove 
was looking forward to a nationally televised game against the 
Portland Power on Dec. 27. But on Dec. 22, the league unexpectedly 
announced it was filing for bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was one of the most devastating things I've ever  
experienced,'' she said Tuesday. ``I'm sure a lot of people in 
Portland can relate to that. There's always going to be an ABL 
hurt. There's players who put their heart and soul into that 
league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 12-team WNBA, now in its third season, took in 37 players  
from the ABL. The WNBA, backed by the marketing muscle of the NBA, 
will expand to 16 teams for 2000. The other new teams will be 
Miami, Indianapolis and Seattle. None of the teams has a name or 
logo yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Portland and Seattle have hired front office personnel.  
Seattle chose former Power coach Lin Dunn as its coach and general 
manager. 
</P>
<P>
	It's still not decided how many players the existing WNBA teams  
will be able to protect for next year's draft, or where the 
expansion teams will be placed in the draft order. 
</P>
<P>
	After the ABL fizzled, Hargrove stayed in Denver for two months,  
then returned to her home in Wichita, Kan., to take a job with the 
city. But she stayed involved with women's pro basketball, 
evaluating talent for the WNBA's Orlando Miracle and helping the 
team with the draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove, who signed a three-year contract with Portland, said  
she was contacted by the other expansion teams. She praised 
Oregon's tradition of support for women's basketball, from high 
school through the Power's short history. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Northwest is a really exciting place to be if you're a  
women's basketball fan,'' she said. ``I've long believed that a 
competitive spirit is not gender-specific, and I think that by 
bringing this franchise to Portland, young women will grow up with 
the understanding that it's OK to be athletic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove, 49, brought the Wichita State program back to life,  
leading the Shockers to six straight Missouri Valley Conference 
postseason appearances in nine seasons. In 17 seasons at Cowley 
Community College in Arkansas City, Kan., her teams went 316-112. 
</P>
<P>
	Blazers president and general manager Bob Whitsitt said Hargrove  
had the passion and work ethic he was looking for. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a 12-month-a-year job for her,'' he said. ``This is  
not four months and `I'll see you next March.' '' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
