<HEADLINE> Rail Killing Suspect Indicted in Ky. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Suspected railroad killer Angel Maturino  
Resendiz has been indicted in the 1997 killing of a University of 
Kentucky student, and he now faces charges in seven slayings. 
</P>
<P>
	Fayette County prosecutors said they will seek the death penalty  
for Resendiz, who was indicted Monday by a grand jury in the 
slaying of Christopher Maier, 21, on railroad tracks near the 
Kentucky campus. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was charged with the rape and beating of Maier's  
girlfriend. The couple were walking back to campus from a party. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities have linked the rail-riding Mexican drifter, who  
went by the alias Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, to a total of nine 
slayings. He is now charged with seven, including two in Illinois 
and four in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	His first trial is scheduled for Feb. 14 in the slaying of a  
Houston-area doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	Resendiz surrendered to authorities last month, ending a  
nationwide manhunt, after his sister brokered an arrangement with 
the Texas Rangers. 
  	   	
