<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 13:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer Students Are Expelled for Guns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For all the attention given recent school  
shootings, fewer guns are being taken onto schoolgrounds, federal 
officials said Tuesday, pointing to new figures showing a decline 
in the number of students expelled for having firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	``America's schools should be safe havens for all children. By  
and large we have done a good job of reaching that standard,'' 
Education Secretary Richard Riley said. ``I believe that all of us 
-- parents, educators, students, all citizens -- can look to this new 
school year with hope, not with fear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report came even as a new shooting incident occurred, with  
three young boys among the wounded at a summer camp at a Jewish 
community center in California. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of students kicked out of school for bringing weapons  
dropped by nearly a third during the 1997-98 school year -- the year 
before the Columbine rampage in Colorado, Riley's department said. 
Fifty states, the District of Columbia and five U.S. territories 
reported that 3,930 students were expelled for firearms violations 
that year, down from 5,724 weapons-related expulsions in 1996-97. 
There are about 52 million students in U.S. public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Education Department officials said the expulsion numbers do not  
provide a complete assessment of the problem of students bringing 
guns to school. Many states' numbers for 1996-97 included 
expulsions of all students caught with weapons, not just those 
kicked out for having firearms. And the department asked 
California, Alabama and Tennessee to recheck their data after 
members of Congress raised concerns that not all districts were 
accurately reporting gun incidents. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Bill Modzeleski, director of the department's Safe and  
Drug-Free Schools Program, said officials are confident there 
really is a decline in school gun incidents because other surveys 
and reports have similar findings. 
</P>
<P>
	``The trend line is, fewer guns are going into schools,''  
Modzeleski said. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas schools expelled 424 students and California schools  
kicked out 382 students for gun violations in the 1997-98 school 
year. Wyoming reported no gun-related expulsions. 
</P>
<P>
	South Dakota reported the highest rate of gun incidents: 49  
students were expelled, or about three of every 10,000 students. 
Oregon had the second-highest rate, expelling 135 students, or 
about two of every 10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Oregon was the site of one of that school year's deadliest  
school shootings, in which 16-year-old Kip Kinkel was charged with 
killing two fellow students at Thurston High School in Springfield. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado, site of the April 20 shootings at Columbine, reported  
expelling 76 students for gun violations in 1997-98, a rate of 
about one per 10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Many schools are not doing enough to respond to the threat of  
violence, said school security officials who joined Riley at a news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of school districts that do not know what  
they're doing with regard to security,'' said Jack Martin, chief of 
police for Indianapolis public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	But no reasonable security measures could be sure of preventing  
another outbreak like the shootings at Columbine, in which two 
students killed a dozen classmates and a teacher before committing 
suicide, the security officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's an event that's beyond predictability,'' said Edward  
Ray, director of security for Denver's public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile Tuesday, an independent education group released a  
survey suggesting fewer teens feel safe in school. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``State of Our Nation's Youth'' survey by the Horatio Alger  
Association found just one-third of public school students said 
they always feel safe in school, down from 40 percent in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings were based on mailed questionnaires returned by  
more than 1,000 teen-agers. The surveys were mailed April 22, two 
days after the Columbine shootings, and Riley and other officials 
said the findings conflicted with other recent student surveys and 
may have been skewed by the timing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
