<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Lauds Bicyclist Armstrong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton offered the nation's  
congratulations Tuesday to Lance Armstrong, who recovered from 
cancer to win the grueling Tour de France, the world's most 
prestigious bicycle race. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong posed for photographs in the Oval Office with the  
president, then appeared with Vice President Al Gore in the 
Roosevelt Room in a ceremony to honor cancer survivors and call 
attention to successes of cancer research. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore hailed the cyclist as an inspiration to cancer survivors  
everywhere and asked the Office of Personnel Management to explore 
offering federal workers time off for cancer screening. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said the idea was based on a program offered to Boston city  
workers under which they can take a half-day paid leave each year 
to get checked out for cancer. ``Prevention and early attention can 
save lives,'' the vice president said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Armstrong dashed off autographs for a dozen or so  
bicycle messengers who clustered around the new bicycle hero as he 
arrived for a speech at the National Press Club. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking questions in the club's crowded auditorium, Armstrong  
told an enthusiastic audience the hardest day physically on the 
tour was its first leg over the steep grades and sizzling heat of 
the Pyrenees Mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	Mentally, he said, the toughest 24 hours came when he was  
accused -- falsely, he insists -- of taking drugs to enhance his 
strength and endurance after his cancer battle. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong said that after a lifetime of good health -- ``not even  
a broken bone'' -- and years of successful competition, his cancer 
became a supreme endurance test. His testicular cancer invaded his 
bones and brain and was fought with aggressive chemotherapy and 
three operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The attitude of a cancer survivor like himself, he said, is,  
``You've been to hell and back, and you want a vacation for the 
rest of your life. But nobody gives you that. You have to go on 
because you are living.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong said for him ``going on'' means continuing the work of  
building and expanding the Lance Armstrong Foundation, which he 
founded to promote cancer research and to help cancer victims and 
survivors. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he intends to compete in the Tour de France through 2001  
and will keep in training until then. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you show up at the Tour de France overweight or out of  
shape,'' he said, ``it doesn't make any difference (what kind of 
bike) you're riding -- you won't win.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
