<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Utah's Layden To Be GM of Knicks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Scott Layden, who masterminded Utah Jazz  
personnel moves for 11 seasons, accepted a job Tuesday with the New 
York Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	The move is a homecoming for Layden, who was born in New York,  
and transports him from the NBA's smallest market to its largest. 
</P>
<P>
	``It comes as a really tough decision to move on, but it just  
feels like the right thing to do,'' Layden, 41, said. ``I need to 
move on and grow up a little bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was clear as soon as Jazz owner Larry Miller sat down, his  
eyes red and welling with tears before a word was spoken, that 
Layden wasn't staying. 
</P>
<P>
	``From a personal, selfish standpoint and from a standpoint of  
wearing my hat as owner of the Jazz, I wish we weren't here today 
talking about this,'' Miller sniffled. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden declined to discuss the Knicks position, saying details  
would come during a news conference Wednesday in New York. He 
likely will be introduced as the successor of fired general manager 
Ernie Grunfeld. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden met last weekend with Madison Square Garden president  
Dave Checketts about the Knicks' general manager's job, which has 
been vacant since Grunfeld was reassigned in April. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Layden met with Miller and other Jazz officials, who  
were unable to convince him to stay. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the one hand, we hate more than I can express to see him  
go,'' Miller said. ``On the other hand, I wish him well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Layden said the deciding factor was his family's enthusiasm for  
living in New York. He and his wife, Marsha, are supporters of the 
arts and Layden lived in New York through his teen-age years. 
</P>
<P>
	The boyish-faced Layden also said he's eager to prove himself in  
a way he could not in Utah, where he lived in the shadow of his 
father, former coach Frank Layden. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've really felt like I've been on the coattails of some  
brilliant people -- coaches, players, owners and the people who work 
in this organization,'' said Layden, who spent 18 years with the 
Jazz. 
</P>
<P>
	News reports indicated Layden could be paid about $1.5 million  
in New York, four times his Utah salary. He wouldn't talk about 
money but denied it was the reason he's leaving. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it was all about money, I would have moved on long ago,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As Utah's vice president of basketball operations, Layden  
developed a reputation as a skilled evaluator of talent. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of Utah's recent second-round draft selections, Bryon  
Russell and Shandon Anderson, contributed greatly to the team's 
runs to the NBA Finals in 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	But Layden also has had trouble making trades, and his signing  
of center Greg Ostertag to a six-year, $39 million contract was 
widely ridiculed around the league. 
</P>
<P>
	There may have been more reasons for Layden to leave than stay.  
For one, the Jazz's aging trio of Karl Malone, John Stockton and 
Jeff Hornacek are each over 35. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's Salt Lake's clean-cut -- some would say boring --  
image. Layden engineered deals in recent years for players like 
Rony Seikaly and Derek Harper, but neither would report. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden denied those factors contributed to his decision.  
</P>
<P>
	``By no means was that the case. This whole thing came up fast  
and it was an opportunity I felt I couldn't pass up,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Knicks player personnel director Ed Tapscott has been performing  
the general manager's duties on an interim basis. New York's only 
player moves this offseason were the signing of free agent forward 
John Wallace and the drafting of French center Frederic Weis. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden's departure leaves Utah without its chief negotiator as  
the Jazz try to resign Anderson, a free agent. Stockton and 
Hornacek also are free agents, but both are likely to return. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah general manager Tim Howells said he will take over talks  
with Anderson's agent. Meanwhile, he said the Jazz have no list and 
no deadline for hiring Layden's successor. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't something we had anticipated,'' Howells said. ``We  
met with Scott about some potential candidates. We have no 
timeline, but it's something we will be working on with a great 
sense of urgency.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
