<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DOE: Plutonium Made Its Way to Tenn. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAK RIDGE, Tenn. (AP) -- The federal government said Tuesday that  
5,600 tons of uranium contaminated with trace amounts of the more 
radioactive element plutonium were brought here in the 1950s and 
1960s for weapons fuel production. 
</P>
<P>
	The impact on workers and the environment is unknown, but  
Department of Energy officials promised to investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	The revelation followed a lawsuit accusing DOE of silently  
exposing workers to plutonium over decades at DOE's uranium 
enrichment plant in Paducah, Ky. The Washington Post reported the 
plutonium eventually contaminated the grounds and spilled into 
nearby streams and a wildlife refuge. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Secretary Bill Richardson on Sunday ordered a medical  
review of current and past workers at Paducah. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, he told NBC's ``Today'' show, ``We're looking at  
other plants, at Oak Ridge, to see whether this might have 
happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The amount of contaminated uranium at Oak Ridge's K-25 site  
represented a small portion of the some 40,000 tons of uranium used 
at the facility between the 1950s and the 1970s, said DOE spokesman 
Steven Wyatt. 
</P>
<P>
	Some workers at Oak Ridge fear they were unwittingly exposed to  
more radiation than they realized. 
</P>
<P>
	Uranium operations at K-25 were shut down in 1985, and some of  
the processing facilities currently are being disassembled and 
cleaned up. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 15:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Portrayals Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In their final pre-verdict arguments, the  
federal government and 19 states alleged Tuesday that Microsoft 
Corp. engaged in a broad pattern of unlawful conduct to maintain 
its lucrative ``desktop paradise'' in the computer software market. 
</P>
<P>
	Denying it's a monopolist, Microsoft said the government has  
failed to show that any of its actions hurt consumers and said its 
antitrust suit is ``largely a vehicle for Microsoft's competitors 
to attack Microsoft rather than compete in the marketplace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although the lengthy filings largely repeat claims made in  
earlier legal documents and over 76 days of courtroom testimony, 
U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson will base the first 
phase of his two-part verdict -- expected later this year -- on these 
arguments. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're the foundation for everything,'' said Rich Gray, an  
antitrust lawyer in San Jose, Calif., who has been following the 
trial closely. ``They're critically important. If (the sides) can't 
tell their story forcefully at this stage, then they're in 
trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first phase of the judge's ruling is expected to telegraph  
in many ways the eventual second part of his verdict, which 
probably will come early next year unless the sides settle. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge's factual findings also are particularly important  
because appellate courts rarely challenge a trial judge's decisions 
on the facts of a case, but typically focus on his application of 
the law. Experts predict the Microsoft case to wind through appeals 
courts for years. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge's factual findings will be ``much more difficult for  
Microsoft to attack on appeal,'' said Robert Taylor, another 
antitrust lawyer in California's Silicon Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending itself against a central claim by the government,  
Microsoft in its 453-page filing argued that it built its Internet 
browser software into Windows for free, to help consumers use the 
Web more effectively - not to force out of business Netscape 
Communications Corp., which was selling similar browser software 
separately. 
</P>
<P>
	``Microsoft's actions have produced higher quality Web browsing  
software and operating systems at lower cost to consumers, thereby 
contributing to the explosive growth of the Internet,'' the company 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a 776-page filing, the government asserted that  
Microsoft's aggressive actions -- such as allegedly pressuring 
computer makers and others against distributing rival software -- 
``distort the pace and direction of innovation in ways that protect 
its monopoly power rather than serving the interests of 
consumers.'' The Justice Department alleges that Microsoft was 
motivated by the fear that Internet software would evolve to the 
point where it made consumers rely less on computers using Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft complained that the government never proved that it  
blocked Netscape from distributing its Internet software from more 
than 40 percent of consumers, a condition the judge had established 
in an earlier ruling. Microsoft also argued that the $10 billion 
purchase of Netscape by America Online Inc. ``provides new avenues 
for the widespread distribution of Netscape's Web browsing 
software.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The government responded that AOL, the world's largest Internet  
provider with more than 16 million subscribers, bought Netscape for 
its popular Web site, not to acquire its browser software. It said 
Microsoft ``has signaled to AOL (and other would-be browser rivals) 
that Microsoft will engage in anticompetitive actions to prevent 
the browser threat from arising again.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
