<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stevenson Begins Tuneup for US Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Alexandra Stevenson doesn't scare  
easily, whether she's playing the semifinals at Wimbledon or being 
interviewed by Barbara Walters. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson's surprising run on the grass in England created a  
buzz about the 18-year-old tennis star that is still following her 
as she plays the Acura Classic, her first U.S. tournament since 
Wimbledon. 
</P>
<P>
	She faced Walters for a ``20-20'' interview last month, where  
the topic of her father, Hall of Fame basketball player Julius 
Erving, came up. He admitted during Wimbledon that Stevenson is his 
daughter. He has supported her financially, but hasn't seen her 
since she was 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``I sat down with Barbara and I said, `You know you always make  
everyone cry after 45 minutes, and you're not going to make me 
cry,''' Stevenson said. ``She started laughing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson said her mother, Samantha, became teary-eyed during  
the interview, which annoyed the teen-ager. 
</P>
<P>
	Walters asked Stevenson if she had heard of retired Gen. Norman  
Schwarzkopf, who's been interviewed by Walters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think so,'' Stevenson replied.  
</P>
<P>
	``Well, he cried on national television,'' Walters told her.  
``Do you think generals cry?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson said no.  
</P>
<P>
	``Well, they do and he cried, so nothing's wrong with crying,''  
Walters said. 
</P>
<P>
	``OK, but I'm not going to cry,'' Stevenson said.  
</P>
<P>
	She showed the same aplomb Monday in talking about her future in  
pro tennis. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson, ranked 41st in the world, plays her first-round match  
tonight against 26th-ranked Anke Huber of Germany. The winner faces 
top-seeded Lindsay Davenport. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to go out and be tough every match. They're going to be  
gunning for me and I'm going to be gunning for them,'' she said. 
``I have a lot of work ahead of me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson insists her life hasn't changed since her splash at  
Wimbledon. She still has the same friends and lives in the same 
apartment with her mother in San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest difference is that she's recognized more, including  
being spotted at dinner Sunday by ``this average Joe guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The man told Stevenson he had never watched women's tennis until  
seeing her at Wimbledon, and now he's coming to watch her tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was very happy, that made my night,'' she said. ``This is  
good for women's tennis, by the way. We need a sponsor, so maybe 
this will help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She'll have another admirer in the crowd at Manhattan Country  
Club. He's 24-year-old Collin Smith, a beach volleyball player she 
met at the recent Pan American Games in Canada, where Stevenson won 
a bronze medal. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best part of the Pan Am Games was beach volleyball. I met  
two guys there,'' she said, smiling. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson and Smith had a dinner date scheduled Monday night. He  
planned to watch her play tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's a nice person,'' Smith said. ``She's a great athlete and  
it's really cool to hang out with someone who also does what you 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson said she isn't worried about being labeled a flash in  
the pan if she doesn't make an impact at the U.S. Open, the year's 
final Grand Slam event. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just the beginning,'' she said. ``I have a lot of  
years.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
