<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Follows Market by Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell broadly Tuesday, as U.S. stocks  
sank further and traders ignored political turmoil abroad that has 
traditionally sent foreign exchange traders seeking the safety of 
U.S. currency. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 114.81  
Japanese yen, down from 115.20 yen at the same point on Monday. The 
euro, the single currency of 11 European nations, was quoted at 
$1.0708, down from $1.0712 on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rekindled tensions between new nuclear powers India and  
Pakistan, edgy relations between China and Taiwan and another 
makeover of the Russian cabinet failed to stir currency markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Upheaval in the Russian government has become commonplace, said  
Kevin Harris, international economist at MCM Currencywatch in New 
York, referring to Monday's installation of a new prime minister 
for the fourth time in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The standoffs in China and India with their neighbors -- Taiwan  
and Pakistan, respectively -- are also long-term situations that 
don't necessarily affect broad financial markets, Harris said. 
Consequently, currency traders apparently don't feel the need to 
flee to the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the absence of other news, the dollar has been following  
the U.S. asset markets,'' he said. The Dow Jones industrial 
average, at one point down 158 points, closed with a loss of 52.55 
at 10655.15. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Tuesday, the dollar was quoted at 1.4957 Swiss  
francs, up from 1.4953 a day earlier, and 1.4992 Canadian dollars, 
down from 1.5029 on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound rose to $1.6145 from late Monday's quote of  
$1.6064. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar rose at 1.8275 German  
marks, up from 1.8258; and 6.1275 French francs, up from 6.1237. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
