<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rains that lingered over the Plains tapered off early today as  
showers and thunderstorms worked their way east. 
</P>
<P>
	Storms dying out over the northern Plains were expected to move  
into the Midwest, with some of the heaviest storms forecast over 
Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	A frontal system working its way east also was expected to bring  
showers and thunderstorms to the Ohio and Tennessee Valleys, the 
Mid-Atlantic and Southeast, with lighter activity forecast in parts 
of the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	The central and southern Plains were expected to have another  
hot summer day with a chance of isolated showers, while a chance of 
showers and thunderstorms also was forecast in areas of the 
Southwest, the northern Rockies and the Pacific Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Severe weather on Monday was centered over parts of the northern  
Plains, where tornadoes were reported in parts of Minnesota and 
Iowa. No serious injuries were reported, but several businesses 
were damaged in Belgrade, Minn., while two farms were destroyed 
near Cleveland, Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, heavy rains and high winds in Louisiana led to flash  
flooding and thousands of power outages in New Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast in the 70s in the Northeast and the  
Great Lakes; in the 80s in the Ohio Valley, the northern Plains, 
the Pacific Northwest and northern Rockies; in the 90s Tennessee 
Valley, Southeast, the central and southern Plains; and in the 100s 
in southern parts of Texas and the desert Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures across the Lower 48 on Monday ranged from 108  
degrees in Gila Bend, Ariz., to 35 degrees in Stanley, Idaho. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
