<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Closes Down 52.55 at 10,655.15 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks continued their slide Tuesday as  
investors remained unsettled by growing expectations that the 
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates at least once more this 
year. Battered Internet stocks broke out of a slump to help slow 
the stock market's retreat. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 52.55 points to close at  
10,655.15. The blue-chip index had been down as much as 158 points 
earlier in the session. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also fell, although they mirrored the  
Dow and crept back from steep early losses. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 
500 fell 16.37 to 1,281.43, and the Nasdaq composite index fell 
29.48 to 2,489.50. 
</P>
<P>
	The S&AMP;P 500 closed 9.7 percent below its record high, set July  
16, dipping as low as the 10 percent decline that Wall Street 
considers a market correction. The Nasdaq is 13 percent below its 
peak, also reached July 16. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow has held up slightly better as investors gravitate  
toward large, well-established names. It is 4.9 percent below its 
record high. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks have been driven lower as the market absorbs the  
possibility of higher interest rates. Hoping to keep inflation from 
creeping into the booming U.S. economy, the Fed is widely expected 
to raise short-term interest rates when its policy-making Federal 
Open Market Committee meets Aug. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher interest rates typically hurt stocks by cutting into  
corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent sessions, market players have begun to debate whether  
the Fed will raise rates in October as well. Increases in August 
and October would be the second and third of 1999, undoing the 
three rate cuts imposed late last year as the Fed sought to keep 
the U.S. economy from being caught up in financial crises spreading 
through Asia, Russia and Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market always goes to extremes of fear and greed, and  
right now, fear is at an extreme,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, chief 
market strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	By Tuesday afternoon, however, fears were quelled by a spike in  
Internet stocks. Those shares, often highly priced relative to 
their paltry or nonexistent earnings, have been punished harshly in 
the past two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts said bargain-hunters and computer-program-guided  
traders stepped in and drove them higher. Yahoo! rose 6 5/16 to 
127 1/2 and Amazon.com rose 5 1/2 to 91. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've been stretched really thin and there's room for them  
to bounce back,'' said Ralph Bloch, chief market analyst at Raymond 
James &AMP; Co. in St. Petersburg, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	EBay, battered last week when the computer system that runs its  
online auction failed, rose 9 5/8 to 89 1/4. In an upbeat meeting with 
analysts Monday, EBay officials detailed plans to auction cars over 
the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The selling pressure on stocks also eased after a regional  
Federal Reserve Bank president with a vote on interest-rate policy, 
Robert McTeer Jr. of Dallas, told the Greater Dallas Chamber of 
Commerce that strong economic growth isn't necessarily 
inflationary, especially if it's fueled by gains in technology and 
productivity. 
</P>
<P>
	The threat of Fed action has pushed long-term interest rates to  
the highest levels in almost two years. On Tuesday, the 30-year 
Treasury bond yielded 6.24 percent, a level last seen in November 
1997, compared to 6.23 percent late Monday. The high yields on 
bonds are presenting an attractive, less volatile alternative to 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial services stocks, which are highly sensitive to  
interest-rate fluctuations, were mostly lower. J.P. Morgan fell 3 
to 121 15/16, contributing most to the Dow's decline. But its 
shares were also hurt by news of a $735 million lawsuit by Sumitomo 
Corp. over a copper trading scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucent fell 2 1/8 to 61 1/2 after agreeing to buy International  
Network Services Inc. for about $3.7 billion. Shares of INS rose 3 
to 50 7/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucent's deal strengthens its competitive position against Cisco  
Systems, analysts said, and helped drag Cisco shares down 1 1/16 to 
58. After the close of trading Tuesday, Cisco reported earnings 
that beat Wall Street's expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	The market slump created a hostile environment for initial  
public offerings. Shares of HotJobs.com, an online job-search firm, 
were priced at 8 but slipped to 7 5/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-1 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 831.64 million shares 
as of 4 p.m., compared with 674.62 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 6.60 to 603.80, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index fell 9.57 to 768.30. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.07 to 422.82. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.07 percent.  
European indexes fared worse. Germany's DAX index was down 1.7 
percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 2.4 percent, and France's 
CAC-40 was down 1.1 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
