<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Layden Discusses Offer With Jazz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Utah Jazz vice president of basketball  
operations Scott Layden has met with owner Larry Miller to discuss 
Layden's future with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden met with the New York Knicks during the weekend about  
their vacant general manager's job. A Jazz source, who asked not to 
be identified, told The Associated Press that Layden spent Monday 
discussing a counterproposal from Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	When the New York Knicks fired their general manager last April,  
Layden's name surfaced as a possible replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	KSTU Fox television, citing its own unnamed sources, reported  
Layden's departure is imminent. However, Jazz publicist Kim Turner 
said he couldn't confirm the move. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden has been valuable at recruiting talent, working trades,  
drafting and signing free agents -- making the Jazz one of the NBA's 
top teams. 
</P>
<P>
	And no one knows that better than Dave Checketts, the Knicks'  
president and chief operating officer who was president of the Utah 
Jazz in the 1980s and maintains close ties to Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Post reported that Checketts offered Layden a  
multiyear deal with a $1.5 million annual salary -- about four times 
his Jazz salary. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden has repeatedly declined comment.  
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks' job opened in April with the firing of Ernie  
Grunfeld, who was general manager before being demoted to 
consultant. 
</P>
<P>
	Grunfeld was let go less than a week after the Knicks lost in  
the NBA finals. The Knicks had done poorly in the Eastern 
Conference, although they made a miraculous run to the Finals 
before finally losing to the San Antonio Spurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden, son of former Jazz coach Frank Layden, joined the Jazz  
in 1981 as an assistant coach. In 1988, he became their chief scout 
and was named director of player development. His title was 
upgraded to vice president of basketball operations in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jazz finished off the 1999 season with a league-best 37-13  
record, but sputtered down the stretch and were eliminated from the 
playoffs in the second round by the Portland Trail Blazers. 
</P>
<P>
	That was Utah's earliest exit since 1995. The Jazz have had 13  
straight winning seasons, as well as four division titles and two 
Western Conference championships in the last decade. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
