<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Lucent To Buy INS for $3.7B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lucent Technologies Inc., plans to buy data  
networking company International Network Services Inc. for about 
$3.7 billion, according to The Wall Street Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was expected to be announced Tuesday, the Journal said,  
quoting people familiar with the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies declined to comment for the report.  
</P>
<P>
	INS had annual profits of $25.4 million for the fiscal year  
ended June 30, as sales grew 82 percent, to $315 million, over the 
previous fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	INS has had close ties with Lucent rival Cisco Systems Inc.,  
which owned 7.8 percent of the company, the newspaper said citing 
Cisco's most recent proxy statement. A Cisco executive sits on 
INS's board, the Journal said. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition is expected to boost Lucent's data networking  
operations. INS, headquartered in Sunnyvale, Calif., helps large 
corporations design, install and maintain computer networks. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the deal were not clear. If structured as an all-stock  
deal, the Journal said the INS purchase be worth $58 an INS, a 22 
percent premium over INS's Monday closing price of $47.43 3/4, up 
$1.37 1/2 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucent has made several recent acquisitions of computer  
networking companies. In June, the Murray Hill, N.J.-based company 
completed a $24 billion purchase of Ascend Communications Inc. and 
a $972 acquisition of closely held Nexabit Networks Inc. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
