<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 11:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cargill Takes Hits From Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Cargill Inc. says a lawsuit filed by Pioneer  
Hi-Bred International alleging misappropriation of genetic 
materials was largely responsible for Cargill's $182 million loss 
in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Cargill's loss for the quarter ended May 31 compared with  
earnings of $219 million in the same period last year, the company 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The private company, which is based in Minnetonka, Minn.,  
markets, processes and distributes agricultural, food, financial 
and industrial products worldwide. The company has about 82,000 
employees in 59 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	For the full fiscal year, Cargill said it earned $597 million,  
including a one-time gain from the sale of its international seed 
business. Cargill earned $468 million in fiscal 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Operating earnings were down 53 percent from the previous year  
to $220 million, and revenues were down 11 percent to $46 billion, 
the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the operating side, our earnings and revenues continue to  
reflect the tough economic climate for agriculture that began in 
Asia two years ago and spread to other parts of the world,'' said 
Robert Lumpkins, vice chairman and chief financial officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Commodity prices suffered their third straight year of decline  
due to the mismatch of weakened purchasing power in key markets and 
successive big global harvests -- a situation aggravated by trade 
barriers to agricultural goods in importing countries,'' Lumpkins 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We realized long ago that this will be a difficult, slow road  
to recovery. Hard-hit countries must institute the reforms needed 
to help their economies heal, and much more work is necessary to 
lower trade barriers to agricultural and food products,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pioneer, based in Des Moines, filed a lawsuit in Iowa against  
Cargill and two other seed companies last October, claiming the 
companies bred corn hybrids using genetic material developed by 
Pioneer. 
</P>
<P>
	Cargill has been trying to settle the lawsuit for several months  
since it traced suspicious genetic material in its breeding program 
back to a former Pioneer employee hired by Cargill. Cargill also 
pulled one of its hybrids off the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Pioneer also sued Thomas Ishler of Leola, Pa., alleging he was  
the former employee who had given its genetics to its competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Cargill's meat, fertilizer and animal nutrition businesses were  
among several that turned in strong performances, Lumpkins said. 
Cargill's financial businesses, which suffered losses last August 
when Russia defaulted on its debt and devalued the ruble, were 
restructured, and profitability improved in the second half, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lumpkins said the company invested $1.4 billion in the business  
over the past year under its new chief executive officer, Warren 
Staley. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
