<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed generally lower  
Tuesday, with the key index falling nearly 3 percent in Hong Kong 
on worries over escalating tensions between Taiwan and China. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, fell 2.7 percent, or 348.76 points, to a nine-week low 
of 12,596.71. On Monday, the index slumped 221.59 points, or 1.7 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said the fall was triggered by news reports that Chinese  
warplanes had crossed into Taiwanese airspace over the Taiwan 
Strait amid heightened tensions between Taipei and Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
	The political row between China and Taiwan erupted last month  
when Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui suggested that Beijing should 
regard the island as a separate state. The two sides split amid 
civil war in 1949. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hong Kong market was also pushed down by persistent rumors  
that China would devalue its currency. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore shares slumped on concerns about a rise in U.S.  
interest rates. The main Straits Times Index fell 46.66 points, or 
2.2 percent, to 2,022.56. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan shares however rebounded sharply as investors shrugged  
off the island's strained relations with China. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taipei market's key Weight Stock Price Index rose 241.59  
points, or 3.43 percent, to 7,269.60. The index has shed 15 percent 
since July 9, when relations with China started to sour. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 11.64  
points, or 0.07 percent, to close at 17,202.09. On Monday, the 
average closed up 106.21 points, or 0.62 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	After spending much of the day in negative territory, the Nikkei  
bounced back in the afternoon after the announcement of a 
better-than-expected figure for June machinery orders. 
</P>
<P>
	The Economic Planning Agency said machinery orders to Japanese  
makers were up 6.3 percent from May. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 114.88 yen in  
late-afternoon trading, down 0.28 yen from late Monday in Tokyo and 
also below its late New York level of 115.20 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares slumped as growing concerns about the  
domestic political situation and the regional markets' bearishness 
dragged down the main index. The Composite Index fell 3 percent, or 
17.766 points, to 576.343. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower. The benchmark  
NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 24.70 points, or 1.1 percent, to 
2,165.10. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed lower on mounting fears of  
rising domestic and U.S. interest rates. The 30-company Philippine 
Stock Exchange Index fell 24.52 points or 1.1 percent, to 2,230.78. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian market's key indicator closed lower,  
dragged down by heavyweight industrial stocks although the resource 
sector finished in positive territory. The All Ordinaries index 
fell 18.2 points, or 0.6 percent, to 2,958.7. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: The key index rose on expectations that the restructuring  
of the financially troubled Daewoo Group will be speeded up. The 
Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 19.69 points, or 2 percent, 
to 968.66. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed higher on  
bargain-hunting. The Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip 
stocks, rose 15.44 points, or 2.3 percent, to 683.65. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stock prices closed slightly lower as a major  
economic stimulus package failed to bolster confidence in a market, 
which fears a hike in U.S. interest rates. The SET index The SET 
index fell 2.60 points, or 0.6 percent, to 430.85. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
