<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies' Ace Schilling OK To Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Curt Schilling's shoulder showed no signs of  
a bone spur in X-rays Tuesday, and the Phillies' ace is on schedule 
to make his next start Friday in Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling received a cortisone injection in the shoulder on  
Sunday and ``feels much better,'' team doctor Michael Ciccotti 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not expect that he will need another shot, and I do not  
expect that he will need surgery,'' Ciccotti said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first good news in a while on Schilling's condition.  
Schilling had made 117 straight starts before missing one July 28 
because of biceps tendinitis. He returned to the rotation Saturday 
and allowed seven earned runs and eight hits in 6 1-3 innings of an 
8-2 loss to Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, Schilling was diagnosed with bursitis and received a  
cortisone shot Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	X-rays were take of Schilling's acromion bone, a small bone at  
the tip of the shoulder where he had a bone spur removed during 
surgery to repair a torn labrum in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks fine,'' Ciccotti said. ``There is no spur there that  
has reformed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling will throw off the mound Wednesday and make his start  
Friday unless there is a setback. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's on schedule,'' general manager Ed Wade said.  
</P>
<P>
	In other injury news, a recent MRI of right-hander Carlton  
Loewer's humerus bone showed improvement. But if he is able to 
pitch again this season, it is expected to be in a relief role -- 
not in the starting rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	Loewer, who has been throwing without pain, also will throw  
Friday. He could pitch in a game in 3-6 weeks -- sometime in 
September. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the point of the season it is, the easiest thing to do  
is for him to throw from the bullpen,'' Ciccotti said. 
</P>
<P>
	Third baseman Scott Rolen still has back spasms, and he's being  
treated with a stretching program. On Monday, Rolen saw spinal 
orthopedist Todd Albert, who agreed with the treatment the Phillies 
prescribed. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortstop Desi Relaford had the cast removed from his right  
wrist. He'll start hitting off a tee next week, and could join the 
team in a limited role soon after that. 
</P>
<P>
	Right-hander Paul Byrd is on an anti-inflammatory for back  
spasms which caused him to miss his start Monday night. He is 
scheduled to pitch Saturday in Cincinnati. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
