<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 10, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Gunman Wounds 5 at L.A. Jewish Center  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A gunman sprayed the lobby of a suburban  
Jewish community center with a 9mm Uzi today, wounding three boys, 
a teen-age girl and a woman, authorities said. An 8-year-old boy 
and the 55-year-old were both in critical condition. Police 
searched the grounds of the North Valley Jewish Community Center 
and the Granada Hills neighborhood for a suspect identified only as 
a white male, said police Cmdr. Dave Kalish. Police did not specify 
the suspect's age. Fire Department spokesman Steve Ruda said he is 
a teen-ager. 

</P>
<P>
	Arafat OKs Israel Withdrawal Delay  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has accepted a  
later date for Israel to carry out a pullback from the West Bank, 
but insists that the government of Ehud Barak subsequently follow 
the timetable laid out in a U.S.-brokered peace pact, a Palestinian 
official said today. That appeared to break an Israeli-Palestinian 
deadlock that had pushed back a planned visit to the region by U.S. 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. Arafat told Barak in a 
letter that all obligations under the Wye River accord ``should be 
implemented fully and by November,'' the official said. 

</P>
<P>
	US Calls for India-Pakistan Dialogue  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- State Department spokesman James P. Rubin  
called for dialogue between India and Pakistan and urged restraint 
after Indian fighter planes shot down a Pakistani surveillance 
aircraft today. Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said 16 
servicemen were killed. Rubin said the United States had no role to 
play in the dispute. India said the aircraft was shot down after it 
crossed into Indian airspace and failed to respond to warnings. 

</P>
<P>
	Dutch To Legalize Mercy Killing  
</P>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- The Dutch government published  
plans today to legalize mercy killing under strict guidelines, 
which would allow children as young as 12 to demand and receive 
euthanasia. The plans are expected to gain parliamentary approval 
next year, which would make the Netherlands the first country in 
the world to legalize mercy killing. The new law formalizes 
practices already widely accepted and carried out in the 
Netherlands. Although 3 percent of all Dutch deaths -- 3,600 people 
-- each year are reported as euthanasia, the actual number is 
believed to be double because many physicians fail to report cases. 

</P>
<P>
	250 Bodies Exhumed in Bosnia  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- Forensic experts,  
reconstructing a 1995 massacre in the Bosnian enclave of 
Srebrenica, have finished exhuming about 250 bodies from a mass 
grave, U.N. officials said today. Srebrenica was a Muslim enclave 
in northeast Bosnia. The United Nations declared it a ``safe 
heaven'' but did nothing to prevent Bosnian Serb forces from 
overrunning it in July 1995. The enclave's brutal fall left over 
7,000 Muslim men missing. Bosnian Serb leaders Radovan Karadzic and 
his war-time general Ratko Mladic were indicted for war crimes but 
are at large. 

</P>
<P>
	Shatner's Wife Found Dead in Pool  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- William Shatner's wife was found dead in  
their swimming pool, an apparent drowning that authorities said 
they were treating as an accident. The distraught ``Star Trek'' 
star said she ``meant everything to me.'' Shatner said he found his 
wife, Nerine, 40, at the bottom of a swimming pool when he returned 
home last night. Shatner said he dialed 911, pulled his wife out of 
the pool and administered CPR, but his efforts to revive her and 
similar efforts by emergency personnel were unsuccessful. 

</P>
<P>
	Tupperware Begins Online Sales  
</P>
<P>
	KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- Tupperware, which for decades relied  
solely on face-to-face sales at parties, today began selling its 
housewares over the Internet. The move online is the latest 
innovation for the company in its efforts to get Tupperware 
containers into the hands of its customers following a year of 
declining sales. Tupperware had $1.1 billion in sales last year. 
Tupperware officials emphasized that the new ventures will 
supplement, not replace, the traditional Tupperware parties. The 
Web site is located at www.tupperware.com. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 53  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before the closing at 4 p.m. EDT, the Dow  
industrials were down 53.19 at 10,654.51. Declining issues on the 
New York Stock Exchange led advancers 2,445-650. The Nasdaq was 
down 35.22 at 2,483.76. 

</P>
<P>
	Knicks Hire Layden As New GM  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Scott Layden, whose personnel moves helped  
the Utah Jazz become an NBA contender in the 1990s, has accepted an 
offer to become general manager of the New York Knicks. News 
reports indicated Layden could earn about $1.5 million in New York, 
four times his Utah salary. The Knicks have been seeking a GM since 
firing Ernie Grunfeld in April. Knicks president Dave Checketts 
worked with Layden in Utah in the 1980s. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
  	   	
</P>
