<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 23:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ill 49er Coach Keeps Coaching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) -- Coaching is not just Bobb McKittrick's  
job. It's part of his therapy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if I didn't have cancer, even if i wasn't sick, when you  
get to be older like I am, it's neat to be around young people, 
like the players,'' said the 49ers' longtime offensive line coach, 
who has cancer of the bile duct. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of them, they're in their 20s. Their music is not my  
music and their movies are not my movies, but anyway, it's kind of 
neat to be around them, maybe even more so when you're sick. 
They've got enthusiasm and vigor. It's upbeat. I'm a coach. It's 
what I do. I want to do this, I can do this and I think, `Jimminy, 
I'm going to be OK.''' 
</P>
<P>
	McKittrick, 63, has been coaching NFL offensive linemen for the  
past 28 years, including the last 21 in San Francisco. He has been 
one of the constants in the long-running 49ers success story that 
began in 1981, when they won the first of five Super Bowls. 
</P>
<P>
	Last January, shortly after the 49ers playoff loss at Atlanta,  
McKittrick learned that he has bile duct cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, he has been hospitalized on seven different  
occasions. He has endured rounds of chemotherapy and radiation 
treatment in the spring that left him weak and gaunt. He has lost 
about 25 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	It was hoped his diseased liver could be replaced with a donated  
one, but doctors in April ruled out a transplant when they 
discovered the cancer had spread beyond the duct. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the discouraging news, McKittrick showed up at the  
team's minicamp in May and continued his coaching from a golf cart. 
The team also gave McKittrick some help, moving Pat Morris from 
coaching tight ends to the offensive line and bringing in former 
lineman Guy McIntyre as an intern. 
</P>
<P>
	At the team's training camp, McKittrick has been feeling a lot  
better. The golf cart is still a constant presence, but he's 
getting out now and then, talking to his linemen and demonstrating 
blocking techniques, though not as much as he did before. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, McKittrick said, in some ways he's a better coach now.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a little different perspective, particularly with Pat  
Morris and Guy McIntyre doing in the sense the leg work that I used 
to do. I can observe maybe a little better than I did when I was 
more hands-on and so close that you couldn't see other things 
around. So in some ways, I probably have a better feel for some 
things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just about his only concessions to cancer are turning in early,  
missing the club's final team meeting of the day and sleeping a 
little later, missing the first morning get-together by coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope he's not doing too much,'' 49ers coach Steve  
Mariuci said. ``It's incredible. He doesn't have to do this. He has 
alternatives in his life. Talk about leading by example.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McKittrick said the work isn't bad and the 49ers have allowed  
him to continue under a reduced coaching schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``All it is is eat, sleep, exercise and get fresh air,'' he  
said. ``It's a pretty good deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the reality of McKittrick's battle is never far away.  
</P>
<P>
	He was scheduled to undergo an MRI today so doctors can  
determine whether his finger-sized tumor has shrunk, stayed the 
same or gotten bigger. The results were expected Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was to have a 3 1/2-inch shunt in his diseased duct  
replaced. The shunt acts as a drain, but it must be replaced about 
every three months. 
</P>
<P>
	McKittrick said he's staying positive and has refused to even  
entertain the notion, ``Why me?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Shoot, here I am 63 years old. I've got five Super Bowl rings,  
been to Pro Bowls, American Bowls. I've had a great life. It would 
not be fair to say, `Why me?' I'd be ashamed to even say `Why me?' 
when there are young people and so many others who are lot worse 
off than I am.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 20:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton and Gore Campaign Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Inseparable was one label for President  
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore on Tuesday. Together, they made 
three fund-raising events, three meals, a tour and a roundtable. 
</P>
<P>
	Insufferable, said Republicans.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have been together under all kinds of circumstances,''  
Clinton said at one of the events. ``They were times of great 
elation, times of great triumphs, times of defeat, times of 
frustration, times of intense difficulty. But we've also been 
together in personal ways. I talk to him about everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's aid to Gore's presidential campaign was spelled out in  
their identical Tuesday calendars: 
</P>
<P>
	--12:15 p.m. Joint tour of Washington-area factory to highlight  
Gore's New Markets Initiative for small businesses and the economic 
success ``that the vice president and I have developed over the 
last 6 1/2 years,'' as Clinton put it. During the tour, Clinton 
learned how to make a wet mop. ``I'm always looking for new skills 
since I have to apply some of these things,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	--12:35 p.m. His-and-his presentation to a business roundtable;  
message same as above. Share a limo back to the White House and 
then huddle over lunch in Clinton's Oval Office suite. 
</P>
<P>
	--6:10 p.m. Address two dozen Democratic fund-raisers, including  
Seagram Chairman Edgar Bronfman Jr., in front of news cameras. 
</P>
<P>
	--6:45 p.m. Eject reporters, schmooze same fund-raisers over  
chicken on wild rice dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	--7:30 p.m. Running behind schedule, nix speech to different set  
of high rollers, New Jersey Nets basketball star Jayson Williams 
among them. 
</P>
<P>
	--8:00 p.m. Repeat closed-door dinner, this time with grilled  
salmon on crabmeat hash. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to have just 25 in each dinner because the more you  
get into a room, the less intimate it becomes,'' Gore spokesman 
Roger Salazar explained about the two supper events. 
</P>
<P>
	Last weekend, Clinton and Gore paired up for the first time on  
the Campaign 2000 trail, picking up more than $300,000 in Arkansas 
and trying to put to rest lingering reports of dissension between 
them. More joint fund-raisers are planned. 
</P>
<P>
	But no money changed hands Tuesday night. Instead, said Salazar,  
the receptions and dinners were intended to energize the people 
organizing future fund-raisers, thank those who already have and 
recruit new blood. 
</P>
<P>
	``I need your help,'' said Gore. ``The decision will be  
contested because change always is resisted and we have been 
bringing change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side, Republican National Committee chairman Jim  
Nicholson mocked up a Gore 2000 campaign poster with the caption 
``Bosom Buddies'' under a photo of Gore hugging Clinton with both 
arms. 
</P>
<P>
	In a news release, Nicholson recalled Gore's statement in June,  
as he launched his presidential campaign, that Clinton's Oval 
Office affair with a White House intern was ``inexcusable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Now Gore and Clinton are back on the prowl, as a fund-raising  
tag team, working to shake down Democrat fat cats,'' Nicholson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Begala, a veteran of the 1992 Clinton-Gore campaign and a  
former White House political strategist, said Gore is smart to 
exploit the president's ``unmatched ability to raise issues and 
money'' and to rally Democrats. Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley 
is challenging Gore for the party's presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	But, added Begala, a Gore booster, ``You don't want them joined  
at the hip. Gore has to stand up and define himself with some 
force.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 16:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR Suspends 2 Racial Prank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASCAR stars Terry Labonte and Derrike Cope fired two employees  
for a racial prank in which one of their workers wore a sheet over 
his head like a Klansman and confronted a black colleague. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses characterized the July 8 episode at the New Hampshire  
International Speedway as a joke by two white motorcoach drivers 
that went too far. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just needs to be understood that there is a line that  
cannot be crossed, joking or otherwise,'' said Kevin Triplett, 
NASCAR's director of operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the two motorcoach drivers were not employed by NASCAR,  
the sanctioning body could only suspend their licenses, which is 
the most severe punishment within its power. That means the two men 
cannot enter any area of a track over which NASCAR has 
jurisdiction. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR did not announce the suspensions until its investigation  
was complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte and Cope said the two motorcoach drivers had confronted  
a coachman for another NASCAR driver, Jeremy Mayfield. 
</P>
<P>
	Cope's driver was identified by team and NASCAR sources as Mike  
``Grumpy'' Culberson, and Labonte's as Ray Labbe. Spokesmen for the 
teams said neither former coachman planned any comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The black coachman, David Scott, also would not comment,  
according to a spokesman for Mayfield's team. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the two men wore the sheet over his head and the other  
accompanied him when they confronted Scott three days before the 
Jiffy Lube 300, according to NASCAR and team sources who spoke on 
condition they not be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	``Behavior like this simply cannot be tolerated in today's  
society,'' Cope said in a statement. ``This was an example of 
grievous behavior that I do not condone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 1990 Daytona 500 champion called it ``an ignorant act'' that  
left him no recourse but dismissal. 
</P>
<P>
	``These actions are deplorable and will not be tolerated,'' said  
Labonte, a two-time Winston Cup champion. ``When this situation was 
brought to my attention, the employee was released immediately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach drivers are employed by most of the circuit's top racers  
who stay at the tracks during events. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR said it would not stand for any racial discrimination.  
</P>
<P>
	``Harassment of any type -- racial, religious, whatever, will not  
be tolerated in any form,'' Triplett said. 
</P>
<P>
	Auto racing is a predominantly white sport, and NASCAR's top  
division has had just one full-time black driver in its history, 
and only a sprinkling of black crew members. Few blacks are seen 
among the vast audiences at race tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	Aware of that image, NASCAR has been working to create minority  
interest. Former basketball great Julius Erving and former football 
star Joe Washington have formed a team, while former Olympic 
champion Jackie Joyner Kersee recently announced she is planning to 
be part of a new team. 
</P>
<P>
	The only black driver to reach NASCAR's top level was the late  
Wendell Scott, who got his lone career victory in 1963. His son, 
Franklin, criticized the sport as being exclusionary during his 
father's posthumous induction earlier this year into the 
International Motorsports Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	One driver who has spoken out about the racial makeup of auto  
racing is Frank Kimmel, reigning champion of the second-tier ARCA 
racing circuit, which is not affiliated with NASCAR. He has had 
some black crew members who have talked openly about the difficulty 
of being minorities in auto racing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't like to admit it, but it is a redneck sport,'' Kimmel  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 16:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McKesson HBOC Earnings Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- McKesson HBOC Inc., the drug and  
medical-supplies distributor plagued by false income statements, 
reported Tuesday that first quarter earnings were up 8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings of 30 cents per share were 4 cents below consensus  
estimates of analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. The San 
Francisco-based company's stock fell nearly 7 percent Tuesday to 
close at $29.75 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	For the quarter ended June 30, McKesson's net income before  
special charges was $86.4 million. In the same quarter last year, 
net income was $80.1 million. Revenues rose 22 percent, to $6.5 
billion on strength in McKesson's pharmaceutical distribution and 
medical-surgical businesses. The company reported it was hurt by 
lower sales of medical-care information software and hardware. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of improper accounting, McKesson was forced last month  
to lower its net income reports by a total of over $191 million for 
fiscal years 1997 through 1999. The accounting problems were due to 
improperly reported software sales at HBOC, a software company 
acquired by McKesson in January. 
</P>
<P>
	McKesson's board of directors fired Chairman Charles W. McCall,  
who led HBOC before McKesson bought it. Mark A. Pulido, president 
and chief executive of the merged company, and Chief Financial 
Officer Richard H. Hawkins both resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Chiarelli, an analyst for J.P. Morgan, said the company's  
failure to meet expectations for the quarter was due in part to 
company executives' reluctance to talk openly with analysts in the 
wake of the reporting problems. 
</P>
<P>
	It will probably take one to two years for McKesson to regain  
investor confidence, Chiarelli predicted. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have a very good chances of turning this thing around and  
being on a very good growth path,'' said Chiarelli. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 07:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NY Police Pull Woodstock Photos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- State Police officials have removed news photos  
from their Woodstock '99 Web pages, the latest step in a 
controversy that brought complaints from news organizations over 
use of the images in police work. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason we took the pictures off was because they didn't  
provide any more leads,'' said Lt. Jamie Mills, a State Police 
spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	The 14 news photos were posted July 30 without permission and  
removed Friday after a week of protests by media groups to police 
and Gov. George Pataki. 
</P>
<P>
	The source of most of the photos -- The Associated Press and  
Syracuse Online, affiliated with Syracuse Newspapers -- had demanded 
the pictures be removed, arguing that their use violated copyright 
and blurred the traditional separation between journalism and 
police work. 
</P>
<P>
	State Police had hoped the photographs would encourage the  
public to identify suspects in the rioting and looting that marred 
the end of the Woodstock concert. As of Monday, none had led to an 
arrest, Mills said. 
</P>
<P>
	New photos have been posted. Mills said most of those were taken  
by state employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Barrantes, a State Police lawyer, said the state had not  
backed away from its argument that it was legal and fair to post 
the news photos on the Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Penchina, a lawyer for the AP, said the news organization  
would ``remain vigilant in making sure that its intellectual 
property is not misused.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We view the fact that the photos have been taken down as a  
victory not only in protecting AP's copyright interests but also in 
avoiding further erosion of the line between investigation and 
reporting done by journalists and the investigatory arm of the 
state,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Various news organizations complained about the posting of the  
photos in letters to police or Pataki, including The New York Press 
Club, The Deadline Club, The New York State Associated Press 
Association, the New York Daily News, The New York Times and The 
Buffalo News. 
</P>
<P>
	Louis D. Boccardi, president and CEO of the AP, had written that  
the role and responsibility of State Police was clear and important 
but that it was equally important to separate police and journalism 
functions. 
</P>
<P>
	``If our photographers are to be seen as proxies for state  
police investigators, they will be placed in danger,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	State Police officials say the photos have produced more than  
150 e-mail responses. So far, police have arrested 39 people on 
charges ranging from disorderly conduct to sodomy. No one has been 
arrested in the five rapes reported at the event or in other major 
Woodstock-related crimes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 20:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton and Gore Campaign Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Inseparable was one label for President  
