<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 12:20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Not Distracted by Bush's Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Former Cabinet secretary Elizabeth Dole  
on Tuesday said she's not distracted by Texas Gov. George W. Bush's 
huge financial edge as she seeks to counter his financial muscle 
with brand-new voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at history,'' Mrs. Dole said, in arguing that money can't  
be the sole basis for a bid for the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	The former head of the American Red Cross slogged through four  
Des Moines campaign stops seeking to lure new voters to the polls, 
and to a big straw poll on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are coming to the events, it's not a matter of having to  
pull them in. They are there,'' Mrs. Dole said. 
</P>
<P>
	At campaign stops, Mrs. Dole carefully positions herself at the  
door after speaking, shaking hands and speaking with all who 
attend. At the same time, aides are busily scurrying around with 
pledge cards, seeking to sign up backers for the Saturday straw 
poll. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowds are heavily female and young, and Mrs. Dole said  
that's who she is targeting as she seeks to broaden the Republican 
base. While she claimed progress, the success rate of aides was 
well under 50 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a tough task, because straw polls and precinct caucuses are  
new to many who attend her events. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do have to inform people and educate them in terms of the  
process,'' Mrs. Dole said. ``We're trying to do that as effectively 
as we can, help to get to know the steps you have to follow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Mrs. Dole doesn't focus her campaign strictly on her  
gender, she points to a series of firsts she's had that appeal to 
women voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what I think it's important to focus on, what you can  
bring to the table,'' she said. ``It's not a liability. What it 
shows is you've been able to break the glass ceiling in many 
instances. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now it's time to break this glass ceiling,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	With her well-heeled political name and long resume, Mrs. Dole  
said she has the strength to survive the looming straw poll even as 
she works to pull together a turnout operation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's a do-or-die for us on Saturday,'' she said,  
``but we want to do well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said a key to her campaign is electability. Most polls show  
her ahead of Vice President Al Gore and she claimed that adds 
substance to her effort. Bush also leads Gore in head-to-head 
matchups. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not distracted by that,'' she said, noting candidates like  
Texas Sen. Phil Gramm, businessman Ross Perot and former Texas Gov. 
John Connally had plenty of money, but didn't win. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have the money he has, but I've got the vision, I've  
got the experience, I've got the ideas on the issues,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you keep going forward with your campaign and not  
distracted,'' said Mrs. Dole. ``It's early and probably less than 5 
percent of Americans across the country are even engaged in 
presidential politics at this point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her comments came in a campaign swing throughout the central  
part of the state, one of a long list of contenders stumping in the 
state and pointing toward a big straw poll on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm energized,'' Mrs. Dole said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
