<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Institute Wants All Knowledge on Web </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- While entrepreneurs and investors worry about how  
to make money from the Internet, Kevin Marsh has a different goal: 
perfect knowledge. 
</P>
<P>
	Marsh hopes to put mankind's accumulated knowledge within a few  
keystrokes of anyone with a computer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Imagine what would happen if all the things that people know  
were recorded online and indexed for easy retrieval. Any question, 
any curiosity, any interest could be quickly and efficiently 
satisfied,'' Marsh, a library scientist, mused to The Dallas 
Morning News. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the stuff that keeps me up at night thinking.''  
</P>
<P>
	Marsh runs a nonprofit group, the Information Access Institute  
(www.information.org), from a former blacksmith's shop next to his 
turn-of-the-century home near Georgetown. The institute helps 
libraries and museums put what librarians call ``knowledge 
records'' online. 
</P>
<P>
	Marsh is helping a Web site that will display a complete  
collection of historic Texas constitutions from a collection at the 
University of Texas, and he's consulting with the Florida State 
Photographic Archive and Texas museums to help catalog their 
collections and put them on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``People fret about all the bad stuff that's on the Internet,''  
Marsh said. ``But it's like New York: Everything from museums to 
red-light districts. The way we fight the red-light districts on 
the Internet is not by censorship, but by putting more of the good 
stuff online.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marsh said that's the best way to make the Internet a tool for  
progress, and he pointed to medical information on the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	``Patients can quickly learn and help their doctors gather  
information on obscure diseases,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the institute is to catalog all human knowledge, however, it  
might have to do it on a shoestring. In a world of Internet 
enterprises worth millions of dollars, the institute last year had 
a budget of $60,000, mostly earned for consulting work. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our biggest clients so far are museums, and they don't have a  
lot of money,'' Marsh said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
