<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Race-Based Busing Request Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A federal judge has denied the request of a group  
of white parents to end race-based busing in the city's schools by 
next month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston School Committee voted last month to end racial  
assignments for the school year beginning September 2000, but four 
white families said that wasn't soon enough. The parents said their 
children were being denied their first choice of schools because of 
racial considerations. 
</P>
<P>
	In a hearing last week, they asked U.S. District Court Judge  
Nancy Gertner for a preliminary injunction to revise the busing 
policy by the start of classes on Sept. 9. 
</P>
<P>
	The injunction would have affected children entering  
kindergarten and first-grade, as well as transfer students and 
those on waiting lists for their top school choices. 
</P>
<P>
	Gertner said Monday the injunction would inflict ``substantial  
disruption'' on the school assignment plan. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials had said there was simply no time to implement  
it in a matter of weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the outgoing Boston plan, children are assigned to schools  
based on race; the proximity of the child's home to the school; 
whether he or she has any siblings there; and the results of a 
yearly school choice lottery. Under the new plan, effective in 
September 2000, race will no longer be considered. 
</P>
<P>
	The outgoing policy emerged out of a federal desegregation court  
order 25 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston schools Superintendent Thomas Payzant said he was pleased  
with Gertner's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``It means that there won't be disappointment for students who  
already have received their assignments,'' he said. ``It means 
there will be no disruptions for families.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 15:52:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Brazil, Germany Bid for World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- Brazil brought a squad of soccer  
heroes, and Germany hosted a beer fest at FIFA headquarters as the 
two countries made their bids to host the 2006 World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil and Germany were the last of five countries to make their  
pitches on Tuesday for the 2006 World Cup, the most coveted soccer 
event on the planet. 
</P>
<P>
	Also presenting to the FIFA were South Africa, England and  
Morocco. 
</P>
<P>
	After Monday's presentations by South Africa, accessorized by a  
chanting, dancing Zulu warrior, and England, who flew in singing 
school children, Brazil pumped up its campaign with a squad of 
football heroes. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to revive a fading bid, Brazil recruited superstar  
Ronaldo, as well as football legends Dunga, Zico and Carlos Alberto 
Torres. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany, meanwhile, hosted a beer fest, complete with pretzels,  
white sausage and a Bavarian accordion band on the FIFA 
headquarters' lakeside terrace. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil, fighting off negative publicity from football legend  
Pele's recent criticism of the bid, dismissed the former-player's 
disapproval, dispelling speculation it would harm the nation's 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the bid is bigger than Pele,'' said Torres, who was on  
the winning squad with Pele at the World Cup in Mexico in 1970. 
``I've known Pele for the past 40 years and I'm sure he will join 
us when he gets to know how serious we are with this project.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With South America last hosting the event in 1978, the  
Brazilians felt it would be unfair for Africa to get the next World 
Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``It needs to go where it is most loved,'' added Torres. ``If  
you had a first basketball World Cup, it would absolutely have to 
go to the United States. It only makes sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil also insisted it had gained full governmental backing.  
</P>
<P>
	The German delegation, led by former football great Franz  
Beckenbauer, underlined its organizational skills, modern 
facilities and technical superiority. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody still has a chance,'' said Beckenbauer, the captain  
of the 1974 German team that won the World Cup title at home and 
coach of the 1990 side that captured the title in Italy. ``Our job 
is now to convince everybody that Germany is the best place for the 
World Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, South Africa made en emotional appeal to host the  
continent's first World Cup, evoking the nation's troubled, 
turbulent past. The nation insists it has the necessary 
infrastructure to host a World Cup, and spent considerable time 
addressing the issue of safety and security. 
</P>
<P>
	The English, who are hoping to host a World Cup for the first  
time in 40 years, jetted in a 135-strong corps for a half-hour 
presentation and press interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	Morocco made its third bid in an attempt to become the first  
African nation to host the World Cup. It has been speculated, 
however, that it may pull out of the running following King 
Hassan's death. 
</P>
<P>
	With FIFA President Blatter repeatedly expressing his wish for  
the 2006 World Cup to go to the African continent for the first 
time, South Africa is being considered the front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-member Executive Committee will make its final vote on  
the 2006 host in July 2000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 15:50:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Newsmagazines Help CBS Ratings / TV Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- CBS had the top three newsmagazines in the  
ratings last week for the first time since the premiere of ``60 
Minutes II'' in January, leading the network to an easy prime-time 
win for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The venerable ``60 Minutes'' was the week's most-watched  
program, drawing an estimated 13.3 million viewers. ``60 Minutes 
II'' on Wednesday and the summertime ``Monday Mysteries'' edition 
of ``48 Hours'' also both made the week's top 10 shows. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week, CBS had a 6.7 rating and 13 share, Nielsen Media  
Research said Tuesday. NBC was second with a 5.8 rating and 11 
share, ABC had a 5.4 rating and 10 share and Fox had a 4.0 rating 
and 8 share. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC's showdown between golfers Tiger Woods and David Duval had  
an average audience of 9.7 million, making it the 17th-rated 
program of the week. ABC estimated more than 20 million people 
tuned in to at least some of the unusual prime-time golf special. 
</P>
<P>
	Two hours of prime-time rock 'n' roll didn't go over well on  
Fox. Its ``Best of Woodstock '99'' special finished in 84th place 
for the week, with only 4.9 million viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the emerging networks, the WB had a 2.3 rating and 4  
share, UPN had a 1.6 rating and 3 share and Pax TV was at 0.8 and 
2. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC's ``World News Tonight'' won the evening news ratings race  
for the second straight week with a 7.0 rating and 16 share. The 
``NBC Nightly News'' had a 6.8 rating and 16 share, and the ``CBS 
Evening News'' was at 5.7 and 13. 
</P>
<P>
	A rating point represents 994,000 households, or 1 percent of  
the nation's estimated 99.4 million TV homes. The share is the 
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week of Aug. 2-8, the top 10 shows, their networks and  
ratings were: ``60 Minutes,'' CBS, 9.6; ``Frasier'' special, NBC, 
9.4; ``Frasier,'' NBC, 8.8; ``Friends,'' NBC, 8.8; ``CBS Sunday 
Movie: Stolen Women, Captured Hearts,'' CBS, 8.7; ``Just Shoot Me'' 
special, NBC, 8.5; ``CBS Wednesday Movie: Undue Influence, Part 
Two,'' CBS, 8.4; ``Touched By an Angel,'' CBS, 8.1; ``60 Minutes 
II,'' CBS, 7.9; ``48 Hours-Monday,'' CBS, 7.7. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
