<DOCNO> APW19990810.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 10:47:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Listens in Queens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton today praised unpaid  
caregivers for children, the sick and the elderly as the nation's 
unsung heroes and said they should benefit from federal tax breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're at a real crossroads. Do we support families in the  
tasks they perform for their loved ones, or do we go on with a 
fiscally irresponsible tax cut?'' the first lady asked several 
hundred participants in a session of her listening tour at a Queens 
union hall. 
</P>
<P>
	Five women on a panel discussed how to balance family and work.  
</P>
<P>
	Carol Levine, whose husband was severely disabled as a result of  
a car accident, said that every day ``is a struggle with all the 
bureaucracies that seem to be resisting helping people in my 
situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Manhattan woman, who works for the United Hospital Fund,  
told Mrs. Clinton that what is needed in addition to tax breaks are 
training and support of family caregivers like herself. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's this gap in the middle of the night -- `Who am I going  
to call when the machine doesn't work?''' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, taking a swipe at proposed Republican tax cuts,  
said 158,000 unpaid state caregivers eligible for federal 
assistance would have their funding cut off. 
</P>
<P>
	Like a busy schoolteacher, she encouraged, mediated and  
organized the discussion, and she got all the names right when 
addressing the participants. 
</P>
<P>
	She listened carefully and took notes as Mercedes Manne, a  
stay-at-home mother, told her of the difficulties of taking care of 
her four children and sick husband. ``I found myself so alone,'' 
she said of the time when her husband, the sole breadwinner, 
developed a severe back problem. ``My husband is so tired. He needs 
help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the discussion, Mrs. Clinton answered a handful of  
questions from reporters before her spokesman abruptly ended the 
discussion. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to a comment that the Republican Party, led by Gov.  
George Pataki, appeared to be uniting behind her potential rival 
for the U.S. Senate, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, she said: ``I try not 
to think about issues I have no control over. What the other party 
does is strictly their business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She did not comment directly on a report that another potential  
GOP candidate, Rep. Rick Lazio, was bowing to Pataki's request and 
will postpone plans to announce his candidacy until Giuliani 
decides. 
</P>
<P>
	After the event, Mrs. Clinton went to Monroe College in the  
Bronx for a private meeting with county Democratic leaders, 
including Bronx Democratic Party Chairman Roberto Ramirez. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the day will be spent in closed meetings in  
Manhattan. She returns to Washington on Wednesday morning, said her 
spokesman, Howard Wolfson. 
</P>
<P>
	The Queens discussion is the last stop on the listening tour to  
be held this month. President Bill Clinton and Mrs. Clinton are 
scheduled to begin a 16-day vacation next Thursday that will 
include stops in Massachusetts and upstate New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady said last week she planned to extend her  
statewide listening tour -- a series of small, controlled 
discussions in various venues -- into the fall. She said the tours 
would help her decide whether to run for the seat being vacated by 
retiring U.S. Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
