<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pavarotti Anticipating Eclipse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- Luciano Pavarotti was anticipating the  
solar eclipse with ``deep emotion,'' but says he's not the 
superstitious type. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if Nostradamus predicted the end of the world, I don't  
think it's going to happen,'' he said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists and tourists have flocked to Romania to view the  
celestial event, expected by NASA to be visible in this country for 
2 minutes and 23 seconds, longer than anywhere else in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	After today's eclipse, the singer was to perform an open-air  
concert in the shadow of the hulking, white palace built by late 
Communist dictator Nicolae Ceausescu. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
