<DOCNO> APW19990810.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 08:36:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Taiwan Eyes Chinese Jets in Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Two Chinese warplanes crossed into  
Taiwan's military airspace over the Taiwan Strait, the island's 
president said today, adding that the incursions were apparently 
accidental. 
</P>
<P>
	After repeatedly denying that Chinese aircraft had entered  
Taiwanese airspace, the Defense Ministry also confirmed that China 
passed over the ``center line'' twice last month. The line is 
generally respected by both sides as the limit of their military 
activity. 
</P>
<P>
	``They came over the center line, which is pretty unclear,  
probably because their planes were flying too fast,'' President Lee 
Teng-hui said at a government seminar. 
</P>
<P>
	As soon as the Chinese pilots realized where they were, ``they  
took off as fast as they could,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A pair of Shenyang J-8 fighters flew three miles into the Taiwan  
side on July 25, and a pair of J-7 fighters crossed six miles over 
the center line on July 30, the ministry said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Ministry officials had denied the crossings as recently as  
earlier today, and said in the statement that it had done so 
because they were considered mistakes without offensive intent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Had the Defense Ministry not taken the background into  
consideration, and simply announced this, it might have created 
doubts and insecurity among the public,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Announcement of the crossings comes amid tensions between  
Beijing and Taipei that have risen to their highest level in years, 
causing international concern over the possibility of a 
confrontation. 
</P>
<P>
	China's anger was sparked on July 9, when Lee said Beijing must  
deal with Taiwan on a ``state-to-state'' basis, a declaration the 
mainland viewed as a major step toward declaring formal 
independence -- which China says could trigger a war. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, officials in Beijing issued no immediate response to the  
president's comments about Chinese planes entering Taiwan's 
airspace. 
</P>
<P>
	Although China has increased training flights in recent weeks,  
its warplanes fly in a mostly north-south direction -- along the 
mainland Chinese coast and not toward Taiwan, said Chung Shen-ning, 
a military data analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung said no military aircraft have crossed east of the center  
line in the Taiwan Strait -- an average of 124 miles wide. 
</P>
<P>
	But China's most advanced Russian-made Sukhoi-27 fighters have  
recently begun flying sorties over the coast of Fujian province -- 
right across the water from Taiwan. Taiwan says China has about 100 
warplanes within a 286-mile range of the island. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan has reportedly stepped-up sorties of its French-made  
Mirage 2000-5 interceptors and other warplanes in response, 
although defense officials declined in a news conference to comment 
in detail on Taiwan's military activity. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taiwanese military was less shy about voicing its views on  
Hong Kong's press, which has rolled out dozens of unconfirmed 
stories about Chinese war preparations over the past month. 
</P>
<P>
	China is selectively leaking material to Hong Kong journalists  
to spread military rumors, with stories that often are accompanied 
by old file photos of Chinese military hardware to increase the 
scare effect, said Hu Yuan-chieh, of the military general 
headquarters' office of intelligence. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan's stock market has fallen sharply on such rumors. Taipei  
blue chips rose about 3.4 percent today, but they remain off by 
almost 15 percent since the crisis began. 
</P>
<P>
	Though divided politically since 1949, China still considers  
Taiwan a breakaway province to be brought into the fold eventually. 
</P>
<P>
	Also today, a bipartisan delegation visiting from the United  
States issued a statement supporting Lee and saying China bears 
full responsibility for creating tensions. The Clinton 
administration, however, has rebuked Lee for challenging the status 
quo. 
</P>
<P>
	``We strongly support President Lee's right to address Taipei's  
views,'' said U.S. Rep. Benjamin Gilman, chairman of House of 
Representative's committee on international relations. ``It is our 
view that the two sides should engage in a dialogue with equals.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 08:36:09 </DATE_TIME>
