<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 16:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Olympian Faces Criminal Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A bobsledder who represented Puerto Rico in  
the last three Olympics and whose optometrist license was revoked 
last year was indicted on insurance fraud charges Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. John C. Amabile, 37, is accused of cheating 29 insurance  
carriers of more than $200,000 by submitting false claims. The 
indictment charged he directed his staff to create 997 false 
patient records and charts so he could bill the carriers for 
services not rendered, or for treatment and tests for conditions 
that the patients did not have. 
</P>
<P>
	Amabile competed in the two-man bobsled in last three Winter  
Olympics. His sled finished 38th of 39 teams in 1998 at Nagano, 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Amabile, of Spring Lake Heights, faces six counts, including  
conspiracy, theft and falsifying records from January 1994 and July 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges carry up to 16 years in prison and $190,000 in  
fines. They were handed up by a state grand jury in Trenton and are 
to be tried in Freehold, Monmouth County. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the conspiracy, Amabile provided glasses and exams at  
little or no cost to attract large numbers of patients, according 
to the indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	In September, state regulators revoked his license after  
determining he cheated insurers of about a half-million dollars, 
and ordered him to pay more than $1.7 million in penalties, 
restitution and costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The payment was stayed pending an ongoing criminal  
investigation, so no money is due until these charges are resolved. 
The state froze $2 million of his assets in 1996, and those funds 
remain under court control. 
</P>
<P>
	Amabile had offices in Long Branch and Neptune City in Monmouth  
County, and Toms River in Ocean County. The criminal charges relate 
only to the Monmouth County offices, which accounts for some of the 
difference in the fraud figures, said Edward M. Neafsey, state 
insurance fraud prosecutor. 
</P>
<P>
	Criminal authorities also wanted to focus on allegations in  
which the evidence was strongest, Neafsey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Usually, criminal charges go first, but the licensing action -- a  
faster procedure -- went first ``because of the egregious nature of 
the conduct and the need to protect the public,'' Neafsey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Amabile was sued by the state in June 1997. The board suspended  
his license the next month, but later allowed him to resume 
practicing under a board-appointed supervisor. 
</P>
<P>
	His license was again suspended in January when the board  
determined Amabile severed his relationship with the supervisor. 
</P>
<P>
	Amabile and his last lawyer could not be reached for comment  
because neither had a current phone listing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 15:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Int'l Aluminum Cos. Talk Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- Three international aluminum  
companies with combined 1998 sales $25 billion are engaged in 
merger talks that could create the world's biggest aluminum 
concern. 
</P>
<P>
	Zurich-based Alusuisse-Lonza (Algroup), Pechiney of France and  
Alcan Aluminium of Canada all said they were in ``advanced 
discussions'' over a possible combination. The resulting company 
would be the world's largest, leapfrogging the Pittsburgh-based 
Alcoa, which had $15.3 billion in revenue in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger will likely face regulatory hurdles if it moves  
ahead, but analysts said they don't believe the company would be 
able to control the aluminum market. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Alcoa hasn't been able to dictate the price until now I  
can't see that the merged company would,'' said Christian George, 
equity analyst with Credit Lyonnais Rouse in London. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a strategic alliance which will bring about a  
reorganization of the aluminum industry,'' said Lawrence Eagles, 
head of research at London-based Gerard National Inter Commodities. 
``There will be huge benefits from a production perspective. I 
don't think this is about creating a cartel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last November, Algroup announced it was discussing a possible  
merger with the German industrial concern Viag. The talks came to 
an acrimonious end in March following a disagreement over a share 
swap arrangement. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada's Alcan is the world's second-largest producer of  
aluminum. It recorded sales of $7.8 billion last year. Pechiney, 
based in Paris, is the world's No. 4, with 1998 sales of $10.9 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Algroup, which nearly went broke in the 1980s after a series of  
disastrous forays into the United States, recorded sales of $6.4 
billion in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	If the merger goes through, the three companies would have a  
combined work force of more than 100,000. The combined company also 
would have a large packaging business. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 08:04:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Actor Victor Mature Dies at 86 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RANCHO SANTA FE, Calif. (AP) -- Victor Mature liked to joke that  
he once tried to get into a country club that didn't accept actors 
by saying, ``Hell, I'm no actor, and I've got 28 pictures and a 
scrapbook of reviews to prove it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the brawny actor given the nickname ``beautiful hunk of  
man'' also took his job seriously. ``I just couldn't show it,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mature died at the age of 86 after suffering from cancer for  
three years, said a friend, Zollie Volchok. The San Diego County 
coroner's office said it was notified that Mature died Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tall, dark-haired and muscular, Mature got his nickname from  
films like ``Samson and Delilah,'' ``One Million B.C.'' and ``Song 
of the Islands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He appeared in musicals, Westerns, comedies, historical epics  
and melodramas before largely retiring from films around 1960. 
</P>
<P>
	While first making his name as a glamour-boy star with a  
devil-may-care attitude, he gradually gained more critical respect 
in the late 1940s in such films as ``Cry of the City'' and ``Kiss 
of Death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1946's ``My Darling Clementine,'' he was Doc Holliday to  
Henry Fonda's Wyatt Earp. The version of the fabled gunfight at the 
O.K. Corral is considered one of director John Ford's greatest 
films. 
</P>
<P>
	Cecil B. DeMille's 1949 telling of the saga of Samson and  
Delilah cast Mature and Hedy Lamarr in the title roles. It was a 
smash hit. 
</P>
<P>
	He was at 20th Century Fox for many years but often worked at  
other studios. ``They turned pictures out like crackerjack,'' he 
told The New York Times in 1971. ```Kiss of Death' got made because 
Fox was one black-and-white picture short on its schedule.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That 1947 film paired Mature with a screen newcomer, Richard  
Widmark. Mature played a thief who turned state's evidence, Widmark 
a psychopathic killer. The film caused a sensation and earned 
Widmark an Academy Award nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Mature's other films: ``The Shanghai Gesture,'' 1941,  
directed by Josef von Sternberg; ``My Gal Sal,'' 1942, with Rita 
Hayworth; ``I Wake Up Screaming,'' 1941, with Betty Grable; 
``Wabash Avenue,'' 1950, with Grable; ``The Robe,'' 1953, as the 
slave Demetrius; a sequel, ``Demetrius and the Gladiators, 1954; 
and ``Chief Crazy Horse,'' 1954, with Mature in the title role. 
</P>
<P>
	Mature was a favorite of reporters during his heyday, always  
available for interviews. He enjoyed deflating the pomposities of 
Hollywood as well as his own image. 
</P>
<P>
	One of his favorite stories concerned the making of ``Samson and  
Delilah.'' DeMille wanted him to wrestle with a tame lion for a 
crucial action scene. The actor refused. ``But Jackie never hurt 
anyone; he doesn't even have any teeth,'' DeMille argued. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah?'' Mature replied. ``I don't want to be gummed to death,  
either.'' A stunt man tussled with Jackie, and Mature did his 
closeups with a lion skin. 
</P>
<P>
	Careful with his money unless a friend was in need, he invested  
in real estate and retail stores, enabling him to retire 
comfortably before he reached 45. He moved to Rancho Santa Fe, and 
once bragged that he played golf four hours a day, six days a week. 
</P>
<P>
	He made only a few film appearances in the past 35 years,  
notably the 1966 Italian farce ``After the Fox,'' in which he 
spoofed his old image; and ``Every Little Crook and Nanny,'' a 1972 
comedy in which he co-starred with Lynn Redgrave. In 1984 he made a 
rare appearance on television, playing Samson's father in a new 
version of ``Samson and Delilah.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mature was born Jan. 29, 1913 -- some references say 1915 and  
1916 -- in Louisville, Ky., the son of an Austrian immigrant who 
became a successful businessman. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming to California in the mid-'30s, he studied at the Pasadena  
Playhouse, paying his way with odd jobs because he didn't want to 
rely on his father. He made his screen debut with a small role in 
``The Housekeeper's Daughter,'' 1939. 
</P>
<P>
	At the height of his stardom, Mature dated stars such as  
Hayworth and Lana Turner. 
</P>
<P>
	He was married five times. Survivors include his wife, Lorey, a  
former Chicago opera singer, and their daughter, Victoria. 
</P>
<P>
	A funeral service was to be held today in Louisville.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 12:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Figures on Registration, Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some figures on registration and the draft:  
</P>
<P>
	Number of men, 18 to 25, currently registered: 13.5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Number of men drafted into the military for major 20th-century  
conflicts: 
</P>
<P>
	--World War I (1917-1918) -- 2,666,867.  
</P>
<P>
	--World War II (1940-1946) -- 10,110,114.  
</P>
<P>
	--Korea (June 1950-June 1953) -- 1,529,537.  
</P>
<P>
	--Vietnam (August 1964- February 1973) -- 1,766,910.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
