<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Racing Promoters Expanding, Aligning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Buoyed by success at one of its tracks, a  
top promoter in Winston Cup racing is expanding its involvement 
with the World of Outlaws. 
</P>
<P>
	Speedway Motorsports Inc. unveiled plans Tuesday to hold World  
of Outlaws races at three of its Winston Cup venues next year, with 
a fourth track possible in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	The multiyear agreement calls for the races to be televised by  
The Nashville Network and to be run as support events on weekends 
that the Winston Cup series is at the SMI tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	Concord-based SMI is building dirt tracks of about four-tenths  
of a mile in length at its flagship property, Lowe's Motor Speedway 
at Charlotte, as well as at Texas Motor Speedway near Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	The company already has a half-mile dirt track at Las Vegas  
Motor Speedway and is considering building one at Atlanta Motor 
Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	SMI president H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler said the company decided to  
expand its World of Outlaws ties after two 1998 races at Las Vegas 
sold out the 12,000-seat facility for the winged sprint cars. 
</P>
<P>
	``Las Vegas certainly got our attention,'' said Wheeler, whose  
company stages nearly one-third of the races on the Winston Cup 
circuit. ``I've always been an advocate of doing a bunch of things 
to keep things going, and this is just another example of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deal calls for the SMI tracks to stage World of Outlaws  
events on Thursday and Friday nights, leaving Saturdays free for 
Grand National races and Sundays open for the main Winston Cup 
events. 
</P>
<P>
	The World of Outlaws tracks at Charlotte and Texas would  
initially seat 12,000-15,000 and cost an estimated $3 million 
apiece. Each track is being designed so it could be expanded to 
55,000 seats. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheeler said SMI hopes to generate $1 million in income next  
year alone from World of Outlaws and related events at its dirt 
tracks in Charlotte, Dallas and Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	SMI officials view the World of Outlaws as a potentially more  
reliable revenue source than the 3-year-old Indy Racing League, 
which has struggled to draw consistent crowds at company 
facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	The only SMI track that has been able to annually draw IRL  
crowds in excess of 50,000 is Texas, where IRL ticket sales are 
tied to those for the track's Winston Cup weekends. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta, Charlotte and Las Vegas have had difficulty making  
money on IRL events, and SMI is considering dropping the series at 
Charlotte, where three spectators were killed during the circuit's 
race in May. 
</P>
<P>
	While the World of Outlaws deal could prove to be a good fit for  
SMI, the sprint-car series also hopes to profit from the alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	The World of Outlaws has developed into one of the  
fastest-growing circuits in racing, but its 60-stop-per-year 
schedule remains rooted mainly in the Midwest. New races in other 
areas of the country as well as added television exposure could 
further increase the circuit's fan base. 
</P>
<P>
	``This takes us to major market areas,'' World of Outlaws  
president and founder Ted Johnson said. ``With Speedway Motorsports 
building new facilities to accommodate us, we'll go to a new 
plateau.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 18:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Alabama Great Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOBILE, Ala. (AP) -- Riley Smith, who quarterbacked Alabama to a  
national championship in 1934, died Monday after a lengthy illness. 
He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith converted from fullback after the 1933 season and  
quarterbacked the Crimson Tide the next two seasons, earning 
All-America honors. 
</P>
<P>
	He won the Jacobs Award, given annually to the Southeastern  
Conference's top blocker, and is still regarded as one of the best 
blockers in school history. 
</P>
<P>
	He came back from an injury to lead the Tide to impressive  
victories over Georgia and Tennessee as a senior. Against 
Tennessee, he rushed for one touchdown and passed for one. 
</P>
<P>
	A quarterback on offense, safety on defense, punter and  
field-goal kicker, Smith was a member of the National Collegiate 
Football Hall of Fame, National Football Foundation Hall of Fame, 
Alabama Sports Hall of Fame, Mississippi Sports Hall of Fame and 
Mobile Sports Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, who was from Columbus, Miss., was a good friend and  
teammate of the late Alabama coach Bear Bryant. Bryant was also a 
member of that 1934 team which won the national championship with a 
Rose Bowl victory over Stanford. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coach Bryant and Daddy would talk weekly when Bear was  
coaching and winning national titles at Bama, and he would always 
tell Bear that he wasn't throwing the ball enough,'' said Riley 
Boykin Smith, his surviving son who is commissioner of the state 
Department of Conservation and Natural Resources. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Smith spent some three years in the NFL, but his  
career was cut short by a leg injury. 
</P>
<P>
	After leaving the Redskins, he became coach at Washington &AMP; Lee.  
He left coaching for World War II and eventually settled in Mobile, 
where he worked in real estate. 
</P>
<P>
	Services will be held at 11 a.m. Friday in the chapel of Radney  
Funeral Home in Mobile. Burial will follow in Pine Crest Cemetery. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his son, survivors include daughters Ocllo Smith  
Malone of Birmingham and Sandra Smith Norton of Jackson, Miss.; one 
sister; nine grandchildren and 12 great-grandchildren. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
