<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Smits To Return Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Rik Smits, the starting center for the  
Indiana Pacers who considered retiring from the NBA because of 
chronic foot pain, has decided to return next season, a newspaper 
reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Smits, who said he was leaning toward retirement after losing to  
the New York Knicks in Game 6 of the 1999 Eastern Conference 
finals, told The Indianapolis Star that he will play for a 12th 
season because his feet haven't been hurting lately. 
</P>
<P>
	``The feet are feeling pretty good, and I did some thinking,''  
Smits said from his offseason home in Walton, N.Y. ``I'm going to 
give it a try.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smits averaged 14.9 points last season, his lowest since  
1992-93. By season's end he said he had grown tired of coping with 
the foot pain that has dogged him for four years. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the first time ever, I really didn't enjoy playing this  
season,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Smits, who played 49 games during last year's condensed  
50-game season, told the newspaper he felt obligated to fulfill the 
final year of his contract, which will pay him $12.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have that feeling now,'' he said. ``If I go back, I'm going  
back to play, not to watch other people play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 32-year-old Smits also said he would consider extending his  
term with the Pacers, depending on how things go. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to say this is my last year, but who can say?'' he  
said. ``I'm just going to concentrate on this year for now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Over the last two weeks, the 7-foot-4 center has been undergoing  
treatments with Boston orthopedic therapist Dan Dyrek. At least two 
more sessions with Dyrek have been planned to relieve any lingering 
pain in his size 21 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, they'll feel better than last year,'' Smits said.  
``I was really disappointed a lot of times last year. I lost my 
explosiveness and my balance and it was hard to be effective. 
Hopefully, I'll get that back this year.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
