<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Campaign Nixes 411 Calls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- George W. Bush is sitting on a massive  
war chest but his campaign is still pinching pennies, directing 
employees nationwide to lay off the 411 calls and use free 
directory-assistance Internet sites instead. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential front-runner's campaign sent an  
e-mail memo on the matter to staffers across the country Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have been informed that there are Internet sites that allow  
you to look up a person's phone number or address FOR FREE,'' 
stated the memo, written by campaign office manager Julie Thomas. 
``Please try to use them rather than spending money on directory 
assistance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Bush's fund-raising dwarfs that of all other presidential  
candidates, the Texas governor has earned a reputation for thrift. 
Many presidential candidates serve lavish meals at donor 
gatherings, but Bush, who raised $37 million in the first half of 
the year, often hands out peanuts and pretzels. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas, who sent the memo from the campaign's Austin, Texas  
headquarters, declined to comment on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just a suggestion to save the campaign money,''  
campaign spokesman Scott McClellan said Tuesday. ``We try to run an 
efficient operation here at the campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McClellan confirmed that campaign staffers nationwide received  
it, but said he wasn't sure whether they had been running up big 
411 bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Bush campaign employees received the memo early this week.  
</P>
<P>
	``We were all cracking up laughing,'' said one Bush staffer in  
California who received the memo and spoke about it on condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why his burn rate is so much lower,'' the employee  
joked, referring to the slow rate at which Bush uses campaign 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush reported last month that he had $30 million in the bank,  
triple that of Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential 
front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's campaign collected $31 for every $1 it spent on  
fund-raising in the first half of the year. The Gore campaign took 
in $6 for every $1 it spent to raise money. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
