<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minorities Can Join U. Michigan Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Supporters of affirmative action won a court  
ruling Tuesday allowing them to argue in possibly precedent-setting 
lawsuits why the University of Michigan should consider race when 
picking its students. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2-1 ruling from a federal appeals court came in class-action  
lawsuits filed by three white applicants turned down by Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Cincinnati said lower  
federal courts erred when they barred 58 individuals -- most of whom 
are minority students at Michigan -- and four groups from joining 
the school in defending the lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the minorities say they want to raise questions that  
Michigan won't. The lawyers say they would argue that the 
university discriminated against minorities in the past, and that 
the administration relies on racially biased standardized tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan had welcomed the minority students' entrance into the  
lawsuits, but lawyers for the white students had fought against it, 
saying the groups would raise too many outside issues and delay 
trials scheduled for the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court's opinion said the groups met the legal burden  
for joining the case as defendants, and could be harmed if Michigan 
loses. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is little room for doubt that access to the University  
for African-American and Latino/a students will be impaired to some 
extent and that a substantial decline in the enrollment of these 
students may well result if the University is precluded from 
considering race as a factor in admissions,'' the court said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a tremendous and historic victory,'' said Miranda K.S.  
Massie, an attorney who represented some of the minority students. 
``It means that black and other minority students will be able to 
bring to bear the truths about racism in higher education to the 
affirmative action debate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuits could change the way public universities attempt to  
lure minority students. 
</P>
<P>
	The three white applicants claim Michigan's affirmative action  
admissions policies discriminated against them in favor of certain 
minorities. They say they were denied admission even though the 
university admitted minorities with lower grades and test scores. 
</P>
<P>
	The Center for Individual Rights, a Washington-based  
organization guiding the lawsuits, argues the university's 
enrollment procedures violate the Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	The university says it fairly uses race in admissions to create  
a diverse student body. It has also said that if it could not use 
race, the minority student population would plunge. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is being closely watched by educational groups, many of  
which have filed briefs in support of Michigan. The Clinton 
administration has also filed in support of the university. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirk Kolbo, an attorney for the Center for Individual Rights,  
said the ruling would not be appealed. Lawyers for all the parties 
said the trials would be pushed back. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
