<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weather Hampers Texas Vintners / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- The vintners growing grapes for Texas wines  
are grappling with the consequences of erratic spring weather. 
</P>
<P>
	An unseasonable chill in April led to a freeze in Fredericksburg  
that reduced the region's grape crop, said George McEachern of the 
Texas Agricultural Extension Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Early hailstorms in Lubbock, home of the Llano Estacado winery,  
damaged some vines and wiped out others. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been one of the strangest weather years we've had,''  
Chad Auler, vice president of Fall Creek Vineyards in Austin, said. 
``Quantity is a little light.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas, the nation's fifth-largest wine making state, produced  
1.3 million gallons of wine in 1998 in its 27 wineries, according 
to the Texas Wine Marketing Research Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	The state's production has grown 20 percent in the past decade.  
</P>
<P>
	This year, excellent yields in southwest Texas are compensating  
for crop shortfalls from the Lubbock hailstorms and early Hill 
Country freezes, according to the institute. 
</P>
<P>
	In some cases, early season anomalies may have been a blessing.  
</P>
<P>
	Although grapevines thrive in warm weather, McEachern said  
periods of intense heat -- as in 1996 and 1998 -- can impede 
photosynthesis, the process by which plants produce food. 
</P>
<P>
	And while storms ruined some grapevines this year, he said the  
overall quality of the fruit improves when the crop's quantity is 
cut. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need leaves to feed the (grape) clusters, but there's  
usually too many clusters for the number of leaves,'' McEachern 
said. ``When things like weather reduce the number of clusters, we 
can anticipate a higher quality fruit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fall Creek, the state's third-largest winery, still expects to  
squeeze 35,000 cases from its 1999 grape yield despite the fact 
that the weather cut its crop size, Auler said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SHELDON, Ill. (AP) -- The costly and damaging western corn  
rootworm is amazing scientists with its resiliency. 
</P>
<P>
	The rootworm has managed to survive despite a 3-year experiment  
in which researchers tried to lure the pests to fields sprayed with 
an attractant laced with a little insecticide. 
</P>
<P>
	Entomologists from the University of Illinois and Purdue  
University have been working on the U.S. Department of Agriculture 
project at dozens of farms near this tiny Iroquois County 
community, about 58 miles northeast of Champaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The fields were sprayed with a material that contained  
insecticide and also chemicals that attract the beetles, slow them 
down and stimulate feeding. 
</P>
<P>
	It was designed to kill female beetles before they laid their  
eggs -- instead of killing larvae, like most soil-applied 
insecticides. The material also used about 1/16 of the amount of 
active ingredient found in regular soil-applied insecticide. 
Scientists want to reduce chemicals used for farming. 
</P>
<P>
	``By year three, we should begin to see beetles at low levels,''  
UI entomologist Mike Gray said. ``By now, we'd hoped to walk into 
fields and find low densities, but we're not finding them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gray said results of the experiment have been better in Kansas  
and Texas, but Iowa scientists' results are similar to those in 
Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	Western corn rootworms confounded the scientific community a few  
years ago by adapting to crop rotation, which had been used to keep 
them in check. Rootworms started laying their eggs in soybean 
fields that would be planted with corn the next year. When larvae 
hatched, they tunneled around looking for corn roots to eat. 
</P>
<P>
	When the larvae have done a lot of root feeding, corn plants  
tend to fall over in the field. That causes harvest trouble and 
yield losses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
