<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Govs. Want To Safeguard State Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The nation's governors told Congress on Tuesday  
that state treasuries should not be raided to pay for federal tax 
cuts, closing a four-day meeting that found Republican governors 
seeking more control over the GOP political agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Governors' Association also voted unanimously to  
urge President Clinton and Washington lawmakers to move quickly to 
aid struggling farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	A resolution approved without debate said Congress must maintain  
the ``fiscal integrity'' of its relationship with governors by 
funding welfare and other social programs at levels promised by the 
lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure grew out of concerns expressed by Republican and  
Democratic governors with the GOP-led Congress' tax cut plan. 
Republican governors support tax cuts, but strongly objected to 
reports that congressional leaders wanted to use state welfare 
money to help pay for the $792 billion package. 
</P>
<P>
	They also expressed concern that Congress may be tempted to use  
the money to help keep the federal budget within spending caps. 
</P>
<P>
	``A deal is a deal,'' said Massachusets Gov. Paul Cellucci, a  
Republican who is pushing tax cuts in his own state. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma promised governors  
Sunday that the leadership would not seek the state money. Though 
the governors are still unsure of the House leadership's plans, 
their anger ebbed after Nickles' remarks; confrontational language 
was edited out of drafts of the resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	Without explicitly mentioning tax cuts, the resolution says  
governors are ``deeply concerned about the potential impact that 
proposed cuts would have on states' ability to provide key human 
services.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic aides said the word ``cuts'' referred to the tax  
plan. Republican aides said it referred to possible program cuts, 
not the tax-cut package. 
</P>
<P>
	The tax debate was part of a broader effort by GOP governors to  
seize more control over the party's national agenda. In private 
meetings, they discussed using their influence to put like-minded 
Republicans on the committee that will write the party's platform 
in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	With a fellow governor, George W. Bush of Texas, emerging as the  
leading Republican presidential candidate, the state leaders want 
the platform to reflect their pragmatic approach to governing. They 
feel past party statements, written for the social conservative 
wing of the party, have appeared too extreme or irrelevant. 
</P>
<P>
	A Republican governor will chair the party platform committee.  
Michigan Gov. John Engler is said to be top candidate for the post. 
</P>
<P>
	The governors also want to begin fashioning an agenda for the  
first hundred days of the next presidency, assuming the next 
president is a Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican governors are meeting with party leaders this  
fall to discuss ways they can have greater input on the party's 
election-year strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	Another NGA resolution said farmers and ranchers were fighting  
against a glut of crops, unstable markets and drought. ``Given the 
current situation, the nation's governors call on the U.S. Congress 
and the president to work together to immediately address the 
crisis facing the farmers and ranchers,'' read the resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure was not on the NGA agenda when state leaders  
gathered Saturday, but Democratic Gov. Tom Vilsack of Iowa pressed 
the issue in behind-the-scenes meetings with lawmakers from both 
parties. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution was already certain of approval today when  
Vilsack read a letter written by an Iowa farmer to his family 
shortly before killing himself. The farmer, who Vilsack did not 
identify, was distraught over financial problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just so tired of fighting this game because it's a losing  
battle,'' Vilsack read from the letter, his voice choking. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
