<HEADLINE> Dow Drops 57; Nasdaq Falls 61 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks extended their losses today as investors  
remained unsettled by growing expectations that the Federal Reserve 
will raise interest rates at least once more this year. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 57.94 at 10,649.76. The blue-chip index was down more than 100 
points for much of the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also off. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was down 21.62 at 1,276.18, and the Nasdaq composite 
index was down 61.57 at 2,457.41. With today's loss, the S&AMP;P 500 is 
10 percent below its July 16 record close, and the Nasdaq is 14 
percent off the record set the same day. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street typically defines a drop of 10 percent from a market  
high as a correction. The Dow has held up slightly better as 
investors gravitate toward large, well-established names, but has 
dropped 5.4 percent from its record high. 
</P>
<P>
	The possibility of higher interest rates has kept the market on  
edge for the past two weeks. Hoping to keep inflation from creeping 
into the booming U.S. economy, the Fed is widely expected to raise 
short-term interest rates when its policy-making Federal Open 
Market Committee meets Aug. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher interest rates typically hurt stocks by cutting into  
corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent sessions, market players have begun to debate whether  
the Fed will raise rates in October as well, traders said. 
Increases in August and October would be the second and third of 
1999, undoing the three rate cuts imposed late last year as the Fed 
sought to keep the U.S. economy from being caught up in financial 
crises spreading through Asia, Russia and Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market always goes to extremes of fear and greed, and  
right now, fear is at an extreme,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, chief 
market strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the pressure on stocks, the threat of Fed action has  
also pushed long-term interest rates to the highest levels in 
almost two years. Today, the 30-year Treasury bond yielded 6.24 
percent, a level last seen in November 1997, compared to 6.23 
percent late Monday. The high yields on bonds are presenting an 
attractive, less volatile alternative to stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial services stocks, which are highly sensitive to  
interest-rate fluctuations, were mostly lower today. J.P. Morgan 
fell 4 7/16 to 120 1/2, contributing most to the Dow's decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucent was one of the steepest decliners in the S&AMP;P 500, losing  
1 15/16 to 61 11/16 after agreeing to buy International Network 
Services Inc. for about $3.7 billion. Shares of INS rose 2 13/16 to 
50 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucent's deal strengthens its competitive position against Cisco  
Systems, analysts said, and helped drag Cisco shares down 13/16 to 
59. Cisco was expected to report earnings after the close of 
trading today. 
</P>
<P>
	The market slump created a hostile environment for initial  
public offerings today. Shares of HotJobs.com, an online job-search 
firm, were priced at 8 and by midafternoon were trading at 7 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by nearly a 4-to-1 margin  
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 677.80 million 
shares in midafternoon, ahead of Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 7.50 at 602.96, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 11.83 at 766.04. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.76 to 419.13.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
