<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wal-Mart Earnings Rise 21 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BENTONVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Wal-Mart Stores Inc., the nation's  
largest retailer, reported a 21 percent increase in second-quarter 
earnings despite being hindered by a large court settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Net income for the quarter was $1.25 billion, or 28 cents per  
share, compared with $1.03 billion or 23 cents per share in the 
same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The quarter, which ended July 31, included a charge for a  
litigation settlement of approximately 3 cents per share. Without 
the charge, Wal-Mart's profits would have increased 35 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart announced in May that it had settled litigation with a  
Mexican grocery store chain. A jury in San Antonio had awarded 
Valores Corp. of Monterrey, Mexico, $624 million after concluding 
that Wal-Mart broke an agreement with the company. Wal-Mart and 
Valores settled for what Wal-Mart said was less than the jury 
award. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues rose 15 percent to $38.47 billion from $33.52 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	The company's Wal-Mart Stores segment, including Supercenters,  
had a pre-tax operating profit of $2.151 billion, compared to 
$1.787 billion for the same quarter last year, a 20 percent 
increase. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sam's Club segment recorded operating profit for the quarter  
of $190 million, an increase of 10 percent compared to the $173 
million for the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The international segment had a profit of $112 million for the  
most recent quarter compared with $124 million for the same quarter 
in the prior year. 
</P>
<P>
	As of July 31, the company had 1835 Wal-Mart stores, 622  
Supercenters, and 453 Sam's Club wholesale stores in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	Internationally, Wal-Mart operated 13 stores in Argentina, 14 in  
Brazil, 155 in Canada, 95 in Germany, 433 in Mexico, 15 in Puerto 
Rico, and 229 in the United Kingdom. The company has six stores in 
China and five in South Korea under joint venture agreements. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart has more than 1 million employees, including 815,000 in  
the United States and 220,000 internationally. 
</P>
<P>
	Net income for the first six months of the fiscal year increased  
27 percent to $2.36 billion or 53 cents per share, compared with 
$1.86 billion or 42 cents per share, for the same period last 
fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Wal-Mart rose $2.68 3/4 to $42.87 1/2 in trading on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 15:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybean Futures Boosted by Drought  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures rose to their highest levels  
since early May on the Chicago Board of Trade Tuesday as Midwest 
drought conditions lingered. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures also gained. On other markets, unleaded gasoline  
futures fell sharply, while natural gas rose. Pork futures also 
rose sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices for soybean futures climbed above $5 a bushel and corn  
futures also rose sharply amid reports of deteriorating crops, 
particularly in Illinois and Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Rainfall of less than .15-inch fell in areas of northern  
Illinois and Indiana Monday, while the rest of the Midwest also 
remained fairly dry. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers are expected to move through the Midwest late this week,  
leading to slight increase in soil moisture and some improvement in 
crop conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts did not expect the scattered rainfall, which was to  
be accompanied by warmer temperatures, to be enough to revive 
moisture-starved corn and soybean crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders also were responding to a U.S. Agriculture Department  
report released late Monday in which soybean crop ratings 
nationwide deteriorated last week -- from 57 percent to 54 percent 
in good to excellent condition. 
</P>
<P>
	More significantly, in Illinois -- the second-largest growing  
state behind Iowa -- only 48 percent of the crop was in good to 
excellent condition, while 17 percent in the crop was in poor to 
very poor condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn for December delivery rose 4 3/4 cents to $2.40 3/4 cents a  
bushel; November soybeans rose 5 1/2 cents to $4.93 1/2 cents a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Unleaded gasoline futures fell sharply on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange amid expectations U.S. inventories are on the 
rise as the peak demand season begins to wane, said Tim Evans, 
senior energy analyst at Pegasus Econometric Group. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, natural gas continued to gain on forecasts calling for  
a return of above-normal temperatures in key heating and cooling 
regions. Hotter temperatures force utilities to power up turbines 
to meet demand from consumers using air conditioners and fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants were expecting the American Gas Association  
this week to report that inventories are now in a year-over-year 
deficit because of the recent heat wave in the Northeast and 
Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	September crude oil futures rose 3 cents to $21.30 a barrel;  
September heating oil fell .11 cent to 55.10 cents a gallon; 
September unleaded gasoline fell 1.01 cents to 65.03 cents a 
gallon; September natural gas rose 2.7 cents to $2.748 per 1,000 
cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, pork bellies continued their climb on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, in part because of U.S. pork donations to 
Russia announced earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	February pork bellies rose 2.58 cents to 58.45 cents a pounds;  
October lean hogs rose 1.12 cents to 46.77 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
