<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sports Leaders Urge Minority Owners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Minorities have made inroads into professional  
sports leadership, but must ascend to the highest levels for true 
change to occur, three sports industry leaders said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, led by National League president Leonard Coleman,  
discussed professional sports as a pathway to power during the 
National Urban League's annual conference in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Also speaking were Michael Huyghue, senior vice president for  
football operations with the Jacksonville Jaguars, and Carl Poston, 
a Houston-based sports agent who represents several star athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been 52 years since Jackie Robinson broke in (to  
baseball) in 1947, and we're on the edge of a new millennium,'' 
said Coleman, the highest ranking black official of a major 
professional league. ``In baseball, have we made progress? The 
answer is yes. Have we made enough progress? The answer is an 
emphatic, `No.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Noting that in the past decade, the number of front-office jobs  
in professional baseball held by minorities has risen from 2 
percent to 21 percent, Coleman pointed out that only one black -- 
Bob Watson of the New York Yankees -- has held the position of 
general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Huyghue noted the disparity of minority athletes to leaders in  
pro football, where there are no minority owners and only three 
black coaches even though 70 percent of the league's players are 
minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am optimistic that in years to come, as I look around the  
NFL meeting rooms I sit in, I won't be the only dark face in the 
room,'' Huyghue said. 
</P>
<P>
	Major League Baseball Commissioner Bud Selig was scheduled to  
speak but was unable to attend, citing scheduling conflicts, Urban 
League spokeswoman Leslie Dunbar said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
