<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Israel-Syria Direct Talks Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy urged  
Syria on Tuesday to come forward to the negotiating table, saying 
the time is ripe for making peace in the Middle East. 
</P>
<P>
	Levy was in Jordan looking for King Abdullah II's help in  
jump-starting negotiations with Syria. Abdullah, whose country 
signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, has been working to help 
revive Syrian-Israeli peace negotiations that broke off in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Abdullah has been passing on peace messages between Israeli  
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian President Hafez Assad. He has 
even proposed Jordan as a venue for the negotiations, Arab 
diplomats said, speaking on customary condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-running conflict between Syria and Israel hinges on the  
Golan Heights. Syria demands that Israel return the strategic 
plateau, which it captured from Syria in the 1967 Mideast war. 
</P>
<P>
	Levy, speaking after his four-hour visit to Jordan, urged Assad  
to participate in direct talks instead of working through 
mediators. 
</P>
<P>
	Levy also said Israel is committed to implementing the Wye River  
accord with the Palestinians. The deal reached last fall includes 
Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the West Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	``I stress that we are committed to the implementation of Wye  
and we expect the other side to implement its side of the agreement 
because each side is dependent on the other,'' Levy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak's aides say he has asked the Palestinians to meet some of  
their security obligations -- such as confiscating illegal weapons 
and shrinking their police force -- before the first phase of troop 
withdrawal begins in October. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdul-Illah Khatib said other issues  
he and Levy discussed included easing Israeli barriers on trade 
with the West Bank, the fate of 17 Jordanian prisoners in Israel 
and sharing scarce water resources in a region battered by drought. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
