<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 18:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Issues Peacekeeper Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- For the first time, the United Nations  
laid out rules Tuesday regarding the conduct of U.N. peacekeepers, 
stating they must abide by the same international humanitarian laws 
that govern soldiers' actions. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary-General Kofi Annan issued an executive order to  
coincide with Thursday's commemoration of the 50th anniversary of 
the Geneva Conventions, which governs the regulations for 
international combat. 
</P>
<P>
	The order essentially puts on paper the principles U.N. force  
commanders have used for five decades -- that the landmark treaty's 
rules for combatants apply to U.N. peacekeepers involved in active 
fighting. They too must protect civilians, give humane treatment to 
prisoners, restrict their use of weapons and face prosecution in 
their homelands if they violate any of the rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. document gained momentum in the early 1990s, when U.N.  
peacekeepers in Somalia, Rwanda and Bosnia were increasingly drawn 
into conflicts in which they not only acted in self-defense but 
used force to do their jobs -- sometimes excessively. 
</P>
<P>
	During the U.N. mission in Somalia, for example, a handful of  
peacekeepers from Canada, Italy and Belgium were accused of 
committing atrocities against Somalis, including dangling a boy 
over an open fire and force-feeding pork to a Muslim Somali boy 
accused of stealing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very important to reaffirm on the 50th anniversary of the  
Geneva Conventions that the U.N. itself and U.N. soldiers are 
subject to the same rules as everyone else,'' said Reed Brody, 
advocacy director of Human Rights Watch in New York, who welcomed 
Annan's order. 
</P>
<P>
	As an international organization and not a state, the United  
Nations cannot sign onto the Geneva Conventions, making Annan's 
order the binding substitute. 
</P>
<P>
	The order only covers U.N. military operations and Security  
Council-authorized enforcement missions in which the United Nations 
commands the force, a senior U.N. official told reporters Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	It doesn't apply, for example, to the Security Council-endorsed  
peacekeeping mission in Kosovo because NATO -- not the United 
Nations -- commands the military personnel, the official said, 
speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The official acknowledged the United Nations had no way to  
compel national courts to prosecute the cases, but said the future 
International Criminal Court might have jurisdiction over 
peacekeepers who commit war crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Nordic and Latin American countries voiced philosophical  
problems with the document because it essentially equates U.N. 
peacekeepers with warriors in terms of their mutual rules of 
engagement, the U.N. official said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a cover letter, Annan acknowledged the controversy but said  
the order's ``promulgation and dissemination in times of peace will 
diminish the risk of violation in times of war.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 16:17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of America To Lend $3 billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Bank of America announced Tuesday it will fund an  
unprecedented $3 billion mortgage program for low- to 
moderate-income borrowers that promises no down payment, no 
application fee and no closing costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The national program will be overseen by Boston-based  
Neighborhood Assistance Corp. of America, led by self-described 
``urban terrorist'' Bruce Marks, who has a track record of getting 
loan commitments from banks after flagrantly accusing them of 
discriminatory lending practices. 
</P>
<P>
	``As cynical as I am that all bankers are evil, this is the  
exception to the rule,'' said Marks. 
</P>
<P>
	The friendly agreement, which the 44-year-old Marks estimates  
will affect 100,000 borrowers nationally, is a watershed for the 
community activist. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Marks and Bank of America say the bank voluntarily decided  
to make the mortgage commitment because it's good business. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not charity,'' said Robert Johnston, senior vice  
president for Bank of America's community development bank. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of cash transactions in the inner city,'' he  
said. ``We see a real value in lending in the inner city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, before NationsBank was acquired by Bank of America, it  
decided to lend $500 million in mortgages through Neighborhood 
Assistance Corp. over five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighborhood Assistance, which now has 20 offices nationwide,  
originated the loans with low-income first-time homeowners who were 
often distrustful of banks. The organization helped navigate the 
borrower through the confusing mortgage process and, most 
important, offered post-ownership assistance -- while NationsBank 
made money, said Johnston. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've always felt that Community Reinvestment Act lending was  
good business for banks,'' said Robert Garsson, spokesman for the 
federal Office of the Comptroller of the Currency. ``We've 
encouraged them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marks calls the program the biggest ever -- and a tremendous  
opportunity for working people who might not have the savings who 
need to buy a home. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a history of having to do whatever it takes to get  
lenders to the table,'' said Marks. ``Now we have lenders say, 
`This works.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of America's home mortgage product will be available  
immediately in Atlanta, Baltimore, Buffalo, N.Y., Charlotte, 
Jacksonville, Fla., Los Angeles, Memphis, Tenn., Washington, D.C., 
Dallas-Fort Worth, Houston, Oakland, Calif., Sacramento, Calif., 
San Antonio and Tampa, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Within the next 12 months, the program will be available in New  
York City, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Albuquerque, N. M., San Diego and 
Little Rock, Ark. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
