<HEADLINE> Swimmer Makes Comeback in 50-Meter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- After a year away from competition, Amy Van  
Dyken resumed her medal-filled career Tuesday by winning the 
50-meter freestyle on the final day of the National Swimming 
Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	And with Van Dyken cheering him on from the deck, Gary Hall Jr.  
completed his own comeback in the men's race. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Dyken, 26, finished the sprint in 25.13 seconds at the  
University of Minnesota Aquatic Center to earn her fourth national 
title. The Lone Tree, Colo., native hadn't competed in a national 
meet since the spring of 1998 after undergoing shoulder surgery. 
Van Dyken will resume her training regimen and continue 
rehabilitating her shoulder in lieu of traveling to Sydney, 
Australia for the Pan Pacific Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall, a three-time medalist in the 1996 Olympics, finished the  
50 in 22.13 to earn his fourth national championship. Hall, 24, was 
diagnosed with diabetes in March, missing the spring nationals, and 
was bedridden with the flu just five days ago. His time was fast 
enough to qualify for the Pan Pacific Games, but he wasn't sure 
whether he'd go. 
</P>
<P>
	Other titlists included Brooke Bennett, who won the women's  
1,500 freestyle in 16:14.77; Kristine Quance-Julian, who earned her 
10th national championship in the women's 200-meter individual 
medley (2:16.06); Tom Wilkens, who won the men's 200 IM in 2:02.03; 
and Chad Carvin, who won his 15th national title in the men's 
1,500-meter freestyle in 15:22.85. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
