<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 10, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Gunman Wounds Two at Jewish Center  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A gunman wounded five people, including a  
child, at a Jewish community center today. Dozens of police 
officers searched the complex for the shooter. Police described the 
gunman only as a male Hispanic. The shooting took place at the 
North Valley Jewish Community Center in the Granada Hills area of 
the San Fernando Valley shortly after the 10:50 a.m. PDT. A group 
of children were seen being led away on a nearby sidewalk. The 
center provides nursery programs, child care and camp activities. 

</P>
<P>
	Dutch Gov't Legalizes Mercy Killing  
</P>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- The Netherlands as soon as next  
year could become the first country to legalize mercy killing under 
a plan that would formalize practices already widely accepted and 
used. The Dutch government published plans today to legalize 
euthanasia under strict guidelines. Doctors judged not to have 
adhered to the guidelines would still face prosecution and a 
maximum 12-year jail term. The plans, which are expected to gain 
parliamentary approval next year, would allow children as young as 
12 to demand and receive euthanasia. Guidelines include making sure 
all other medical options are exhausted and a second opinion be 
sought. 

</P>
<P>
	Shatner's Wife Found Dead in Pool  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- William Shatner's wife was found dead in  
their swimming pool, an apparent drowning that authorities said 
they were treating as an accident. The distraught ``Star Trek'' 
star said she ``meant everything to me.'' Shatner said he found his 
wife, Nerine, 40, at the bottom of a swimming pool when he returned 
home last night. Shatner said he dialed 911, pulled his wife out of 
the pool and administered CPR, but his efforts to revive her and 
similar efforts by emergency personnel were unsuccessful. 

</P>
<P>
	250 Bodies Exhumed in Bosnia  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- Forensic experts,  
reconstructing a 1995 massacre in the Bosnian enclave of 
Srebrenica, have finished exhuming about 250 bodies from a mass 
grave, U.N. officials said today. Srebrenica was a Muslim enclave 
in northeast Bosnia. The United Nations declared it a ``safe 
heaven'' but did nothing to prevent Bosnian Serb forces from 
overrunning it in July 1995. The enclave's brutal fall left over 
7,000 Muslim men missing. The men are believed to have been 
systematically executed. Bosnian Serb leaders Radovan Karadzic and 
his war-time general Ratko Mladic were indicted for war crimes but 
are at large. 

</P>
<P>
	Rail Killing Suspect Indicted in Ky.  
</P>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Suspected railroad killer Angel Maturino  
Resendiz has been indicted in the murder of a University of 
Kentucky student, and now faces charges in seven slayings. Fayette 
County prosecutors said they will seek the death penalty for 
Resendiz, who was indicted in the 1997 slaying of Christopher 
Maier, 21, on railroad tracks near the Kentucky campus. Authorities 
have linked the rail-riding Mexican drifter, who went by the alias 
Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, to a total of nine slayings. 

</P>
<P>
	Census Plans Ads To Improve Count  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A major advertising campaign is being designed  
to help encourage participation in Census 2000, the program's 
director said today. The projected $166 million campaign will 
target the millions of people the agency historically has trouble 
counting, such as blacks, Hispanics and immigrants, Census Bureau 
Director Kenneth Prewitt said. Half the money will be used for ads 
in Spanish and other foreign languages. The bureau expects to get 
back about 61 percent of the census questionnaires that it plans to 
mail out next year. Enumerators will then be sent out into the 
streets to find those who did not return the forms. 

</P>
<P>
	Govs. Want To Safeguard State Money  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The nation's governors urged President Clinton  
and Congress today to move quickly to aid struggling farmers and 
voted unanimously to tell Congress not to raid state treasuries to 
cut federal taxes. A resolution unanimously approved by the state 
leaders said farmers and ranchers were fighting against a glut of 
crops, unstable markets and drought. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 102  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 102.90 to 10,604.80. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 2,516-553. The Nasdaq was down 48.81 to 
2,470.17. 

</P>
<P>
	Utah's Layden To Be GM of Knicks  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Scott Layden, whose personnel moves helped  
the Utah Jazz become an NBA contender in the 1990s, has accepted an 
offer to become general manager of the New York Knicks. News 
reports indicated Layden could earn about $1.5 million in New York, 
four times his Utah salary. The Knicks have been seeking a GM since 
firing Ernie Grunfeld in April. Knicks president Dave Checketts 
worked with Layden in Utah in the 1980s. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
