<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Retailers Settle Sweatshop Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Four prominent retailers will pay for  
independent monitoring of Saipan's garment industry as part of a 
settlement of a federal class-action lawsuit brought to prevent 
worker abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Nordstrom Inc., J. Crew Group Inc., Cutter &AMP; Buck Inc. and  
Gymboree Corp. agreed to the oversight of their contractors with 
factories in the U.S. territory in an effort to comply with 
American labor laws and international human rights treaties. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one wants to destroy the garment industry in Saipan, but it  
should not come at the price of indentured servitude,'' plaintiffs' 
attorney William Lerach said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Christina Snyder still must approve the  
settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Three lawsuits filed Jan. 13 described approximately 32  
contractors in Saipan as ``America's worst sweatshop'' where there 
were beatings, forced abortions, vermin-infested quarters, barbed 
wire and armed guards. Employees worked 12 hours a day, seven days 
a week, the suits claim. 
</P>
<P>
	Abuses in Saipan, a 13-mile-long Western Pacific island in the  
Northern Marianas, had been documented previously, but the lawsuits 
were the first legal attempt to hold U.S. retailers accountable for 
alleged mistreatment of workers by subcontractors under the federal 
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Clothing made in the Saipan factories are stamped with ``Made in  
the USA'' tags, making it appear it was made in compliance with 
U.S. labor laws, the suits alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the settlement call for the companies to establish a  
$1.25 million fund to finance the independent monitoring program, 
provide money to the workers, create a public education campaign 
and pay attorneys' fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Nordstrom co-president Erik Nordstrom called the deal ``a  
positive step toward our goal of ensuring that the goods we 
contract to manufacture in Saipan are made in compliance with 
law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Cutter &AMP; Buck chairman Harvey Jones said his company already  
closely monitors its Saipan contractors, and called the firm's 
decision to settle ``a business decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Statements released by J. Crew and Gymboree stressed the  
companies have not admitted wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys also filed a letter of agreement in principle to  
settle with Polo Ralph Lauren Corp., Phillips-Van Heusen Corp., 
Donna Karan International Inc. and Chadwick's of Boston Ltd., who 
were to be named as defendants. 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles on Monday, attorneys for the lawsuit's 13  
remaining defendants argued the case should be shifted to Saipan 
for jurisdictional reasons. No ruling was made. 
</P>
<P>
	A related federal suit filed in Saipan targeting overtime pay  
was dismissed by a judge on Friday, Lerach said. A third suit, 
filed at state court in San Francisco against 18 retailers, will 
also be settled, he said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 16:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Is Dangerous for Forests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW LISBON, N.J. (AP) -- From his 7-by-7-foot perch overlooking  
the piney wilderness, Sean Morgart can spot trouble 10 miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgart, who works for the New Jersey Forest Fire Service,  
spends his days atop a 100-foot tower in the heart of the state's 
million-acre Pinelands region, looking for smoke. When he sees a 
column rising from the trees, the first thing he notices is the 
color. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it comes up in a dark cloud with a lot of turmoil in the  
plume, you know you're in trouble,'' he said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	And Morgart has been seeing a lot more trouble this summer.  
</P>
<P>
	While the drought of 1999 has devastated Eastern farms --  
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman on Tuesday made farmers in New 
Jersey and parts of New York and Pennsylvania eligible for 
emergency loans -- the dry spell also is taking a severe toll in 
woodlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Forest fires are easier to ignite, burn hotter once they get  
started and are harder to extinguish. Three times as many wildfires 
as normal have been reported in New Jersey this year, and other 
states are facing similar threats. 
</P>
<P>
	--In Massachusetts, 5,000 acres have burned since April; in a  
typical year, 3,000 acres burn. 
</P>
<P>
	--New Hampshire officials have counted more than 1,245 wildfires  
this spring and summer, compared with 550 in a normal year. 
</P>
<P>
	--West Virginia has recorded more than 100 forest fires this  
summer, instead of the usual three or four. And autumn -- when dry, 
fallen leaves pose the biggest danger of fire -- is still ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Even places that have escaped major forest fires have had small  
underground fires that burn into the forest floor, where root 
systems are starved for water. Firefighters must continually check 
back on blazes that appear to have been extinguished. 
</P>
<P>
	``They follow the root systems and sometimes burn horizontally  
under the ground for days -- sometimes weeks -- before they resurface 
again,'' said Jim Downie, a forest ranger with the Maine Department 
of Conservation. 
</P>
<P>
	Fires can start with burning cigarette butts thrown from  
automobiles, lightning strikes, campfires, arson -- even tall grass 
ignited by an automobile's overheated catalytic converter. 
</P>
<P>
	While few of this summer's fires have caused significant  
property damage and no deaths have been reported, they are 
decimating trees and shrubs that -- in some places -- will never 
recover, according to botanist Bruce Stein of The Nature 
Conservancy, an Arlington, Va.-based group. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem in an extreme drought is that you can have fires  
that burn hotter than normal,'' Stein said. ``Where the forest 
might be adapted for low-intensity fires, a hotter-than-average 
fire can be more destructive than normal fires.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey and other states have imposed drought emergency  
restrictions, including a ban on outdoor fires. They hope that's 
enough, especially come fall, when the danger increases. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's so dry, anything can light a fire,'' Morgart said. ``The  
only thing left to do is to close the woods entirely.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
