<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IEA Foresees Tighter Oil Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Economic recovery in Asia and meager growth in  
world oil supplies are likely to cause the petroleum market to 
tighten, although revised estimates of global inventories have 
eased fears of an impending shortage, according to a closely 
watched industry survey. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Energy Agency said in a report released  
Tuesday that an unexpected increase of 54 million barrels in 
estimates of May oil inventories in the world's wealthiest 
countries offset much of the drawdown in stocks during the year's 
first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	If correct, the revision weakens the argument the agency made  
last month that the world faces an oil shortage this winter that 
could be its worst in more than a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The revised figures also could undermine the logic for the  
current strength in oil prices, which continued to rise in July. 
</P>
<P>
	The Paris-based IEA is part of the Organization for Economic  
Cooperation and Development, a group of the world's most developed 
nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The IEA report warned against overreaction to the inventory  
revisions, saying they might be readjusted downward somewhat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even so, the picture painted by the data is of a market still  
in transition from last year's massive glut to what looks to be a 
much tighter market next year,'' the study said. ``That tighter 
market may be farther down the road than had been perceived.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It said U.S. authorities recently added 19.5 million barrels to  
the country's inventories in a recalculation of May figures. 
European stocks were revised due to unexpected increases in 
inventories in Germany and some smaller countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, the IEA forecast that a gathering economic recovery  
among countries in East Asia, combined with a sluggish growth in 
oil output by non-OPEC producers, still will cause global demand to 
exceed supply by 1.4 million barrels per day in the third quarter 
of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The gap is expected to widen to 2.87 million barrels a day in  
the fourth quarter and 3.51 million barrels a day in the first 
quarter of the year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said members of the Organization of Petroleum  
Exporting Countries boosted production by 190,000 barrels per day 
in July but still achieved a 91 percent compliance rate with 
cutbacks they agreed upon in March. OPEC's revised compliance rate 
for June was 87 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The price for widely traded Brent crude has surged on OPEC's  
discipline in limiting output, rising 8 percent in July alone, the 
IEA noted. Brent was trading Tuesday at $20.26 per barrel on the 
spot market, more than $8 per barrel higher than a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	West Texas Intermediate crude climbed 3 percent last month and  
was trading Monday at $21.28 per barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	Some industry analysts suggest that prices may have peaked and  
could reverse course. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question that the oil price is out of line with the  
fundamentals. It's only a matter of time before there's some 
downward correction,'' said Charlie Sharp, an analyst with the 
London-based brokerage T. Hoare Canaccord. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC's biggest producer, Saudi Arabia, has said it wants Brent  
prices to stay within a range of $18 to $20 per barrel. If oil 
prices rise beyond their current levels, some OPEC members may be 
tempted to exceed production quotas to maximize their earnings. But 
gains would prove short-lived, as more abundant oil would depress 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher prices also would make it possible for non-OPEC suppliers  
with higher production costs to begin pumping crude of their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anyone seriously believes we're in for $20 per  
barrel next year,'' said Alan Sinclair, an analyst at Charterhouse 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Sinclair called the current price ``a spike'' and predicted that  
Brent would drift back down toward $16 per barrel, based on its 
level in previous years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0218 </DOCNO>
