<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Super Size Doesn't Mean Super Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Shoppers who believe they always get a  
better deal when they buy a bigger size may be getting fooled. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers from Purdue University presented a study Tuesday  
that found consumers often don't bother to compare per-ounce or 
per-unit prices -- and they may pay more because of it. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because of a retailing practice called ``surcharging,''  
where larger packages cost more per unit than smaller packages of 
the same product, said James Binkley, a professor of agricultural 
economics at Purdue. 
</P>
<P>
	Binkley and study co-author John Bejnarowicz, a Purdue graduate  
student and executive for AC Nielsen Research, studied canned tuna 
prices and found the larger the cans, the more expensive the tuna. 
They concentrated their study on tuna because it consistently has 
surcharges and the product sizes are easy to compare. 
</P>
<P>
	To illustrate their findings, Bejnarowicz bought tuna at a local  
Kroger supermarket: the 6-ounce can cost 89 cents; the 12-ounce can 
was $2.19 -- 41 cents more than two 6-ounce cans. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers say surcharges also often are found on toilet  
paper, coffee, dish detergent and ketchup. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Mullen, a spokesman for StarKist Seafood in Newport,  
Ky., said the company provides a recommended retail price, but the 
actual price generally is left to individual supermarkets. 
</P>
<P>
	He said 6-ounce cans of tuna are often used as ``loss leaders''  
-- items grocers are willing to lose money on to get a customer into 
the store to buy other products. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the practice of StarKist to surcharge our product,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ross Thomas, a spokesman for Cincinnati-based Kroger Co., said  
the 6-ounce can of tuna is the most popular promotional size and 
manufacturers tend to discount the price. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers used price data compiled by Selling Areas  
Marketing Inc. in 54 major metropolitan areas. They studied the 
52-week price average of three brands that share 90 percent of the 
tuna market: StarKist, Bumble Bee and Chicken of the Sea. 
</P>
<P>
	The study was presented at the American Agricultural Economics  
Association annual meeting in Nashville. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
