<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jets To Give Lucas a Chance at QB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- -- Two seasons ago, Jets coach Bill  
Parcells gambled on turning special-teams ace Ray Lucas into an NFL 
quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday at Green Bay, Parcells will see if his investment is  
working out. 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells said Tuesday that Lucas will receive a majority of the  
snaps when the Jets open their preseason schedule against the 
Packers. Starter Vinny Testaverde will begin the game, but won't 
play beyond the early part of the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's a good athlete,'' said Parcells, who signed Lucas  
for New England as an undrafted free agent from Rutgers in 1996. 
Lucas played quarterback in college, but has emerged as a 
special-teams star as a pro. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he wants to win games. I think he has no fear. I think  
he's an outstanding competitor. But this has been quite a long 
project to try to turn him into a professional quarterback. This is 
his time now. He knows it. We're going to see progress, or we're 
going to have to move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lucas, who turned 27 last week, was played at receiver and  
special teams during his one season at New England, competing in 
the postseason and Super Bowl that year. Once with the Jets, 
however, Parcells tinkered with switching Lucas to defense before 
settling on a move back to quarterback, utilizing the 6-3, 
214-pound speedster as a running threat behind center in occasional 
short-yardage situations. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, Lucas is battling another former Patriot, Scott  
Zolak, for a backup role to Testaverde. Former New England punter 
Tom Tupa, who like Zolak can be a backup quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've come from being a free agent to the practice squad to a  
defensive back to a wide receiver to just special teams, back to 
wide receiver to getting in and running the quarterback draw for 
positive yards,'' Lucas said. ``The next thing you know, I'm still 
playing special teams and last year I played eight snaps at 
quarterback. Now I'm here competing for the backup job to Vinny 
Testaverde. It's unbelievable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The roller coaster ride may come to a quick halt, however, if  
Lucas fares poorly this summer, particularly against Green Bay. He 
is 4-of-7 passing over the past two seasons for 56 yards and one 
interception. He has rushed for 88 yards on 13 attempts. In an 
intrasquad scrimmage on Saturday, Lucas looked solid. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pretty pleased with him,'' Parcells said, ``but doing a  
good job out there (on the practice field) and doing a good job in 
Green Bay is another thing. It's a hostile environment and I think 
this is a good place to let him try.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lucas already feels the pressure.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be sick about four or five times,'' he said. ``When I was  
at wide receiver, I'd be so excited before the game, I'd get 
physically sick.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
