<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Courts Face Vacancy Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Federal courts are experiencing a ``mounting  
vacancy crisis'' because Senate politics has slowed the 
confirmation of judicial nominees, President Clinton told the 
nation's largest lawyers' group. 
</P>
<P>
	``We simply cannot afford to allow political considerations to  
keep our courts vacant and to keep justice waiting,'' the president 
told the American Bar Association at its annual meeting Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the slow process of confirming judicial nominees  
was thwarting the administration of justice. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate confirmation process ``can be an unnecessarily long  
and grueling process that I believe serves neither the judiciary 
nor the nation,'' he said. ``Despite the high qualifications of my 
nominees, there is a mounting vacancy crisis in the courts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The worst effects of the slowdown are making themselves felt  
across our country,'' the president said. ``Exploding civil and 
criminal court dockets affect the lives of tens of thousands of 
Americans. They strain our justice system to the breaking point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton thanked Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch,  
R-Utah, for working with him to break a nomination logjam after the 
1996 presidential elections. 
</P>
<P>
	But this year, only 11 of the 61 federal judges Clinton has  
nominated have been confirmed by the Senate, and the slowdown was 
blamed in part on a standoff between Hatch and the administration 
over the senator's wish to see former aide Ted Stewart appointed to 
the bench in Utah. Clinton nominated Stewart last month. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Hatch sent a letter to Clinton saying the Judiciary  
Committee had been acting on judicial nominations ``in a balanced 
and thorough manner.'' However, he contended the president had not 
sent nominations and background material on the nominees to the 
committee as quickly as he might have. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch said the Senate's ``solemn responsibilities ... require  
that this committee review thoroughly the records of each nominee 
to ensure that he, or she, is capable and qualified to serve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The conservative Free Congress Foundation today said the  
confirmation of Clinton judicial nominees has proceeded at 
approximately the same pace as the confirmation of nominees by 
President Reagan. Clinton ``has absolutely nothing to complain 
about,'' said Thomas Jipping of the foundation's judicial selection 
project. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton touted the diversity of his judicial nominees, saying  
nearly half of them had been minorities or women. Two of his recent 
nominees would be the first black judges on the 4th and 9th Circuit 
federal appeals courts. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he would again ask the Senate to confirm Bill Lann  
Lee, the Justice Department's acting civil rights chief. Lee has 
faced stiff opposition from GOP senators over the issue of 
affirmation action. 
</P>
<P>
	After the president's speech, ABA President Philip Anderson told  
reporters, ``We are going into an election year and we can't afford 
to have ... our judicial system compromised by that many vacancies 
left unfilled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not fair to the system of justice, it's not fair to the  
litigants, it's not fair to the judges who are still there,'' 
Anderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ABA plays a role in the judicial nominating process. The  
organization's Standing Committee on the Federal Judiciary 
evaluates and reports on the professional qualifications of people 
being considered by the president for nomination to federal 
judgeships. The committee rates prospective judicial nominees as 
``well qualified,'' ``qualified'' or ``not qualified.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
