<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 17:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PGA Player Shun Ryder Cup Pay  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- No Ryder Cup pay. No Ryder Cup boycott. And  
after a one-hour meeting Tuesday afternoon among 16 top American 
players and Ryder Cup officials, there appears to be no problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talked enough to know that everyone is on the same page,''  
said Mark O'Meara, who triggered the pay-for-play issue last year 
when he raised questions about how much the PGA of America rakes in 
from the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	What emerged from the meeting was a pledge from the PGA of  
America to look into the channeling some of its net profit to 
charities of the players' choice. More importantly, players and PGA 
officials agreed that whatever controversy had been brewing over 
the past several months was now behind them. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to be talking to the players about the charitable  
contributions and what we can do that lets everybody feel good 
about our support of the game,'' said Jim Awtrey, chief executive 
officer of the PGA. 
</P>
<P>
	``The players right now are focused on the Ryder Cup, winning  
the Ryder Cup, and there is no issue between the PGA of American 
and players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't always the case.  
</P>
<P>
	O'Meara first raised questions about Ryder Cup money a year ago,  
when he complained about the corporate functions required during 
the matches and the amount of money made from them. Tiger Woods and 
David Duval also joined the fray, and Duval had the strongest 
comments of all. 
</P>
<P>
	The September issue of Golf Digest reported that the PGA of  
America would pull in $63 million in gross revenue from next 
month's matches at The Country Club in Brookline, Mass., with a net 
profit of $23 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same issue, Duval said that the Ryder Cup was  
``overcooked, but it's probably going to stay that way until 
players choose not to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Without the players, they're not going to have a Ryder Cup,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The prospect of a boycott -- Duval later said that's not what he  
meant -- threatened to divide a United States team that has lost 
five of the past seven Ryder Cup matches. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shouldn't get money every time we turn around,'' said Fred  
Couples, who has played on more Ryder Cup teams than any other 
active American. 
</P>
<P>
	Love earlier said whatever controversy existed had been blown  
out of proportion by the media. 
</P>
<P>
	``Keep asking questions, you're going to get a various bunch of  
answers,'' Love said. ``If you let it die, it will die.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just two hours before the meeting, Woods was resolute in his  
belief that players should be paid. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to see us receive whatever the amount is -- 200,  
300, 400, 500,000 dollars, whatever it is -- and I think we should 
be able to keep the money and do whatever we see fit,'' Woods said. 
``Personally, I would donate all of it to charity. But I think it's 
up to the other's person's discretion what they would do with it. 
</P>
<P>
	``With all the money that's being made, I think that we should  
have a say in where it goes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked to comment after the meeting, Woods said only that ``it  
went great. We had a wonderful time. I need to go play, boys,'' and 
then headed off to the first tee. 
</P>
<P>
	Duval said before the meeting that he wanted a situation similar  
to the Presidents Cup, in which players received $100,000 to donate 
to a charity of their choice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand the PGA of America does a lot of good stuff. I  
grew up in it,'' said Duval, whose father was a club pro in 
Jacksonville, Fla., and now plays the Senior PGA Tour. ``I think we 
should get money to take back to our community. And if people see a 
problem with that, I'm sorry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he would not play on a Ryder Cup team if that wasn't  
the case, Duval declined to answer. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's pretty premature,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The meeting at Medinah Country Club, where the PGA Championship  
starts Thursday, included Awtrey, the 16 players, U.S. captain Ben 
Crenshaw and PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every single player who attended this meeting made it clear  
that they had no interest or desire or request to be compensated 
for playing in the Ryder Cup,'' Finchem said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, Awtrey took the occasion to explain exactly  
what the PGA of America does with its profit from the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Ryder Cup Outreach Program, $12.5 million is earmarked  
for programs designed to help the game grow, such as The First Tee, 
a learning center in Port St. Lucie, Fla., and education programs 
for PGA club professionals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Players understand where it's going,'' Awtrey said. ``It's not  
a matter of anything the PGA is not doing correctly. They would 
like to be involved and have influence in some of the things we do, 
and we're committed to doing that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Awtrey said details were not discussed in the meeting, and he  
said another meeting wasn't immediately scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	``The players are satisfied that we're going to take a look at  
all this, and then we'll see in the next few weeks at what we can 
do and how soon,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	One by one, the players walked out of the clubhouse and none got  
into specifics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is on the same page,'' Lehman said. ``There will not  
be compensation to players under any circumstance. The PGA of 
America heard what the players had to say about having a voice. The 
players want what's close to their hearts to be heard as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``The idea of a boycott was, is and and always will be ...  
ridiculous.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 10:34:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Derides Spain on Pinochet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attempts by Spanish authorities to try former  
Chilean President Augusto Pinochet for alleged human rights 
violations amount to ``foreign intervention'' and cannot be 
accepted by Chile, Foreign Minister Juan Gabriel Valdes said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't think that foreign intervention, even if it is well  
intentioned, will help solve the problem,'' Valdes told a news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Valdes, here for consultations with U.S. officials, said Chile  
is very much in favor of an international judicial system that 
prosecutes crimes against humanity. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we are not prepared to accept a decision by one court and  
one country by itself to take measures and pretend to subordinate 
our own courts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet was arrested by British authorities last October on  
orders of Spanish Judge Baltasar Garzon. Spanish efforts to 
extradite Pinochet are before the courts. 
</P>
<P>
	Valdes said the Spanish action ignores legal processes in Chile  
to deal with what he admitted was a difficult past. As an example, 
he noted that Pinochet is facing 28 cases in Chilean courts. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James P. Rubin expressed sympathy  
Monday for Chile as it attempts to cope with the problem 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States is committed to the principles of  
accountability and justice, and to supporting Chile as it wrestles 
with the difficult problem of how to balance the need for justice 
with the requirement of reconciliation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Valdes' meetings with U.S. officials were dominated by trade  
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking with reporters on Monday, Valdes said Chile is giving  
up on becoming a member of the North American Free Trade Agreement 
and is instead seeking a bilateral trade agreement with the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	``NAFTA is in the past,'' Valdes said after a meeting with  
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. 
</P>
<P>
	After Mexico joined with the United States and Canada in 1994,  
an invitation was extended to Chile to become NAFTA's fourth 
member. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan failed because of congressional opposition to creating  
new trade agreements or enlarging the scope of existing ones. 
</P>
<P>
	Influenced by labor union opposition, Congress has refused to  
grant President Clinton the ``fast track'' authority he needs to 
negotiate free trade agreements with Chile and other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Valdes said he informed Albright of Chile's decision to invite  
the United States to begin a review process ``leading to the 
initiation of a negotiation beyond the subject of fast track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the NAFTA option dead, Valdes said though a translator,  
``what interests us is a bilateral economic relationship between 
Chile and the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While spurned on its NAFTA bid, Chile has since become an  
associate member of Mercosur, a South American free trade grouping 
led by Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay, and Uruguay. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 08:11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Driver Runs Over Israelis; 12 Hurt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NACHSHON JUNCTION, Israel (AP) -- A Palestinian on a suicide  
mission twice rammed his car into hitchhiking Israeli soldiers 
during today's morning rush hour, injuring 12 before being shot to 
death by troops. 
</P>
<P>
	The 22-year-old assailant, Akram Al Qam from the West Bank town  
of Bethlehem, called his mother early today and told her he was 
going to carry out a suicide attack. 
</P>
<P>
	``He told me, 'I am at a junction and I see a lot of  
soldiers,''' said Al Qam's mother, Fadwa. 
</P>
<P>
	She said her son had no ties to the Islamic militant group  
Hamas, but in the past week had been reading a book about the Hamas 
chief bombmaker, Yehiyeh Ayyash, who was assassinated in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Al Qam said that after her son called, her husband and  
another son went to stop him. They came too late and instead were 
asked to identify the body. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak called the attack  
``cowardly,'' but he said it would strengthen Israel's resolve to 
cooperate with Palestinian security services to fight terrorism. 
Barak's hard-line predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, routinely 
accused Palestinian security of not doing enough to prevent 
attacks. Israel's new moderate leader did not make such 
allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinian Authority criticized those who opened fire on  
the driver, saying they acted too quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack occurred at Nachshon Junction, a major intersection  
30 miles west of Jerusalem. Al Qam's red Fiat with yellow Israeli 
license plates struck two soldiers near a hitchhiking post as they 
were about to cross the street. The car sped away and a police 
helicopter was called in to chase it. 
</P>
<P>
	After about 10 minutes, the driver made a U-turn, returned and  
plowed into the soldiers again, said army spokesman Lt. Col. Sharon 
Grinker. Paramedics said one soldier suffered serious injuries and 
the others were slightly hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	One witness, Reuven Gvirts, was riding his bicycle nearby at the  
time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw the car hit the soldiers again, including some who were  
already on the ground,'' said Gvirts, 47. The car dragged some of 
the injured and then crashed into a flatbed truck, Gvirts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Local police official Shimon Sharvit said police and soldiers  
opened fire on the Fiat when it approached the second time. Sharvit 
said the driver was killed before his car hit the truck. 
</P>
<P>
	Police searched the car for explosives, but found none.  
</P>
<P>
	Several times before, Palestinian militants have driven cars  
into Israelis at hitchhiking posts or bus stops. Iron barriers have 
been set up at some intersections to prevent such attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Militants in the past have carried out bombings and shootings in  
Israel in hopes of wrecking interim peace agreements between Israel 
and the Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's attack came at a time of dispute between Israel and the  
Palestinians over the implementation of the Wye River 
land-for-security agreement. Relations between the sides are 
strained, but both have said there is no deadlock. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 08:11:15 </DATE_TIME>
