<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MLS Commissioner Learning the Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Admitting he will draw snickers for his lack of  
soccer knowledge, new Major League Soccer commissioner Don Garber 
said Tuesday that learning about the sport is one of five things on 
his short-term ``to do'' list. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know you guys will laugh at this, but I need to spend as  
much time as I can getting as broad an understanding of the soccer 
world so that I can be confident with the game and lead it in this 
country appropriately,'' Garber said on MLS' weekly telephone news 
conference with reporters. ``I need to be as comfortable with this 
game so I can lead it comfortably.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garber, who replaced Doug Logan a week ago in the 3 1/2-year-old  
league's second major management shakeup in less than six months, 
came to MLS from the National Football League, where he rose 
through the ranks of its marketing and international divisions. His 
most recent responsibilities were NFL Europe and exhibition games 
outside the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Garber, 41, acknowledged last week at his introductory press  
conference that he knew little of soccer, but said he arrives with 
vast sports business experience, including selling American 
football to an uninformed public in Europe, Asia and Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	Garber said other major objectives included getting investors to  
operate the league-run teams in Tampa, Florida, and Dallas; working 
with its domestic television partners ABC-ESPN and the 
Spanish-language Univision to better promote the league; spending 
time with reporters to better learn their wants and needs; and 
working with strategic sponsors to get them to commit to the league 
in broader aspects. 
</P>
<P>
	MLS owners said Logan was replaced because the league needed to  
be doing better in attendance and television ratings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0238 </DOCNO>
