<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Names Black Speech Director </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton has named J. Terry Edmonds  
as his director of speechwriting, the first black person to hold 
the position. 
</P>
<P>
	Edmonds also was the first black presidential speechwriter in  
history, serving Clinton from 1995 to 1997. He succeeds Michael 
Waldman, who resigned as speechwriting director to work for Harvard 
University's Institute of Politics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Terry Edmonds has already served my administration with great  
distinction,'' Clinton said. ``I am looking forward to the 
invaluable contribution he will make in this new role.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a little overwhelmed because it is historic,'' Edmonds  
said Tuesday. ``I don't really like to think of myself as the first 
African-American this or that. I'm a professional just like 
everybody else. But I think it shows this president chooses people 
because of their abilities and not their color.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A graduate of Morgan State University, Edmonds currently is  
associate commissioner for external affairs at the Social Security 
Administration. He and Harvard Law professor Christopher Edley 
authored the draft assessment of race relations from which Clinton 
is compiling his own report on race. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, Edmonds was a speechwriter for Health and Human  
Services Secretary Donna Shalala, communications director for the 
Joint Center for Political and Economic Studies and press secretary 
for former Rep. Kweisi Mfume, now director of the NAACP. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Edmonds served as a senior speechwriter for Clinton's  
re-election campaign. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 22:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Newsmagazines Help CBS Ratings / TV Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tiger Woods and David Duval couldn't quite match  
the appeal of Mike Wallace and Dan Rather. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS won an easy prime-time ratings victory last week, with three  
newsmagazines in the top 10. It was the first time CBS had the 
three top-rated newsmagazines since ``60 Minutes II'' premiered in 
January. 
</P>
<P>
	Top-rated ``60 Minutes,'' its junior edition and ``48 Hours''  
each outranked ABC's prime-time showdown of golfers Wood and Duval. 
The unusual match was the 17th-rated program of the week, with ABC 
estimating more than 20 million people saw at least part of it. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week, CBS had a 6.7 rating and 13 share, Nielsen Media  
Research said Tuesday. NBC was second with a 5.8 rating and 11 
share, ABC had a 5.4 rating and 10 share and Fox had a 4.0 rating 
and 8 share. 
</P>
<P>
	Two hours of prime-time rock 'n' roll didn't go over well on  
Fox. Its ``Best of Woodstock '99'' special finished in 84th place 
for the week, with only 4.9 million viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the emerging networks, the WB had a 2.3 rating and 4  
share, UPN had a 1.6 rating and 3 share and Pax TV was at 0.8 and 
2. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC's ``World News Tonight'' won the evening news ratings race  
for the second straight week with a 7.0 rating and 16 share. The 
``NBC Nightly News'' had a 6.8 rating and 16 share, and the ``CBS 
Evening News'' was at 5.7 and 13. 
</P>
<P>
	A rating point represents 994,000 households, or 1 percent of  
the nation's estimated 99.4 million TV homes. The share is the 
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week of Aug. 2-8, the top 10 shows, their networks and  
ratings were: ``60 Minutes,'' CBS, 9.6; ``Frasier'' special, NBC, 
9.4; ``Frasier,'' NBC, 8.8; ``Friends,'' NBC, 8.8; ``CBS Sunday 
Movie: Stolen Women, Captured Hearts,'' CBS, 8.7; ``Just Shoot Me'' 
special, NBC, 8.5; ``CBS Wednesday Movie: Undue Influence, Part 
Two,'' CBS, 8.4; ``Touched By an Angel,'' CBS, 8.1; ``60 Minutes 
II,'' CBS, 7.9; ``48 Hours-Monday,'' CBS, 7.7. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 14:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lott Gets Around Limits on Donations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- From tobacco companies to high-tech investors,  
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott is raising money in chunks much 
larger than the strict limits imposed by Watergate-era federal 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mississippi Republican collected the money legally by  
setting up a state political committee in Virginia, which imposes 
no limits on the size or source of donations. 
</P>
<P>
	Other congressional leaders also are raising huge contributions  
from corporations and wealthy individuals through nonfederal 
entities, which allow them to get around the campaign finance laws 
that ban corporate donations and limit individuals to $2,000 per 
candidate, $1,000 for the primary and $1,000 for the general 
election. 
</P>
<P>
	The national political parties have exploited similar loopholes  
for state politics to raise six-figure donations from wealthy 
individuals, labor unions and companies. The contributions are 
known as ``soft money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott set up his political committee in Richmond, Va., on Oct. 9,  
1997, and has reported a total of $197,373 in donations so far, 
including $10,000 apiece from R.J. Reynolds and U.S. Tobacco last 
year while the Senate was debating proposed increases in the 
cigarette taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	His Democratic counterpart, Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle,  
reported contributions of $10,000 apiece from Northwest Airlines 
and American Airlines. Congress is debating legislation to renew 
Federal Aviation Administration programs. Overall, Daschle, who 
began his political action committee earlier this year, raised 
$274,491 in soft money through June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	At least a dozen lawmakers are raising money outside federal  
limits, including House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas; and Rep. 
Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., chairman of the Democratic Congressional 
Campaign Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``The explosion in leadership PACs that take soft money is  
further evidence of the need to pass campaign finance reform,'' 
said Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., a lead sponsor of legislation to 
ban such donations. ``If the Congress does nothing, more and more 
members are going to establish PACs that raise soft money, much of 
it in undisclosed, unlimited amounts from corporations and 
individuals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott said the contributions have nothing to do with his  
positions on issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm prepared to vote for or against tobacco or any other area  
when I think it is in the people's best interest and I've proven 
that time and time again,'' Lott said. ``There is so much going on 
in Congress and I am involved in so many issues ... I could almost 
not accept a contribution from anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he set up his committee in Virginia because that's where  
his federal PAC is based as well. ``I'm up there in Northern 
Virginia,'' he said. ``I don't think either one of my PACs are in 
actually set up in Jackson, Miss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott has spent $188,130 so far from his Virginia PAC, including  
$30,000 to the Foundation for a Responsible Government, a group 
affiliated with the centrist Republican Leadership Council. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott also gave $5,000 to the Committee for a Strong and  
Effective NRA, a group led by some National Rifle Association board 
members. The April contribution came two months before he spoke at 
an NRA conference in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee is addition to Lott's own campaign committee that  
collects donations for his Senate re-election, and a separate 
federal political action committee he controls. Those entities are 
bound by the federal contribution limits. 
</P>
<P>
	But his Virginia committee boasts numerous donations that Lott  
otherwise would have been forbidden to collect under federal 
control. For example, venture capitalist L. John Doerr gave $20,000 
-- 10 times more than he could give to Lott's re-election campaign. 
Doerr is a founder of a group that represents the high-technology 
industry, which has had a host of business before Congress from Y2K 
legislation to Internet taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle's political director, Michael Meehan, said the senator  
does not accept soft money donations greater than $10,000 and is 
raising the money to help elect Democrats on the state and local 
level. 
</P>
<P>
	``Senator Daschle's committed to electing Democrats to the  
Senate and the House and encouraging the next wave of potential 
Senate and House candidates,'' he said. ``One way to do that is to 
financially support them.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
