<DOCNO> APW19990810.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 01:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Powell Pushes Volunteerism Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- While some would prefer seeing him on the road  
to the White House, Retired Gen. Colin Powell is busy campaigning 
for the welfare of children. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking before the nation's governors in St. Louis, Powell said  
children must know that ``we care about them with all our heart and 
soul.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For two years, Powell has headed a campaign called ``America's  
Promise: The Alliance for Youth.'' The campaign has contributed 
more than $295 million to 10 million disadvantaged children 
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Powell compared the problems of children to the threats he once  
faced on the battlefield. 
</P>
<P>
	``The enemies they face in our society are every bit as real,  
every bit as dangerous, every bit as destructive. Every child has 
to be made a child of promise,'' he said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance seeks to make sure children have an ongoing  
relationship with a caring adult, a safe learning environment from 
which to develop a marketable skill and an opportunity to give back 
through community service. 
</P>
<P>
	The volunteer service should be required, Powell said, despite  
arguments by some that a law mandating such service would be 
unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was growing up, they made me do algebra against my  
will,'' he said. ``I see nothing wrong with service to community 
being part of a high school education curriculum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to his speech, Powell told The Associated Press he  
wouldn't run for president or vice president in 2000, but he isn't 
ruling out serving in the Cabinet if the next president asks. 
</P>
<P>
	``When a president comes to you and says, `Would you do this for  
me? Would you do this for the nation?' you have to stop and take it 
under consideration. I would do it for any president. But I'm not 
looking for a job,'' Powell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Powell would likely be on a short list for a key Cabinet post if  
Texas Gov. George W. Bush were elected, Bush associates said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Colin Powell is an icon. He's a walking statue,'' said Gov.  
Frank Keating, R-Okla. ``People admire him and respect him. I hope 
that he could be the next secretary of state in a George Bush 
administration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota said he personally won't run for  
president in 2000, but he would gladly run for vice president on a 
Reform Party ticket headed by Powell. 
</P>
<P>
	To make Monday's presentation, Powell didn't attend the 50th  
anniversary celebration of his former position as chairman of the 
joint chiefs of staff. Six of the 14 men who have served as joint 
chiefs chairmen joined President Clinton at the ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	Powell is best known for serving as joint chiefs chairman during  
the Gulf War. His brief flirtation with a presidential run in 1996 
attracted interest across party lines. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
