<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PGA Adds Events to 2000 Schedule  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- The PGA Tour is adding two new events to  
the 2000 schedule and bumping the B.C. Open to the same week of the 
British Open. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pennsylvania Classic, the brainchild of Arnold Palmer, will  
make its debut Sept. 14-17. The location has not been determined, 
although Laurel Valley Country Club near Palmer's home course in 
Latrobe has been mentioned. 
</P>
<P>
	The addition of the Pennyslvania Classic was made possible when  
the tour ended its relationship with the CVS Charity Classic at 
Pleasant Valley Country Club in Sutton, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've always focused on places we don't play,'' commissioner  
Tim Finchem said Tuesday. ``Pennsylvania is on top of the list. We 
haven't wrapped up the details, but we think it's going to be a 
great event.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other addition will be the Tampa Bay Classic, which will be  
played opposite The Presidents Cup the third week of October. It 
will take place at the Westin Innisbrook Resort, site of the former 
mixed team JCPenney Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	Penney is pulling its sponsorship of the mixed team event after  
this year, deciding instead to support an LPGA Tour event. The 
Tampa Bay Classic will be held every other year, giving players who 
don't make the Presidents Cup team a place to play for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the B.C. Open agreed to move from the second week in  
September to the middle of July and will play opposite the British 
Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not going to help us any, but it's not going to hurt us,  
either,'' tournament director Mike Norman said. ``Everybody thinks 
that because we're playing opposite the British Open that it's the 
end of the tournament, the sky is going to fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``Are we going to lose some players? Absolutely,'' he said.  
``But that's not going to make or break the B.C. Open. There's so 
much parity out there right now that the purist coming to watch 
golf is going to see good golf, regardless.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some tournaments are swapping places on the schedule. The Buick  
Classic at Westchester Country Club in New York, which was played 
the week after the U.S. Open this year, returns to its traditional 
spot the week before the Open. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest change is the International, which traditionally has  
been sandwiched around the PGA Championship and the World Series of 
Golf so that it can attract a strong international field. 
</P>
<P>
	But the PGA Championship and the new NEC Invitational, the World  
Golf Championship for Ryder and Presidents Cup players, will be 
back-to-back next year. Because the British Open is being played 
one week later (July 20-23), the International is scheduled two 
weeks before the PGA. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's some real questions about what's best for them on that  
date,'' Finchem said. ``The British Open moved a week, and somebody 
had to move. They're slated to be two weeks before the PGA 
Championship, and they're not sure that's not a better date.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tournament directory Larry Thiel was out of the office and could  
not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2000 schedule gives the PGA Tour 49 official events,  
starting with the Mercedes Championship in Hawaii and ending with 
the Stroke Play Championship in Spain. Five weeks will have two 
tournaments because of the WGC events, the Presidents Cup and the 
British Open. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
