<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Key Stock Index Rises / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's key stock index rose Tuesday following a  
government announcement that Japanese machinery orders were higher 
than expected in June. The dollar fell against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 11.64 points,  
or 0.07 percent, to close at 17,202.09. On Monday, the average 
closed up 106.21 points, or 0.62 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.88 yen in late-afternoon trading, down  
0.28 yen from late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York 
level of 115.20 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices opened slightly lower as many  
investors held off buying in the absence of market-moving news. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market may have been a little weak after retreating from  
yesterday's gains. Overall though, there is no good reason to sell 
shares or to buy them,'' said Yoshiyuki Higashi, manager of 
investment information at Taiheiyo Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	After spending much of the day in negative territory, the Nikkei  
bounced back in the afternoon after the announcement of a 
better-than-expected figure for June machinery orders. 
</P>
<P>
	The Economic Planning Agency said machinery orders to Japanese  
makers were up 6.3 percent from May. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 0.28 points, or 0.02 percent, to 1,424.25. 
The TOPIX closed up 3.85 points, or 0.27 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's main section was estimated at 354.94  
million shares, up from 323.16 million shares Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar barely budged against the yen as  
market participants saw little reason to push it in either 
direction. Trading was subdued as many market participants took 
time off during Japan's summer holiday season. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese banks bought some dollars for yen in the morning, but  
Japanese life insurers later sold the U.S. currency, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.30 yen, up from  
123.03 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.8900 percent from Monday's finish of 1.8450 percent, 
driving its price down to 99.23 yen from 99.61 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
