<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 12:20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BP Amoco Expects To Cut More Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- BP Amoco PLC boosted its quarterly operating  
profit by 14 percent and announced plans to cut 4,500 more jobs 
this year than originally expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Operating profit rose to $1.23 billion in the second quarter,  
compared with last year's $1.08 billion, the company said Tuesday. 
BP Amoco's main line of business, exploration and production, led 
the way with a 54-percent improvement in operating profit. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, formed by British Petroleum PLC's purchase last  
year of Chicago-based Amoco Corp., is in the process of absorbing 
Atlantic Richfield Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	It has realized the financial benefits of its merger sooner than  
anticipated, chief executive John Browne said, and expects to save 
$2 billion per year as a result of the union. 
</P>
<P>
	``Additional restructuring benefits have been identified and  
will continue to flow through to results in the future,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of its cost-cutting efforts, the company plans to reduce  
its work force by 14,500 people by the end of the year. It already 
made most of the cuts -- 12,500 -- by the end of July. 
</P>
<P>
	``So the bulk has already happened, mostly in the U.S.,'' Browne  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The announced reductions mark an increase from the company's  
original plan, outlined in February, to cut 10,000 jobs this year. 
The latest cuts will leave BP Amoco with 82,500 jobs by year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	A company official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
many of the remaining cuts would come in downstream operations such 
as refining and petrochemicals, which have suffered pinched profit 
margins due to higher prices they must pay for oil. The official 
would not name the countries where the remaining cuts would be 
made. 
</P>
<P>
	The improvement in profits in the company's upstream sector  
stemmed largely from higher oil prices. Average oil prices during 
the three months ending June 30 were $14.49 per barrel, against 
$12.13 during the same quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Browne warned that downstream margins, including  
refining and petrochemicals, would remain weak in months to come. 
</P>
<P>
	Worsening market conditions caused a 29 percent drop in  
quarterly operating profit for refining operations. Increased 
output and cost-cutting efforts helped boost operating profit for 
chemicals by 18 percent, but chemical margins will remain weak in 
the short term, the company said, due partly to higher oil prices 
and excess capacity. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco shares edged up 0.2 percent in London to close at 1,225  
British pence, or $19.60, a share. On the New York Stock Exchange, 
the company's U.S. shares were down 62 1/2 cents at $117.62 1/2 in late 
trading Tuesday. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
