<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Brazil, Germany Bid for World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- Brazil brought a squad of soccer  
heroes, and Germany hosted a beer fest at FIFA headquarters as the 
two countries made their bids to host the 2006 World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil and Germany were the last of five countries to make their  
pitches on Tuesday for the 2006 World Cup, the most coveted soccer 
event on the planet. 
</P>
<P>
	Also presenting to the FIFA were South Africa, England and  
Morocco. 
</P>
<P>
	After Monday's presentations by South Africa, accessorized by a  
chanting, dancing Zulu warrior, and England, who flew in singing 
school children, Brazil pumped up its campaign with a squad of 
football heroes. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to revive a fading bid, Brazil recruited superstar  
Ronaldo, as well as football legends Dunga, Zico and Carlos Alberto 
Torres. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany, meanwhile, hosted a beer fest, complete with pretzels,  
white sausage and a Bavarian accordion band on the FIFA 
headquarters' lakeside terrace. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil, fighting off negative publicity from football legend  
Pele's recent criticism of the bid, dismissed the former-player's 
disapproval, dispelling speculation it would harm the nation's 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the bid is bigger than Pele,'' said Torres, who was on  
the winning squad with Pele at the World Cup in Mexico in 1970. 
``I've known Pele for the past 40 years and I'm sure he will join 
us when he gets to know how serious we are with this project.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With South America last hosting the event in 1978, the  
Brazilians felt it would be unfair for Africa to get the next World 
Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``It needs to go where it is most loved,'' added Torres. ``If  
you had a first basketball World Cup, it would absolutely have to 
go to the United States. It only makes sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil also insisted it had gained full governmental backing.  
</P>
<P>
	The German delegation, led by former football great Franz  
Beckenbauer, underlined its organizational skills, modern 
facilities and technical superiority. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody still has a chance,'' said Beckenbauer, the captain  
of the 1974 German team that won the World Cup title at home and 
coach of the 1990 side that captured the title in Italy. ``Our job 
is now to convince everybody that Germany is the best place for the 
World Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, South Africa made en emotional appeal to host the  
continent's first World Cup, evoking the nation's troubled, 
turbulent past. The nation insists it has the necessary 
infrastructure to host a World Cup, and spent considerable time 
addressing the issue of safety and security. 
</P>
<P>
	The English, who are hoping to host a World Cup for the first  
time in 40 years, jetted in a 135-strong corps for a half-hour 
presentation and press interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	Morocco made its third bid in an attempt to become the first  
African nation to host the World Cup. It has been speculated, 
however, that it may pull out of the running following King 
Hassan's death. 
</P>
<P>
	With FIFA President Blatter repeatedly expressing his wish for  
the 2006 World Cup to go to the African continent for the first 
time, South Africa is being considered the front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-member Executive Committee will make its final vote on  
the 2006 host in July 2000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0254 </DOCNO>
