<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Appalachian Poverty Focus at Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRIFFITHSVILLE, W.Va. (AP) -- After the Rev. Joe Hacala was  
ordained as a Jesuit priest in 1975, his first assignment was in a 
poverty-stricken corner of southern West Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember the house where we lived in Griffithsville that  
fall -- no running water and no heat,'' Hacala said recently. 
</P>
<P>
	The hardships were a fact of life for many residents, and things  
aren't much different today, said Hacala, now an assistant 
secretary of the U.S. Housing and Urban Development. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, Hacala is organizing a follow-up conference to a  
four-day tour last month by President Clinton through poor areas of 
the country. Clinton called for public and private investment in 
areas that have been left out of the nation's booming economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Government cannot do this alone, but business cannot be  
expected to go it alone,'' Clinton said then. 
</P>
<P>
	The conference -- which convenes Thursday in Ashland, Ky., and  
wraps up Friday in Huntington, W.Va. -- will include HUD Secretary 
Andrew Cuomo as well as the secretaries of transportation, labor 
and agriculture, and the governors of West Virginia and Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	Hacala said educating others about poverty-stricken areas of  
Appalachia is the conference's main goal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to get people to realize that at the turn of the  
millennium, in the wealthiest nation on earth, there are people who 
still don't have safe drinking water,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have an economy that is daily setting new records, and now  
we need to figure out how to help those people who don't sit around 
waiting for the closing bell to ring on Wall Street.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His concerns are echoed by Amy Glasmeier, a professor of  
geography and regional planning at Pennsylvania State University 
and a John Whisman scholar to the Appalachian Regional Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until people have the right to clean water, the right to sewer  
systems, the right to garbage pickup -- rights that are taken for 
granted all over the country -- you will have a situation where ... 
people have a low opinion of themselves, where they think that no 
one cares,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Appalachian region has experienced a long history of  
government attempts to combat poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	By some accounts, it started with Eleanor Roosevelt's  
``subsistence homesteading'' idea of 1933, an attempt to relieve 
the worst of the poverty created by the Depression. But the laws to 
carry out the concept of worker-owned factories and communities 
were ruled unconstitutional before the communities became 
self-supporting, and the plan died. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1960s, Lyndon Johnson tried to develop the ideas  
articulated by John F. Kennedy as a ``war on poverty,'' including 
the development of the Appalachian Regional Commission and the 
Volunteers in Service to America. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost as though, every 30 years or so, people look over  
their shoulders and realize that somehow we still are not right 
there behind them,'' said John David, a professor of social science 
at the West Virginia University Institute of Technology in 
Montgomery. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
