<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Divide Over Nixon Remains Strong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YORBA LINDA, Calif. (AP) -- Pandy Byrd sat in a dimly lit room at  
the Richard Nixon Library &AMP; Birthplace surveying the life-size 
black-and-white photograph of a fallen man waving farewell to his 
presidency and the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-five years to the day Nixon resigned, the image in the  
library's permanent exhibit brought back Mrs. Byrd's childhood 
memories of her parents watching coverage of the Watergate scandal 
that transfixed the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	``It did happen and it shouldn't have happened,'' Mrs. Byrd, 35,  
said as she sat on a bench with one her two boys. ``I hope that my 
children would come away with the understanding that the end does 
not justify the means.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although the rhetoric has eased since Aug. 9, 1973, visitors to  
the library on Monday had strong opinions about a man who has 
inspired both fierce loyalty and contempt. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was very, very wrong,'' said Bob Teston, 60, who, like Mrs.  
Byrd, is from Yorba Linda. ``I hated to see him resign. I had voted 
for him. But it was for the good of the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teston said he would tell the 2-year-old grandson he cradled in  
his arms when he was old enough to understand that Nixon ``was a 
good president who made mistakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harold Leung, 51, of New York City remains a Nixon admirer,  
crediting him for opening China and attributing his downfall to 
``crazy left-wingers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a Vietnam veteran and he did a lot of things to try to  
protect us in Vietnam,'' he said. ``I think people forget that he 
made one mistake and he did so much for the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Choosing to visit the library on the anniversary of the  
resignation was a ``curious coincidence'' for the Rev. Leo 
Constantino, 64, of Wheaton, Ill., a Vietnam War opponent who 
protested against Nixon and voted for candidate George McGovern. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must look at his presidency in a balanced and fair  
manner,'' Constantino said. ``But we must never forget that he 
caused a crisis in the republic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among Nixon supporters, his resignation was viewed as an  
honorable act. 
</P>
<P>
	``In light of everything that's going on I think the darkest day  
in American politics was the day the Senate acquitted Bill Clinton 
of lying under oath,'' said Patricia Fortier, 43, of Buena Park. 
``President Nixon had the dignity to resign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leung said the resignation was for the good of the country.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's more than you could say about the man who holds the  
current position,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The library did not mark the day with a special exhibit.  
Executive Director John Taylor said that was unnecessary because 
the museum is full of references to Watergate and the final days. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a time of reflection,'' he said. ``Neither is it a time  
of celebration nor a time of breast-beating.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
