<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miss Sally: A Show Within a Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- You won't find it on Nickelodeon. It's no  
Children's Television Workshop presentation. ``Miss Sally's 
Schoolyard'' is a kiddie show, but the only televisions that 
receive it are inside the walls of Oswald Penitentiary -- on the HBO 
prison drama ``Oz.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gathered around a TV set in Cell Block 5, Miss Sally's jail  
house devotees watch with a passion that has little to do with her 
goody-goody manner or the goofy skits with her puppet pals. What 
makes them prisoners of ``Miss Sally's Schoolyard'' is something 
else: Miss Sally's very large chest. 
</P>
<P>
	Oddly enough, they seem more aware of it than Miss Sally is. She  
jumps and bounces with the fidgety abandon of a 5-year-old. Nothing 
about the figure she cuts seems to strike her as excessive. No 
wonder she captivates the prisoners. No wonder she also brings some 
comic relief to the otherwise ferocious ``Oz.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, for television, she represents a first. On ``The  
Simpsons,'' the cartoon siblings Bart and Lisa watch ``Itchy and 
Scratchy'' cartoons. But ``Miss Sally's Schoolyard,'' however 
little of it ``Oz'' viewers ever get to see, surely qualifies as 
TV's first live-action series-within-a-series: Miss Sally always 
stays behind the glass. 
</P>
<P>
	This earns a certain distinction for Whitney Allen, the  
24-year-old actress who plays Miss Sally. In her wordless and 
uncredited role, Allen stars in a TV series you have to watch 
another TV series in order to glimpse. As Miss Sally, she is not 
once but twice removed from real life. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, playing Miss Sally wasn't all that complicated.  
</P>
<P>
	``I knew what I was supposed to be,'' says Allen, summing it up:  
``Good body, sweet face.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Behold Miss Sally as a Girl Scout, cheerleader or Swedish  
milkmaid. The leering prisoners certainly do. ``Miss Sally's 
Schoolyard'' may be aimed at little children. But among her 
unintended audience of lifers, Miss Sally isn't kid stuff. 
</P>
<P>
	On this week's ``Oz'' (premiering Wednesday at 10 p.m. EDT),  
Miss Sally looks fetching in a nurse's uniform as she farcically 
attends to poor, sick puppet Nooter. The other puppet, Pecky, is 
the doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that you can hear any of it -- nor, by choice, do the  
inmates. The TVs are audible only through headphones, which are 
clearly unrequired for savoring Miss Sally's, er, effervescence. 
</P>
<P>
	But here's the best part of the joke that Miss Sally embodies:  
contemplating who the joke is on. Is it Miss Sally, the unwitting 
lust object for a pack of murderers and rapists? Or is it those 
inmate-admirers, in the grip of a woman who mocks their deprivation 
with every jiggle -- yet will never even know they exist? 
</P>
<P>
	Or is the joke on you, the ``Oz'' viewer? As it turns out, Miss  
Sally is padded. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess my own body was good enough at the audition, but with  
the costumes they chose, it just wasn't the `dream bust' they 
wanted,'' Allen says, amused by the vagaries of show biz. ``They 
wanted something out of control! I had these things that look like 
chicken cutlets in my bra.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Sally was born not only out of naughtiness, but expedience.  
In its first two seasons, the inmates of ``Oz'' watched actual 
shows. But buying rights to use TV clips is complex and costly, 
according to ``Oz'' creator Tom Fontana. 
</P>
<P>
	``This year, we said, `Let's make up our own show,''' he  
explains. 
</P>
<P>
	Fontana knew this interior series would have to be something  
prisoners would want to watch. He considered a mock soap opera. Or 
maybe a ``Jerry Springer''-like talk show. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then I recalled when I was a kid and I watched `Kukla, Fran  
and Ollie': a woman with two puppets. We decided to do a show like 
that. Except our woman would have enormous breasts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her co-star puppets were designed and suggestively christened.  
Pecky emerged as a little man who pays visual homage to Kukla. 
Nooter looks like a bespectacled, toothless version of the dragon 
Ollie. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a call went out for the Fran.  
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the girls we saw were too Playboy-esque, too  
Vegas-y,'' says casting director Alexa Fogel. ``We needed someone 
playful, with a sense of humor, and voluptuous. But wholesome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Allen, a lovely girl-next-door type with a flair for comedy,  
filled the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Wilmette, Ill., she had moved to Manhattan three  
years earlier, where she promptly won a role in ``Forbidden 
Broadway,'' a long-running revue that spoofs New York theater. She 
also did a guest shot on ``Spin City,'' as a former girlfriend of 
star Michael J. Fox. 
</P>
<P>
	But now she was a regular -- sort of -- in a critically acclaimed  
series that, in its previous seasons, she had watched and loved. 
</P>
<P>
	Last January, weeks before ``Oz'' resumed production, she  
reported for the ``Miss Sally'' shoot. They had just one day to 
tape segments for all eight of this season's ``Oz'' episodes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was really fun,'' Allen says. ``I just told myself, `This  
is a character who has no idea what she looks like. She is a 
complete innocent.' And that's what you laugh at. That, and the 
perverted, awful things those guys say about Miss Sally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Allen tunes in ``Oz'' each week, she finally gets to hear  
them. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`TREASURES IN YOUR HOME': This week the Pax TV network is  
launching a live TV series that will blend interactive elements 
from the Web and television into a seamless entertainment 
experience. And it helps you shop for stuff, too. On ``Treasures in 
Your Home,'' which airs weeknights at 7 p.m. EDT, viewers have an 
opportunity to bid on featured collectibles in real-time via the 
Internet after researching those items on the Web site. In 
addition, the series itself can be seen simultaneously on the Web 
site, TreasuresInYourHome.com. ``Treasures'' will showcase 
everything from priceless antiques to quirky collections of pop 
culture items, as well as featuring information on antique shows 
around the country, expert appraisals, interactive audience games 
and much more. John Burke is host. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ``at'' ap.org  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
