<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 10, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	MCI Problem Cripples ATMs, Data  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A glitch in MCI WorldCom Inc.'s data transmission  
network has partially disabled thousands of automated teller 
machines and restricted market trading of corn, soybeans and other 
financial futures. The problem at the No. 2 U.S. long-distance 
carrier began late last week during a system upgrade and has 
disrupted high-speed data service for nearly 30 percent of MCI's 
global data network customers, a spokeswoman said. MCI was 
upgrading network software when the system began experiencing 
problems in New York, Boston, Chicago, Los Angeles and San 
Francisco and other cities. MCI WorldCom stock closed down 2 3/8 at 75 
1/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Silicon Graphics To Cut 3,000 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Silicon Graphics Inc. shares plunged  
more than 23 percent today after the struggling company said it 
will cut up to 3,000 jobs and spin off its Cray supercomputer 
division. SGI said the cuts and reorganization -- the company's 
third in three years -- will help it focus on selling software and 
computers related to the Internet, and exploit the explosive growth 
of the medium. Shares in SGI, known for generating graphics in 
movies like Jurassic Park, fell 3 3/4 to 12 7/16. 

</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco Expects To Cut More Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- BP Amoco PLC boosted its quarterly operating  
profit by 14 percent and announced plans to cut 4,500 more jobs 
this year than originally expected. Operating profit rose to $1.23 
billion in the second quarter, compared with last year's $1.08 
billion. BP Amoco's main line of business, exploration and 
production, led the way with a 54-percent improvement in operating 
profit. The company is in the process of absorbing Atlantic 
Richfield Corp. A company executive said BP Amoco has realized the 
financial benefits of its merger already and expects to save $2 
billion per year as a result. BP Amoco stock closed down 3/4 at 117 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes Down 52.55 at 10,655.15  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks continued their slide today as investors  
remained unsettled by growing expectations that the Federal Reserve 
will raise interest rates at least once more this year. At the 
close of trading, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 52.55 
at 10,655.15. Broader stock indicators also fell, namely the 
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, which fell 22.87 to 1,274.93. The 
Nasdaq is more than 10 percent below its peak, a decline that Wall 
Street considers a correction. 

</P>
