<P>
	Grand Jury Investigates Lockheed  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A federal grand jury is investigating whether  
Lockheed Martin Corp. paid kickbacks to win contracts for the sale 
of military radar systems to Taiwan, the largest U.S. defense 
contractor disclosed in documents filed with the Securities and 
Exchange Commission. The investigation centers on payments made to 
Richard Hei, a former Taiwanese air force officer who helped secure 
contracts for radar sold by Lockheed Martin Sanders, a wholly owned 
subsidiary, in 1990. 

</P>
<P>
	Tupperware Begins Online Sales  
</P>
<P>
	KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- Tupperware, which for decades relied  
solely on face-to-face sales at parties, today began selling its 
housewares over the Internet. The move online is the latest 
innovation for the company in its efforts to get Tupperware 
containers into the hands of its customers following a year of 
declining sales. Tupperware, which had $1.1 billion in sales last 
year, announced in May that it would sell merchandise on the Home 
Shopping Network during television specials. Tupperware stock 
closed down 5/8 to 23 13/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Lawyer Partnerships Plan Uncertain  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The nation's largest lawyers' group delayed  
consideration today of a proposal to allow clients one-stop 
shopping for legal, financial and other professional help. At issue 
is the longstanding ban on lawyers forming partnerships with other 
professionals such as accountants, psychologists and social 
workers. Many in the American Bar Association want to consider 
dropping the ban amid increased competition from huge, 
multi-service international firms. 

</P>
<P>
	EU Clears Pharmaceutical Merger  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Union antitrust regulators  
have approved a merger between pharmaceutical firms Hoechst AG of 
Germany and Rhone-Poulenc SA of France after the companies agreed 
to divest certain businesses in which they might gain an unfairly 
dominant position. The companies agreed to spin off activities in 
chemicals and animal health and to surrender licenses on a number 
of products where an overlap risked creating an anticompetitive 
advantage, the European Commission said today. 

</P>
<P>
	Institute Wants All Knowledge on Web  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- While entrepreneurs and investors worry about how  
to make money from the Internet, Kevin Marsh has a different goal: 
perfect knowledge. Marsh hopes to put mankind's accumulated 
knowledge within a few keystrokes of anyone with a computer. Marsh 
runs a nonprofit group, the Information Access Institute 
(www.information.org). The institute helps libraries and museums 
put what librarians call ``knowledge records'' online. 

</P>
<P>
	Lucent To Buy INS for $3.7 Billion  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lucent Technologies Inc. is buying International  
Network Services Inc. for about $3.7 billion, bolstering Lucent's 
push into the fast-growing arena of advising corporations on 
setting up high-speed data networks. The agreement gives Lucent, a 
leading maker of telecommunications equipment, additional expertise 
to offer corporate customers seeking efficient systems for 
transmitting information and carrying conversations. Lucent plans 
to combine INS with its NetCare unit, which designs and sets up 
data networks. Lucent stock closed down 2 to 61 5/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com Standardizes on Dell  
</P>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Dell Computer Co. announced today that  
Amazon.com, the largest retailer of videos, music and books, will 
standardize the company's corporate PC line, OptiPlex. Amazon.com 
also will purchase Dell Latitude notebook PCs and Dell Precision 
WorkStations. In March, the companies announced a strategic 
agreement to offer linked Web sites and to provide customized 
content for Amazon.com and Dell customers. 

</P>
