<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bears Prowl in Eastern Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Bears left hungry by withered berry bushes are roaming into  
campgrounds and back yards from New Jersey to Maine, plundering 
knapsacks and bird feeders to survive their season of discontent. 
</P>
<P>
	But the drought isn't all bad news for creatures of the wild,  
nor of the deep. West Virginia's wild turkeys and ruffled grouse 
are flourishing after years of wet weather. And in Maryland's 
Chesapeake Bay, biologists say oysters and anchovies could thrive 
thanks to higher saline levels. 
</P>
<P>
	All along the food chain, animals are feeling the effects of  
unmercifully dry months, scrounging, dying or thriving in high 
numbers as the sun beats down. 
</P>
<P>
	In general, ``wildlife handle it a lot better than people do,''  
said Roy Grimes of Kentucky's Department of Fish and Wildlife 
Resources. Elk and wild turkeys have adapted well, while fish died 
en masse when heat reduced the oxygen supply in the Kentucky River. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York's Adirondack Mountains, officials say the drought --  
combined with a bear population boom -- have made bear raids a 
nightly occurrence in backpacking camps this season. Desperation 
has made the state's 6,000 to 8,000 bears increasingly adept at 
swatting down food strung high in trees. 
</P>
<P>
	Rangers have resorted to firing rubber bullets at them from  
shotguns, biologist Lou Berchielli said. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been 1,200 bear complaints this year in neighboring  
New Jersey, after fewer than 900 in all of 1998, officials say. 
Maine has also noticed a slight increase in complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	But elsewhere in the East, an increase in less threatening  
creatures is a welcomed change. 
</P>
<P>
	The abnormally arid climate has been perfect for a comeback of  
wild turkeys and grouse in West Virginia, where three years of rain 
and damp killed half their young. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's too early to say if this is a banner year, but it's  
certainly way above last year and above the last three years,'' 
said Curtis Taylor, a wildlife biologist with the state's Division 
of Natural Resources. Other animals, including deer, are emerging 
from the West Virginia woods in search of water and food. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything green they can find, they are going to eat,'' said  
Don Phares, a DNR project manager. 
</P>
<P>
	In Chesapeake Bay, higher salinity due to less fresh water could  
lead to a boost in oyster reproduction -- or a spike in disease 
among them. Scientists won't know until fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The salinity shift affects others in the bay's ecosystem. It's a  
boon to anchovies, since a lower salt level indirectly reduces the 
numbers of their predator, the jellyfish. And more anchovies means 
more food for the bigger fish that eat them, scientists say. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet fish have other worries. Blooms of oxygen-robbing algae in  
tributaries this season have caused large fish kills in the 
Pocomoke, Magothy and Patapsco rivers. State biologists say the 
drought is probably a factor. 
</P>
<P>
	While Eastern campers shoo away bears, they're swatting fewer  
mosquitoes. The stagnant pools in which the insects breed have gone 
dry, said Ed Reed, a New York state wildlife biologist. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've only seen two or three mosquitoes all summer,'' said John  
Zellner, caretaker at the Forked Lake campground in the central 
Adirondacks. 
</P>
<P>
	But bloodthirsty deer flies are worse than usual, breeding in  
the mud flats exposed by receding ponds and streams, Reed said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Connecticut, officials say drought has reduced the population  
of most of the state's 45 mosquito species. In a recent survey, 
only 50 mosquitoes were caught in a trap, compared to 250 during 
the same week last year. But ferocious salt marsh mosquitoes are 
flourishing along the state's coast. 
</P>
<P>
	``One night, my husband killed 53 mosquitoes in our kitchen and  
den.'' said Joan Rosa, who lives in the shoreline community of 
Guilford. ``I am having a nervous breakdown.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
