<HEADLINE> Reports: Ford To Buy Mazda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. will buy a parts-making subsidiary  
of Japan's Mazda Motor Corp. by the end of September, local news 
reports said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to acquiring Mazda's Naldec Corp., Ford is also  
considering capital tie-ups with about 10 other Japanese parts 
makers, the Nihon Keizai business daily said. 
</P>
<P>
	Naldec was formed in 1987 as a 50-50 joint venture between Mazda  
and NEC Corp. The company makes and sells electronic components for 
automobiles. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda will buy all of NEC's shares in the unit and then sell  
them along with its own stake to Ford parts unit Visteon Automotive 
Systems, the Nihon Keizai report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase is expected to total several million dollars, the  
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda and Ford officials in Japan could not be reached  
Wednesday, as the two companies were closed for summer holidays. 
</P>
<P>
	Hiroshima-based Mazda is 33.4 percent owned by Detroit-based  
Ford, the world's second-largest automaker. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest deal follows the sale of Mazda's credit arm to Ford,  
announced earlier this month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
