<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crops Push Corn, Soybeans Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures climbed above $5 a bushel for the  
first time since early May, while corn futures also rose sharply 
Tuesday, as crop conditions continued to deteriorate. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures prices on the Chicago Board of Trade have rallied  
sharply in the past few sessions as a drought takes its toll on 
Midwest crops, particularly in Illinois and Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Agriculture Department reported late Monday that  
soybean crop ratings nationwide deteriorated last week, from 57 
percent to 54 percent in good to excellent condition. 
</P>
<P>
	That was slightly above analyst expectations for a 2  
percentage-point decline in conditions. More significantly, in 
Illinois -- the second-largest growing state behind Iowa -- only 48 
percent of the crop was in good to excellent condition, while 17 
percent in the crop was in poor to very poor condition. 
</P>
<P>
	That was a sharp deterioration from a week earlier and showed  
that even the hardy soybean crop can suffer under extreme 
conditions. Projections of record production likely will be revised 
downward. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn crop conditions also fell 3 percentage points, the  
government reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors do not expect the situation to improve this week,  
because only scattered rainfall is expected along with warmer 
temperatures. Some investors said that would not be enough to 
replenish and revive corn and soybean plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 1/4 cent to $2.96 3/4 cents a  
bushel; December corn rose 4 3/4 cents to $2.40 3/4 cents a bushel; 
December oats prices remained unchanged; November soybeans rose 5 1/2 
cents to $4.93 1/2 cents a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and pork bellies futures were mostly higher on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while feeder cattle were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose .50 cent to 65.47 cents per pound;  
October feeder cattle rose .07 cent to 76.92 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs rose 1.12 cents to 46.77 cents a pound; February pork 
bellies rose 2.58 cents to 58.45 cents a pounds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
