<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cisco Systems' Revenues Soar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Nowhere is the Internet gold rush more apparent  
-- and real -- than at Cisco Systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Capping a stunning fiscal year in which revenues grew 43 percent  
and operating profits improved 35 percent, Cisco's fourth-quarter 
results showed that it continues to dominate the frenzied race to 
upgrade systems for Internet communications. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues for the three month period ended July 31 totaled $3.55  
billion, a 48 percent increase from last year's fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisco, based in San Jose, Calif., earned $727 million or 21  
cents per share, in the quarter, excluding one-time charges 
totaling $97 million for acquisition-related expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	In the year-ago period, Cisco posted an operating profit of $525  
million, or 16 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	The results edged most forecasts by industry analysts, which  
averaged 20 cents a share, according to a survey by First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	There was some caution, however, on the part of Cisco executives  
regarding the uncertainty over whether concerns about the Year 2000 
computer bug would interrupt technology orders later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still don't know,'' said chief executive John Chambers.  
But, he added, ``We're more comfortable with Y2K than we were 
6-to-12 months ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Including all one-time factors, Cisco posted a net profit of  
$635 million, or 18 cents per share, in its fourth quarter, up from 
$493 million, or 15 cents a share a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisco closed its fiscal year with revenue of $12.15 billion, up  
from $8.49 billion during the previous 12-month period. 
</P>
<P>
	Operating income totaled $2.55 billion, or 75 cents per share,  
for the fiscal year, an increase of 35 percent from the prior 
year's tally of $1.88 billion, or 58 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Net income for the fiscal year amounted to $2.10 billion, or 62  
cents per share. That compares with a net profit of $1.35 billion, 
or 42 cents per share, in the prior fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisco again attributed its stellar results to the rapid growth  
of the Internet, including the race to bring high-speed, multimedia 
services to consumers over a single cable or phone wire. Revenues 
related to upgrading cable and phone systems for that purpose rose 
20 percent from the prior quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also pointed to the move away from traditional modes  
of voice and video communications, which are starting to be 
packaged in the format used to transmit data on the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	``By providing the systems that make the Internet work, Cisco is  
playing a major role in helping customers thrive in the explosive 
Internet economy,'' said Chambers. As a result, he boasted, Cisco 
is ``the fastest growing and most profitable company in the history 
of the computer industry.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
