<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants Ink DE Strahan for $32M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Michael Strahan didn't mind sacrificing  
about $6 million in his signing bonus for a shorter deal -- and the 
biggest contract in New York Giants history. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-time Pro Bowl defensive end says the risk is worth it if  
it gets him back to the negotiating table at least one more time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd rather take that chance and see what I get negotiating a  
new contract instead of tying myself up for seven or eight years,'' 
Strahan, 27, said. ``I think I am young enough where I have enough 
confidence in my ability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strahan, who led the NFL with 29 sacks the past two seasons,  
cashed in Monday, signing a four-year, $32 million contract. The 
deal, which includes a $12 million signing bonus, makes him the 
league's second-highest paid defensive player. 
</P>
<P>
	``Michael is a very modest guy,'' said Tony Agnone, Strahan's  
agent. ``He absolutely is the best defensive player in football, 
and they wanted to make him the highest-paid guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only Dallas cornerback Deion Sanders will make more than  
Strahan, averaging $10.3 million annually under terms of a complex 
contract. However, Sanders has to play more than 70 percent of the 
Cowboys' defensive plays to be No. 1, Agnone said. 
</P>
<P>
	If he doesn't, Strahan will be the highest paid.  
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, recovering from toe surgery, is not in the Cowboys'  
training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am extremely happy. They made a commitment to me and I think  
we made a commitment to each other,'' Strahan said after signing 
the contract between practices at the University at Albany. ``I am 
happy to be in New York. I love New York and never wanted to go 
anywhere in the first place. So I'm glad they were able to get an 
agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the deal, Strahan will earn $400,000 in salary  
this year. He will get $4.6 million in 2000 and then $7 million and 
$8 million, respectively, in the last two years of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Not bad for a young man who grew up in Germany and who didn't  
play football until his senior year in high school. 
</P>
<P>
	Strahan's previous contract with the Giants would have expired  
after this year, and he warned the team during the offseason to get 
it done before this season started. 
</P>
<P>
	Agnone and Giants general manager Ernie Accorsi met several  
times in the last month, discussing both long- and short-term 
contracts, as well as ones with incentives, voidable years and 
other gimmicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Their breakthrough meeting came last Wednesday at Giants  
Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we realized was: `Let's not try to make everything so  
complicated and make things more simple,''' Agnone said. ``As we 
simplified things, we started realizing we could make this 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The result was a three-page contract, unlike some of the 35-page  
ones Accorsi has seen recently. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't get a contract any cleaner than this,'' Accorsi  
said. ``There isn't anything in it. There are five lines, each of 
the four years and the signing bonus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $8 million average salary also makes Strahan the  
highest-paid defensive linemen, moving ahead of Minnesota's John 
Randle, who averages $6.5 million under a deal he signed last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Now entering his seventh season, Strahan blossomed over the last  
two. He dominated up front and was selected to the Pro Bowl each 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
                             *Falcons    	
</P>
<P>
	Running back Jamal Anderson, holding out of training camp in a  
bid for a new contract, planned to meet with the Falcons today at 
Furman University, coach Dan Reeves said. 
</P>
<P>
	While Reeves downplayed the possible meeting, it could signal a  
major break in the holdout that has kept Anderson off the practice 
field since training camp began July 29. 
</P>
<P>
	Since he is under contract for this season, Anderson accumulated  
$60,000 in fines -- $5,000 per day -- as of Monday. The running back, 
set to make $2.6 million in the final year of his current deal, has 
been seeking a new five-year contract with a signing bonus of at 
least $8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, defensive end Chuck Smith returned to practice for the  
first time since spraining a toe during the first day of training 
camp on July 29. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Colts    	
</P>
<P>
	Edgerrin James arrived in Indianapolis with his agent Leigh  
Steinberg in hopes of coming to terms with the Colts. He was the 
fourth overall draft pick and is already figured as the starter at 
running back in place of Marshall Faulk, traded to St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	However, team president Bill Polian said the two sides are not  
any closer to an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	``The young man is holding out. They haven't made any movement  
off a ridiculous number, which is $11 million to sign for five 
years,'' Polian said. ``That's not acceptable, that's not do-able 
under any circumstances. They haven't made any movement off 
voidable years.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             *Panthers    	
</P>
<P>
	The promising season of Carolina rookie cornerback Tony Booth  
ended with a knee injury that will require surgery and at least six 
months of rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	Booth, a seventh-round draft choice who was getting rave reviews  
from coach George Seifert, injured his left knee during the team's 
morning practice. Tests showed a complete tear of both the anterior 
cruciate and medial collateral ligaments, Seifert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting safety Mike Minter was knocked unconscious shortly  
before Booth's injury. Seifert said Minter likely would miss most 
of the exhibition season, but should be ready for the Sept. 12 
regular-season opener at New Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Raiders    	
</P>
<P>
	Kicker Michael Husted was held out of practice because of a back  
problem that might have contributed to a missed 43-yard field goal 
at St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Husted said he felt a twinge in his back Friday morning while  
reading in bed, and that he had back spasms before the game. X-rays 
were negative and Husted said he felt better Monday, and hoped to 
return to practice today. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Dolphins    	
</P>
<P>
	Running back J.J. Johnson, Miami's top draft pick, is expected  
to miss up to 10 days after straining his left hamstring in a 
weekend scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, the first of Miami's two second-round draft picks, said  
he heard a ``popping'' sound as he went down after catching a 
15-yard pass in Saturday's scrimmage against the Tampa Bay 
Buccaneers. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Lions    	
</P>
<P>
	Offensive lineman Aaron Gibson, Detroit's first-round draft  
pick, will undergo several weeks of rehabilitation on his injured 
shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibson met with Dr. James Andrews, an Alabama-based orthopedist,  
on Monday morning and Andrews recommended rehabilitation, team 
spokesman Steve Reaven said. 
</P>
<P>
	He has a ``50 percent chance to come back in and play'' this  
season, coach Bobby Ross said. 
</P>
<P>
	The team feared Gibson, the 27th overall pick, would require  
surgery. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
