<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Investors Look Beyond S&AMP;P 500 Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Many investors not only want solid profits, they  
want them with a minimum of risk. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why they have turned to ``enhanced'' S&AMP;P 500 funds, or  
funds that try to outperform the well-known market index, while at 
the same time minimizing investors' risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Enhanced S&AMP;P 500 funds buy stock in companies outside the 500  
stocks that make up the index. The companies are selected through 
highly sophisticated computer programs that consider all of a 
company's important historical financial data. 
</P>
<P>
	Fund watchers familiar with enhanced funds say much of the  
analytical work is geared toward reducing the added risk brought on 
by tinkering with the traditional S&AMP;P model. 
</P>
<P>
	``The traditional S&AMP;P 500 index fund is only going to get you so  
far, and the mutual fund arena is kind of saturated with these 
things,'' said Chris Brown, an analyst with the Financial Research 
Corp. in Boston. ``The enhanced funds provide a different take.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Given the steady growth of the S&AMP;P 500 index over the past  
decade, a mutual fund that outperforms the index by just one 
percent is an attractive proposition, Brown said. ``That's where 
returns will really start to compound themselves,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Take American Century's $5.5 billion Income &AMP; Growth Fund, for  
example, which tends to focus more on smaller companies whose 
stocks are undervalued along with small, but fast-growing 
companies. The fund still holds positions in such blue-chip giants 
as General Electric, Microsoft Inc. and Chase Manhanttan Bank. It 
is trailing the S&AMP;P 500 by 1.24 percent in 1999, and by 2.86 
percent over the past year, but it has outperformed the index by 
0.15 percent over the last three years, according to Morningstar. 
</P>
<P>
	John Schniedwind, a senior vice-president and portfolio manager  
at American Century, attributed the fund's recent lackluster 
performance to a dismal first quarter of 1999, when a handful of 
large-cap stocks did phenomenally well, a dynamic that drew 
attention and money away from virtually every other segment of the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not for everyone,'' Schniedwind said. ``We're primarily  
for investors looking for an opportunity to take on additional risk 
relative to the S&AMP;P 500, but with the opportunity of outperforming 
that benchmark index.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schniedwind said the Income &AMP; Growth fund is geared toward  
longer-term investors who have the patience and the stomach to ride 
out volatile swings in the market. ``Somebody should be in this for 
at least three to five years, probably longer,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The computer generated models used to select the stocks that go  
into enhanced funds tend to tweak the portfolios ``just enough so 
that there will be a little more growth'' than standard S&AMP;P 500 
indexes, said Art Bonnel, portfolio manager of U.S. Global's Bonnel 
Growth Fund. ``It takes a lot of work to beat the S&AMP;P 500, but it 
can be done,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	One disadvantage to investing in enhanced S&AMP;P 500 index funds is  
that the turnover rates of stocks held in an enhanced portfolio are 
higher than those of traditionally stable S&AMP;P 500 index funds. S&AMP;P 
index funds simply mirror an established list of companies, so no 
tinkering is required. Enhanced funds, however, are trying to beat 
the S&AMP;P 500 by dabbling here and there. 
</P>
<P>
	The increased frequency of buying and selling means capital  
gains distributions are higher for investors of enhanced funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Cooley, a senior analyst at Morningstar, explained that,  
while many enhanced S&AMP;P 500 funds have equaled or outperformed the 
gains of the benchmark index in recent years, investors frequently 
find that their cash gains don't quite measure up because of the 
taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Operating expenses also tend to be cheaper for traditional S&AMP;P  
500 index funds since they don't need much active management and 
because their size allows for the costs to be spread out among 
thousands of investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Other enhanced S&AMP;P 500 funds include U.S. Global's All American  
Fund, Vanguard's Growth &AMP; Income Fund and Phoenix Income &AMP; Growth 
Fund. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
