<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lucent To Buy INS for $3.7 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MURRAY HILL, N.J. (AP) -- Lucent Technologies Inc. is expanding  
its presence in the growing field of designing and consulting on 
high-speed data networks by acquiring International Network 
Services Inc. for about $3.6 billion in stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucent, a leading maker of telecommunications equipment, plans  
to combine INS with its NetCare unit, which designs and sets up 
data networks, to create a 5,500-person division led by INS chief 
executive officer and president John Drew. 
</P>
<P>
	But Lucent now faces the challenge of retaining INS's 2,200  
employees -- and recruiters are already calling, an analyst said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lucent made a huge coup in the market, because INS, frankly,  
was thought to be unattainable,'' said Ellen Carney, a principal 
analyst at Dataquest. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, ``INS brings an extremely perishable aspect -- the  
intellectual capital of their people. It's sort of like of sushi in 
the refrigerator. It's nice while it lasts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lucent chairman Rich McGinn said the merger, to be completed by  
the end of the year, ``will offer customers the industry's deepest 
portfolio of network planning, design, integration, maintenance and 
management solutions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the nation's largest independent network consulting  
providers, INS earned $25.4 million in the fiscal year ended June 
30 on sales of $315 million. Its customers include more than 50 of 
the Fortune 100 companies, and one-third of the Fortune 1000, 
including AT&AMP;T Corp., MCI WorldCom Inc. and Microsoft Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lucent deal will have an impact on rival Cisco Systems, a  
leading maker of networking equipment, which owns between 7 percent 
and 8 percent of INS, and also has an executive on INS' board. 
Cisco vice president Charles Giancarlo will remain on the board 
until it ceases to exist when the deal closes, INS spokesman Jeff 
Kaplan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisco Systems will get a good return on its INS investment and  
has enough service relationships in place to keep from being badly 
hurt by the Lucent acquisition, Carney said, ``But their ego took a 
bit of a bruise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cisco spokesman Doug Wills said the deal would not hurt because  
Cisco works with hundreds of consulting firms and systems 
integrators. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good news for INS employees is that Cisco and KPMG are  
hiring,'' Wills said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisco, based in San Jose, Calif., on Monday announced it would  
invest $1 billion in KPMG LLP to aid the accounting and consulting 
firm's expansion onto the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Lucent dropped 3 percent, or $2, to $61.62 1/2 in trading  
on the New York Stock Exchange, decreasing the deal's value from 
its original $3.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	INS was up 6 percent, or $3, to $50.43 3/4 in trading on the Nasdaq  
Stock Market. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
