<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Fall on Rate Hike Fears / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell slightly Tuesday, pushing  
long-term yields to a new 21-month high, as worries over additional 
interest rate increases and a rush of new bonds to the market cut 
demand for U.S. government securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 3/16  
point, or $1.87 1/2 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, rose to 6.24 percent from 6.23 percent -- 
reaching a level last seen on Nov. 4, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The government bond market continued to be under pressure  
because of $22 billion in new 10-year notes and 30-year bonds that 
the Treasury is scheduled to auction Wednesday and Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The government sold $15 billion in five-year Treasury notes on  
Tuesday at the highest auction yield since August 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	An additional $1 billion in corporate supply is also weighing on  
the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Many traders expect the market to continue to trade poorly  
overall amid mounting expectations that Federal Reserve 
policy-makers will raise rates when they meet Aug. 24 and on fears 
that there will be one more rate increase before the year ends. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed raised rates on June 30, nudging a key interest rate up  
by a quarter-point, the first increase in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan warned last month that the central  
bank would be on the lookout for any signs of inflation and would 
move quickly to stanch such tendencies in the U.S. economy, which 
has shown surprisingly strong signs of growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, several economic reports have suggested that labor  
costs may be rising for employers, a key signal to interest policy 
makers that inflation could be on the horizon. Signs of inflation 
hurt the value of bonds, which pay a fixed rate of interest. A rate 
increase would also erode the value of bonds already in 
circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	However, a regional Federal Reserve Bank president with a vote  
on interest-rate policy, Robert McTeer Jr. of Dallas, told the 
Greater Dallas Chamber of Commerce on Tuesday that strong economic 
growth isn't necessarily inflationary, especially if it's fueled by 
gains in technology and productivity. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged to down 1/32 point, and intermediate maturities were 
down as much as 3/16 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.94 percent as the  
discount rose 0.02 percentage point from Monday's auction to 4.81 
percent. Six-month yields were 5.13 percent, as the discount rose 
0.01 percentage point from the weekly auction to 4.93 percent. 
One-year yields were 5.20 percent as the discount rose by 0.01 
percentage point from late Monday to 4.95 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, was unchanged from late Monday at 4.94 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 7/32 to 115 1/8. The average yield to 
maturity rose to 5.72 percent from 5.71 percent late Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
