<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Race-Based Busing Request Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A request by a group of white parents to end  
race-based busing in the city's schools by next month was denied 
Tuesday by a federal judge. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston School Committee already voted last month to end  
racial assignments for the school year beginning September 2000, 
but four white families said that wasn't soon enough. The parents 
said their children were being denied their first choice of schools 
because of racial considerations. 
</P>
<P>
	In a hearing last week, they asked U.S. District Court Judge  
Nancy Gertner for a preliminary injunction to revise the busing 
policy by the start of classes on Sept. 9. 
</P>
<P>
	The injunction would have affected children entering  
kindergarten and first-grade, as well as transfer students and 
those on waiting lists for their top school choices. 
</P>
<P>
	Gertner said Monday the injunction would inflict ``substantial  
disruption'' on the school assignment plan. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials had said there was simply no time to implement  
it in a matter of weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the outgoing Boston plan, children are assigned to schools  
based on several factors: race; the proximity of the child's home 
to the school; whether he or she has any siblings there; and the 
results of a yearly school choice lottery. Under the new plan, 
effective in September 2000, race will no longer be considered. 
</P>
<P>
	The outgoing policy emerged out of a federal desegregation court  
order 25 years ago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
