<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y.'s Lazio Suspends Senate Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Bowing to Gov. George Pataki's wishes, Rick  
Lazio will suspend his plans for a U.S. Senate campaign as New York 
City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani weighs the race, several Republicans 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republicans, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Lazio  
will not completely withdraw from the Senate competition, keeping 
his options open in case the mayor does not run for the seat being 
vacated next year by Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate comment Tuesday from Lazio and his aides  
refused to confirm the plans. The congressman plans to make his 
announcement at a news conference Wednesday morning in Bay Shore on 
Long Island. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Pataki asked Lazio to defer the Senate candidacy  
announcement the Long Island congressman had planned to make next 
week. The Republican governor said Giuliani had earned the right to 
the GOP Senate nomination and he urged the mayor to quickly declare 
his candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki has had frosty relations with Giuliani since 1994 when  
the mayor crossed party lines to endorse then-Democratic Gov. Mario 
Cuomo in the governor's race won by Pataki. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate race could pit Giuliani against first lady Hillary  
Rodham Clinton, who is pondering a bid as the Democratic candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki's plea to Lazio was designed to avoid a potentially  
bitter GOP primary. The governor had been under pressure from some 
national and New York GOP leaders to use his muscle to keep Lazio 
out of the race on the grounds that Giuliani would be a stronger 
Republican candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate comment Tuesday from Pataki, who is  
vacationing in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, who was still on her summerlong listening tour  
Tuesday in Queens, brushed aside concerns about a united GOP. 
</P>
<P>
	``I try not to think about issues I have no control over. What  
the other party does is strictly their business,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	While both Mrs. Clinton and the mayor have formed Senate  
exploratory committees and are raising money for their possible 
Senate bids, neither has formally announced their candidacies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
