<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jazz Official Takes Job in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Scott Layden has spent 11 seasons as the  
brains behind the Utah Jazz's personnel decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	By his own admission, it's time to mature.  
</P>
<P>
	Layden on Tuesday resigned as Utah's vice president for  
basketball operations, leaving the NBA's smallest market for its 
largest as he joined the New York Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It comes as a really tough decision to move on, but it just  
feels like the right thing to do,'' Layden, 41, said. ``I need to 
move on and grow up a little bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Layden declined to discuss his new job in detail, but he was  
expected to be introduced today in New York as the Knicks' general 
manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden's departure leaves the Jazz in a lurch as they try to  
re-sign free agent Shandon Anderson. Also pending are talks with 
free agents John Stockton and Jeff Hornacek, and both are expected 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah general manager Tim Howells said the Jazz have no list of  
potential successors for Layden, nor a deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no time line, but it's something we will be working on  
with a great sense of urgency,'' said Howells, who will take over 
negotiations with Anderson's agent. 
</P>
<P>
	Jazz owner Larry Miller, who usually cries at his team's news  
conferences, wasted no time welling up over Layden, whom he called 
``the Jazz's secret weapon'' of the past decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``From a personal, selfish standpoint and from a standpoint of  
wearing my hat as owner of the Jazz, I wish we weren't here today 
talking about this,'' Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden said the deciding factor was his family's enthusiasm for  
living in New York. He and his wife, Marsha, are supporters of the 
arts, and Layden lived in New York through his teen years. 
</P>
<P>
	The boyish-faced Layden also said he's eager to prove himself in  
a way he could not in Utah, where he lived in the shadow of his 
father, former coach Frank Layden. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've really felt like I've been on the coattails of some  
brilliant people -- coaches, players, owners and the people who work 
in this organization,'' said Layden, who spent 18 years with the 
Jazz. 
</P>
<P>
	News reports indicated Layden could be paid about $1.5 million  
in New York, four times his Utah salary. He wouldn't talk about 
money, but denied it was the reason he's leaving. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it was all about money, I would have moved on long ago,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As Utah's vice president of basketball operations, Layden  
developed a reputation as a skilled evaluator of talent. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of Utah's recent second-round draft selections, Bryon  
Russell and Anderson, helped the team's runs to the NBA Finals in 
1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	But Layden also has had trouble making trades, and his signing  
of center Greg Ostertag to a six-year, $39 million contract was 
widely ridiculed around the league. 
</P>
<P>
	There might have been more reasons for Layden to leave than  
stay. For one, the Jazz's aging trio of stars Karl Malone, Stockton 
and Hornacek are each over 35. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's Salt Lake's clean-cut -- some would say boring --  
image. Layden engineered deals in recent years for players like 
Rony Seikaly and Derek Harper, but neither would report. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden denied those factors contributed to his decision.  
</P>
<P>
	``By no means was that the case. This whole thing came up fast  
and it was an opportunity I felt I couldn't pass up,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
