<HEADLINE> Dollar, Gold Rises in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was down against other most major  
currencies in European trading today. Gold prices rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0733, up from $1.0694 Monday. Later,  
in midday trading in New York, the euro traded at $1.0748. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday,  
included 114.67 Japanese yen, down from 115.33; 1.4901 Swiss 
francs, down from 1.4967; 1.5005 Canadian dollars, down from 
1.5022. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6126, up from $1.6024.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 114.52 yen, and  
the pound was worth $1.6166. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8223 German marks, down from 1.8289; 
6.1116 French francs, down from 6.1339; 2.0532 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.0607; 1,804.03 Italian lire, down from 1,810.61. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $257.00 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$256.90 on Monday. In Zurich the bid price was $256.65, up from 
$256.35. Gold rose $0.70 in Hong Kong to close at $257.45. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.29 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$5.34. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
