<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nixon's Secret Tapes To Go On Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hear Richard M. Nixon pound his fist and bark  
orders to his White House staff. Replay the famous ``smoking gun'' 
conversation about Watergate that led to his resignation 25 years 
ago. Listen as Nixon says he wants to be sure the next IRS 
commissioner ``will go after our enemies and not go after our 
friends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning in January, 264 hours of Nixon's once-secret White  
House tapes go on sale from the National Archives. Details are 
still being finalized. Prices for cassettes have not yet been set, 
although archives officials say the government will not profit from 
the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	It won't be like listening to today's top-quality compact discs.  
These are scratchy, hard-to-hear recordings. 
</P>
<P>
	``What the public has to understand is that we're talking about  
recording devices that were not exactly state-of-the-art,'' Karl 
Weissenbach, director of the Nixon Presidential Materials Project 
at the National Archives, said Monday. ``People didn't always speak 
loudly and clearly. They get up and walk around the room. An 
individual could be 10 to 15 feet from where a microphone was 
located.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nixon's baritone voice is easily identified. So is the deep  
timbre of the voice of Henry Kissinger, Nixon's national security 
adviser and secretary of state. The voices of other players in the 
Nixon White House are harder to discern. 
</P>
<P>
	The archives has a total of 3,700 hours of Nixon tapes. But the  
public will only be able to buy copies of 264 hours of ``abuse of 
government power'' tapes that contain conversations about the 
break-in and bugging of the Democratic National Committee 
headquarters in the Watergate complex in Washington on Memorial Day 
weekend in 1972, the subsequent cover-up and wrongdoing by the 
president or his staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Making copies of the tapes was an issue in 1992 when historian  
Stanley Kutler and Public Citizen, an advocacy group, sued the 
archives, saying the Nixon tapes weren't being released fast 
enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Nixon intervened in the suit, and in 1993, they got  
a court order banning any further release of tapes until all 
personal and private conversations were returned to the president. 
</P>
<P>
	In a compromise reached in 1996, the parties agreed that if all  
the tapes were not opened by January 2000, the archives could make 
copies of the abuse of government power sections for public 
release. 
</P>
<P>
	John Taylor, director of the Richard Nixon Library &AMP; Birthplace  
Foundation in Yorba Linda, Calif., said he thinks the recordings 
should only be projected against the backdrop of the Vietnam War 
and released only within the context of the war and other events of 
the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``History will only have the complete story of the  
Vietnam-Watergate era when it has seen all the tapes in the context 
and in the light of the documentary record,'' Taylor said. ``I do 
not believe history will fully understand Watergate ... until it 
comes to terms with the fact that that was a wartime administration 
and that Richard Nixon was a wartime commander in chief.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the most popular snippets of tape:  
</P>
<P>
	-- A March 21, 1973 conversation between Nixon and John Dean,  
counsel to the president, who remarks that the Watergate affair had 
become a ``cancer'' on the presidency. ``We have a cancer -- within 
-- close to the presidency, that's growing,'' Dean tells Nixon. 
``It's growing daily. It's compounding, it grows geometrically 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- A June 30, 1971 recording when Nixon is heard telling his  
chief of staff, H.R. Haldeman, and others to arrange a break-in at 
the Brookings Institution, a think tank in Washington, to obtain 
Vietnam War files. ``I want them just to break in and take it out. 
Do you understand?'' Nixon tells Haldeman. ``You're to break into 
the place, rifle the files and bring them in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- A May 13, 1971 recording where Nixon talks about a prospective  
IRS commissioner. ``I want to be sure that he is a ruthless son of 
a bitch, that he will do what he is told, that every income tax 
return I want to see, I see,'' he said. ``That he will go after our 
enemies and not go after our friends. It's as simple as that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- The ``smoking gun'' conversation on June 23, 1972 -- just six  
days after the Watergate burglary. That exchange with Haldeman 
revealed that the president was interested in using the CIA to 
derail the FBI's Watergate investigation and led to his resignation 
on Aug. 9, 1974. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
