<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Drive Out Islamic Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russian forces today drove Islamic  
rebels out of two villages, and surrounded the militants in two 
others in the turbulent Caucasus Mountains, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian troops and the rebels have been skirmishing for four  
days in the southern republic of Dagestan, and the Russians 
appeared to be gaining the upper hand. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians cleared the militants from two villages in the  
southwest Tsumadinsky district and had encircled the rebels in two 
villages in the Botlikh region, according to Dagestan officials. 
The fighting was relatively light, the officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation in Dagestan has changed and is controllable  
now,'' Anatoly Kvashnin, the chief of the army's general staff, was 
quoted as saying by the ITAR-Tass news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	In Moscow, acting Prime Minister Vladimir Putin estimated it  
would take two weeks to end the standoff, according to the 
ITAR-Tass news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The remaining rebels will not be allowed to retreat across the  
border to Chechnya, said Dagestan's Interior Minister Omar 
Magomedov. They must either surrender or face renewed attacks, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dagestani government said four Russian pilots were killed  
today when their helicopters were shot down over Botlkikh. Four 
rebels and two Russian soldiers were killed Monday, and both sides 
suffered a number of wounded, according to Dagestan television and 
the Interior Ministry. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian troops said the rebels shot at Russian helicopters  
Monday, including one carrying Kvashnin. He was unhurt and the 
aircraft was only slightly damaged, according to Dagestan 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has been amassing forces in the region, and the troops  
have far more firepower than the rebels, who seized the villages on 
Saturday after marching across the border from the breakaway 
territory of Chechnya. 
</P>
<P>
	After the disastrous 1994-6 war in Chechnya, Russia appears wary  
of igniting a larger conflict. Still, Russia military and political 
leaders have insisted that the rebel forces must be crushed. 
</P>
<P>
	The gunmen's motives are not entirely clear, but they appear to  
be members of the Wahhabi Islamic movement seeking independence for 
Russia's mostly Islamic republics in the Caucasus Mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	The gunmen from Chechnya appear to have received some support  
from local Dagestan residents, though many villagers fled for 
Dagestan's capital Makhachkala. 
</P>
<P>
	Muslim leaders in Dagestan appeared to disagree over the  
standoff. 
</P>
<P>
	An unrecognized council of Muslim leaders, or Shura, gathered in  
Botlikh on Tuesday and declared an independent Muslim state of 
Dagestan governed by Islamic rule. The council called on all 
Dagestani Muslims to ``fight until all the infidels are ousted from 
the Muslim territory,'' according to a statement it sent to news 
agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	However, a far more powerful council of Muslim leaders, the  
Muslim Board of Dagestan, condemned the gunmen as extremists who 
are misusing Islam. It said Dagestan would not break away from 
Russia and that the Shura decision should hold no sway over 
Dagestani Muslims. 
</P>
<P>
	The conflict in Dagestan is linked to the ongoing tension in  
Chechnya, which has had de facto independence since Russian troops 
withdrew three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscow has placed security forces along Chechnya's borders to  
try to fence it off, but warlords and criminal gangs roam the area 
and often venture into neighboring regions such as Dagestan. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimates of the size of the militant force in Dagestan vary  
widely, though the Russian military puts the number at between 300 
and 600. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of Russian forces was also unclear. They include  
troops from several federal and local agencies and at least 500 
volunteers recruited by Dagestani security forces, Dagestani 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of refugees in Makhachkala, Dagestan's capital, has  
reached 4,000, said Mayor Said Amirov. Dagestan's government was 
setting up refugee camps at resorts and summer camps. 
</P>
<P>
	Dagestan's government opposes the Wahhabis and has shown no sign  
of splitting from Moscow, largely because its weak economy is 
heavily dependent on federal funding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
