<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of America To Lend $3 billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Many of the nation's banks have had to be  
embarrassed by activists or coerced by federal regulators into 
complying with the Community Reinvestment Act, aimed at fighting 
discrimination by mortgage lenders. 
</P>
<P>
	But in an unusual announcement, Bank of America has announced it  
voluntarily decided to fund an unprecedented $3 billion mortgage 
program for low- to moderate-income borrowers that promises no down 
payment, no application fee and no closing costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The program, announced Tuesday, is expected to assist about  
100,000 borrowers nationally. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be overseen by Boston-based Neighborhood Assistance  
Corp. of America, led by self-described ``urban terrorist'' Bruce 
Marks. Marks has a track record of getting loan commitments from 
banks after accusing them of discriminatory lending practices, but 
he said the Bank of America agreement was voluntary. 
</P>
<P>
	``As cynical as I am that all bankers are evil, this is the  
exception,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Low-income and first-time home buyers could begin accessing the  
program in about a dozen cities Tuesday. Neighborhood Assistance 
Corp. originates the loans, then helps the borrowers through the 
mortgage process and offers post-ownership assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	It is an investment for the bank as well, said Robert Johnston,  
senior vice president for Bank of America's community development 
bank. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not charity,'' Johnston said. ``There are a lot of cash  
transactions in the inner city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, before NationsBank was acquired by Bank of America,  
NationsBank agreed to lend $500 million in mortgages over five 
years through Neighborhood Assistance Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Garsson, spokesman for the federal Office of the  
Comptroller of the Currency, said the programs were examples of the 
Community Reinvestment Act at work. 
</P>
<P>
	The act, started by the Carter administration, directs banks to  
make investments to meet the credit needs of all the communities 
where they collect deposits, particularly in minority, poor and 
working-class neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of America's home mortgage program started Tuesday in  
Atlanta, Baltimore, Buffalo, N.Y., Charlotte, Jacksonville, Fla., 
Los Angeles, Memphis, Tenn., Washington, D.C., Dallas-Fort Worth, 
Houston, Oakland, Calif., Sacramento, Calif., San Antonio and 
Tampa, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Within the next 12 months, the program will be made available in  
New York City, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Albuquerque, N. M., San Diego 
and Little Rock, Ark. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
