<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Clears Pharmaceutical Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Union antitrust regulators  
have approved a merger between pharmaceutical firms Hoechst AG of 
Germany and Rhone-Poulenc SA of France after the companies agreed 
to divest certain businesses in which they might gain an unfairly 
dominant position. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies agreed to spin off activities in chemicals and  
animal health and to surrender licenses on a number of products 
where an overlap risked creating an anticompetitive advantage, the 
European Commission said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The commitments submitted by the companies are able to remove  
the competition concerns generated by the operation,'' said a 
statement from the EU executive body. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoechst and Rhone-Poulenc announced in December they would merge  
to create an international pharmaceutical giant named Aventis that 
will have annual sales of around $20 billion, spanning 
pharmaceuticals, agricultural chemicals and animal health products. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies have agreed to spin off their industrial chemical  
subsidiaries and the animal health company Hoechst Roussel 
Veterinaer GmbH. Hoechst intends to demerge its industrial chemical 
assets into a new group called Celanese AG. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhone-Poulenc will also sell or share licenses for about half a  
dozen products where they risked gaining an unfairly dominant 
position, particularly in the French market. The products range 
from an antibiotic used to treat throat infections to insecticides 
to kill cockroaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders from the two companies approved the merger last  
month. The merger is set to be completed by November. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
