<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 12:20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rehnquist Lobbies Congress for Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Proposed funding for federal courts is too low  
and if not increased will seriously hamper court operations, Chief 
Justice William H. Rehnquist is telling leaders of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to principal members of the House and Senate,  
Rehnquist portrayed the $4.1 billion sought for federal courts in 
fiscal year 2000 as a bare-bones request. He said levels initially 
approved are ``less than is required to furnish the services the 
judiciary provided this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate voted to cut $280 million from the federal  
judiciary's request for the fiscal year that will begin Oct. 1. The 
House version cut $180 million from the request. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of both houses will meet in conference after Labor Day  
to reconcile the differing proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	Rehnquist, in a letter dated Aug. 9, called the Senate proposal  
``unjustified and impractical'' and said the House version ``also 
would have a noticeable adverse impact on court operations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rehnquist, the top-ranking federal judge, called the $4.1  
billion request ``a minimal budget proposal for salaries and 
expenses,'' one that for a second consecutive year would provide no 
additional court staff despite growing workloads. 
</P>
<P>
	``As you know, the courts do not control their workload but  
rather must respond to filings created in large part by Congress' 
expansion of the federal courts' jurisdiction,'' Rehnquist wrote. 
``I therefore urge you to provide the necessary funding for the 
judiciary for FY 2000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letter was sent to Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, Senate  
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, House Speaker Dennis Hastert and House 
Minority Leader Richard Gephardt. A copy was made public by the 
Administrative Office of the U.S. Courts, along with a list of 
possible ramifications under the heading ``catastrophic funding 
scenario.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The list said the Senate funding bill would compromise public  
safety by requiring a cut in the number of officers supervising 
released felons, likely would require a 10-day furlough of all 
court employees except judges, would leave unfinanced ``critical 
court security enhancements'' and would provide enough money to pay 
court-appointed lawyers for only part of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	In one respect, the House bill would be worse: it would reduce  
funding for court security systems by $6 million below the level 
proposed by the Senate, the chief justice said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Administrative Office release noted that the proposed $4.1  
billion federal court budget would amount to less than two-tenths 
of one percent of the total federal budget. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
