<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lightning Kills College Pitcher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	THOMASVILLE, Ga. (AP) -- A Valdosta State student was struck by  
lightning and killed while pitching a hometown baseball game 
Sunday, as his college teammates celebrated a victory in the 
National Baseball Congress World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Ben Jackson, 22, was hit about 5 p.m. as he stood on the  
pitcher's mound at the Brookwood School in Thomasville, Thomas 
County Emergency Management Agency officials said. He died about an 
hour later at Archbold Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of Jackson's college teammates learned of his death while  
celebrating an early victory in the National Baseball Congress 
World Series in Wichita, Kan. 
</P>
<P>
	The left-hander was 13-8 during his three seasons at Valdosta  
State, making nine starts in 1999 and posting a 7.05 ERA with 46 
strikeouts. He struck out 140 batters in 167 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	His death also affected New York Mets reliever Billy Taylor, who  
had tutored Jackson for 13 years. Taylor was unavailable for 
comment Monday night after the Dodgers defeated the Mets 9-2. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers cut short their celebration of the victory series  
after learning of Jackson's death. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson had been playing a men's over-40 summer baseball league  
in his hometown to regain arm strength after surgery earlier this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ben was one of our best friends and we are all pretty  
distraught over here,'' teammate Jarrett Bridges told The Valdosta 
Daily Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Bridges said the players would most likely not be able to make  
it back from Kansas in time for Jackson's funeral Tuesday because 
of the long drive. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's such a tragedy,'' Valdosta State athletic director Herb  
Reinhard said. ``Ben was a tremendous example of what we want our 
student-athletes to be and a wonderful role model for young 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson had recently returned from a mission to Latin and South  
America as a member of Athletes in Action. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ben was a shining star in every way. He was a solid standout  
majoring in business and an integral part of our baseball team,'' 
Valdosta State coach Tommy Thomas said. ``If you didn't like Ben 
Jackson, you had to find out what was wrong with you.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
