<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starr To End Probe Before 2000 Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Independent counsel Kenneth Starr says he plans  
to wrap up his Whitewater investigation before the 2000 New York 
Senate election in which first lady Hillary Clinton is a likely 
candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are trying to move forward very, very rapidly,'' Starr told  
reporters Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	He was in Atlanta to give his annual review of Supreme Court  
decisions to members of the Institute for Judicial Administration, 
a group affiliated with New York University that promotes judicial 
education and research and predictability in the law's 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr made clear that his final report, which would be turned in  
to the panel of federal appeals judges who appointed him in August 
1994, would not draw any conclusions about conduct and would simply 
lay out the evidence gathered by grand juries and his 
investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress did not want a final report to be an avenue for  
alleging that one or more individuals had engaged in criminal 
conduct,'' Starr said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would anticipate that the final report will come at the  
earliest practicable moment. It would need to be a comprehensive 
final report that is factually straightforward, that does not 
engage in characterization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did not give a possible date for the final report. But when  
asked whether he plans to finish before the 2000 election, Starr 
replied, ``The answer is yes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton also was in Atlanta to address the American  
Bar Association, but his and Starr's appearances were separated by 
several blocks and several hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was careful to note for his fellow lawyers that his wife  
once headed the ABC's Commission on Women in the Legal Profession 
as well as the Legal Services Corp., a federally funded program 
providing legal aid to the poor. 
</P>
<P>
	ABA President Phil Anderson is an old friend of Clinton's from  
Little Rock, Ark. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason I'm here is that I got beat for governor in 1980  
and I was the youngest former governor in the history of America,'' 
Clinton said. ``I had extremely limited career prospects and Phil 
Anderson was the only guy in Arkansas that offered me a job. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's either a great prognosticator or a good gambler,''  
Clinton added. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
