<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 10:47:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Derides Spain on Pinochet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attempts by Spanish authorities to try former  
Chilean President Augusto Pinochet for alleged human rights 
violations amount to ``foreign intervention'' and cannot be 
accepted by Chile, Foreign Minister Juan Gabriel Valdes said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't think that foreign intervention, even if it is well  
intentioned, will help solve the problem,'' Valdes told a news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Valdes, here for consultations with U.S. officials, said Chile  
is very much in favor of an international judicial system that 
prosecutes crimes against humanity. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we are not prepared to accept a decision by one court and  
one country by itself to take measures and pretend to subordinate 
our own courts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet was arrested by British authorities last October on  
orders of Spanish Judge Baltasar Garzon. Spanish efforts to 
extradite Pinochet are before the courts. 
</P>
<P>
	Valdes said the Spanish action ignores legal processes in Chile  
to deal with what he admitted was a difficult past. As an example, 
he noted that Pinochet is facing 28 cases in Chilean courts. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James P. Rubin expressed sympathy  
Monday for Chile as it attempts to cope with the problem 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States is committed to the principles of  
accountability and justice, and to supporting Chile as it wrestles 
with the difficult problem of how to balance the need for justice 
with the requirement of reconciliation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Valdes' meetings with U.S. officials were dominated by trade  
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking with reporters on Monday, Valdes said Chile is giving  
up on becoming a member of the North American Free Trade Agreement 
and is instead seeking a bilateral trade agreement with the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	``NAFTA is in the past,'' Valdes said after a meeting with  
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. 
</P>
<P>
	After Mexico joined with the United States and Canada in 1994,  
an invitation was extended to Chile to become NAFTA's fourth 
member. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan failed because of congressional opposition to creating  
new trade agreements or enlarging the scope of existing ones. 
</P>
<P>
	Influenced by labor union opposition, Congress has refused to  
grant President Clinton the ``fast track'' authority he needs to 
negotiate free trade agreements with Chile and other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Valdes said he informed Albright of Chile's decision to invite  
the United States to begin a review process ``leading to the 
initiation of a negotiation beyond the subject of fast track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the NAFTA option dead, Valdes said though a translator,  
``what interests us is a bilateral economic relationship between 
Chile and the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While spurned on its NAFTA bid, Chile has since become an  
associate member of Mercosur, a South American free trade grouping 
led by Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay, and Uruguay. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 21:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 10, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Gunman on Run After L.A. Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Police SWAT teams are surrounding a hotel  
Tuesday night where authorities found a car believed to have been 
carjacked by the suspect in a shooting at a Jewish community center 
that wounded five people. The motive of the gunman, described as a 
balding white man in his 40s, is unknown, police said. The most 
seriously injured in the shooting was a 5-year-old boy who was shot 
in the stomach and leg and lost 30 percent of his blood. He was in 
critical condition after six hours of surgery and his prognosis for 
recovery was fair, his surgeon said. 

</P>
<P>
	Baby AIDS Cases Plummet With Drug  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The number of babies who got AIDS from their  
mothers dropped by two-thirds between 1992 and 1997, largely 
because of prenatal treatment with the drug AZT, a study has found. 
An expert not involved in the study said it suggests the 
possibility of virtually eliminating mother-to-child HIV 
transmission in the United States, an idea that was almost 
unimaginable a few years ago. The number of babies who developed 
AIDS after being infected with HIV before or during birth peaked at 
907 in 1992, then declined 67 percent over the next five years, to 
297 in 1997, the researchers reported in Wednesday's Journal of the 
American Medical Association. 

</P>
<P>
	Four Killed in Calif. Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	ROSEMEAD, Calif. (AP) -- Sheriff's deputies searched Tuesday for  
a man who allegedly shot and killed four people, wounded two 
others, then kidnapped his ex-girlfriend before freeing her hours 
later. Los Angeles County Sheriff's deputies were looking for 
Evelio Rivera Zacarias, 42, and an accomplice who drove him from 
the shooting scene, said Deputy Steve Flamm. The relationship among 
the victims was not immediately known. 

</P>
<P>
	250 Bodies Exhumed in Bosnia  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- Forensic experts,  
reconstructing a 1995 massacre in the Bosnian enclave of 
Srebrenica, have finished exhuming about 250 bodies from a mass 
grave, U.N. officials said Tuesday. United Nations spokeswoman 
Kelly Moore said the bodies will be taken to a morgue, where they 
will be photographed, catalogued and analyzed. Srebrenica was a 
Muslim enclave in northeast Bosnia. The United Nations declared it 
a ``safe heaven'' but did nothing to prevent Bosnian Serb forces 
from overrunning it in July 1995. The enclave's brutal fall left 
over 7,000 Muslim men missing. The men are believed to have been 
systematically executed. So far, some 2,000 bodies have been found. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Issues Peacekeeper Guidelines  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- For the first time, the United Nations  
laid out rules Tuesday regarding the conduct of U.N. peacekeepers, 
stating they must abide by the same international humanitarian laws 
that govern soldiers' actions. Secretary-General Kofi Annan issued 
an executive order to coincide with Thursday's commemoration of the 
50th anniversary of the Geneva Conventions, which governs the 
regulations for international combat. 

</P>
<P>
	Romania Prepares for Eclipse  
</P>
<P>
	RAMNICU VALCEA, Romania (AP) -- Romanian scientists are preparing  
their telescopes for Wednesday's total eclipse of the sun. In 
Ramnicu Valcea, a city of 100,000 about 100 miles northwest of 
Bucharest, the eclipse will be seen for two minutes and 23 seconds 
-- the longest anywhere on Earth. The eclipse will actually start in 
southern England at 11:10 a.m. (6:10 a.m. EDT). The moon's shadow 
will then sweep eastward across northern France, Germany, Austria 
and Yugoslavia and Hungary before reaching Romania. Bulgaria is 
next followed by Turkey, Iraq, Iran, Pakistan and India before 
dying in the Bay of Bengal. 

</P>
<P>
	Pentagon To Honor Spielberg  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Filmmaker Steven Spielberg will be given the  
Pentagon's public service award tomorrow, primarily for his movie 
``Saving Private Ryan.'' Defense Secretary William Cohen feels the 
film helped increase national understanding of the contribution 
that the U.S. military has made to the nation's security and 
character. Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said Cohen would 
present the award to Spielberg at a Pentagon ceremony. 

</P>
