<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woods Searching for Second Major  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- When Tigermania reached its height, Tiger  
Woods could make news with the color of shirt he wore. 
</P>
<P>
	His clothes, his shoes, the head cover for his driver, even his  
caddie -- no bit of information on sports' latest obsession was too 
trivial. His days of heading to a local course for a quick round 
were over, unless that course had tight security. Forget about 
trying to go out for dinner or a show. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a lot to handle, especially for a kid who wasn't even 21.  
</P>
<P>
	``Stanford, even with all of its wonderful classes, didn't have  
this kind of media class being offered,'' he said, looking around 
at a crowd of reporters. ``I had to learn on the go, on the fly. 
And I've made my share of mistakes, but I also did the right 
things, too. I learned from both.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Which is why Woods doesn't get annoyed when he's asked yet again  
about winning his second major. When he blew through Augusta in 
1997, winning the Masters by 12 strokes, it seemed like it would be 
a matter of months before he won another major. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, it's been almost 2 1/2 years. Ten majors have come and  
gone without his name being engraved on another trophy. This week's 
81st PGA Championship at Medinah Country Club is chance No. 11. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I can do is keep giving myself chances and I've come close  
a couple of times this year,'' said Woods, who had an outside shot 
at the Masters entering the final round, tied for third in the U.S. 
Open and tied for seventh in the British Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't win every time you're in the hunt. You'd like to,  
but it just doesn't happen that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though he's still searching for his second major, Woods' game  
has never been better. No, not even in 1997. Since tying for 
seventh in the Byron Nelson in May, he's won three tournaments, 
including a European PGA event. 
</P>
<P>
	His victory in the Western Open last month was his third in four  
tournaments. He leads the PGA in top-three finishes this year with 
six. He dropped to No. 2 in the world this week only because of a 
quirk in the way the rankings are figured. 
</P>
<P>
	Even last year, when he struggled to adjust to changes he made  
in his swing, he held the No. 1 ranking and led the tour with 13 
top-10 finishes despite winning ``only'' one PGA Tour event. 
</P>
<P>
	``My game has improved so much,'' he said. ``Every shot in my  
bag has gotten better, and that's just because of maturity and more 
experience and a lot more practice. Hopefully two, five, 10 years 
down the road from now, I can say I'm a better player than I am 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asking Woods if he can top Jack Nicklaus, who won 18 majors,  
isn't fair, Greg Norman said. The competition when Nicklaus played 
wasn't as deep as it now, when an unknown like Paul Lawrie can win 
the British Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Interest in the sport wasn't as intense in Nicklaus' prime,  
either. Sure, he drew crowds, but not like the thousands who broke 
through the security ropes to follow Woods up the 18th fairway at 
the 1997 Motorola. Reporters from all over the world didn't cover 
the tournaments he played. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's easy for us to sit here and say, `Yeah, it's just another  
golf tournament.' You can wrap yourself in a cocoon and say, `I'm 
not going to read the paper.' But it builds up,'' Norman said. 
``Any young individual coming out nowadays has to be an extremely, 
extremely talented individual and have the ability to deal with 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woods readily admits he wasn't always able to do that. There  
really wasn't anyone on the tour he could ask for advice, either, 
because other golfers couldn't understand what he experienced in 
1997. Few athletes could. 
</P>
<P>
	The only person who'd gone through anything similar was Michael  
Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	``He helped me a lot in '97. He'd had his own run-ins with the  
media and the fans and learned from his mistakes, and he was able 
to share those mistakes with me,'' he said. ``It's nice to have a 
sounding board like that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
