<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coast Guard Limits Pepper Spray Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Eight Coast Guardsmen who used pepper spray and  
water hoses on Cuban refugees trying to swim to shore were cleared, 
and the Guard has revised its policy on such methods, Rear Admiral 
Thad Allen said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	No disciplinary action will be taken against the eight Guardsmen  
involved in the June 29 incident. The eight, who had been 
temporarily removed from law enforcement duty, will be reinstated, 
Allen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The use of pepper spray and fire hoses on the Cuban refugees was  
inappropriate, but Coast Guardsmen were not at fault and acted 
under a flawed policy, Allen said, announcing the results of a 
monthlong investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Under current immigration policy, foreigners who reach U.S.  
shores are allowed to seek asylum, but those intercepted at sea are 
returned to their homeland or another country. 
</P>
<P>
	Use of pepper spray will now be restricted to when there is a  
clear threat to the safety of officers or the refugees. Guardsmen 
also will not be allowed to use water hoses directly against 
people, but may still use them to disable engines, Allen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Live television broadcasts of the confrontation between Coast  
Guardsmen and six Cubans trying to make it to land in Surfside 
prompted widespread protests by Cuban Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation determined that the Cubans repeatedly  
threatened Coast Guard personnel and threatened to harm or kill 
themselves. Those threats were not visible or audible on media 
coverage, Allen said. 
</P>
<P>
	News footage showed Guardsmen blasting the refugees with a hose  
as they stood in their 14-foot rowboat about 150 yards from shore. 
Several Guardsmen swarmed them as they jumped overboard and swam 
toward land. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the swimmers was doused with pepper spray. Two reached  
the beach and four were plucked from the water and detained aboard 
a Coast Guard cutter. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for a prominent Cuban exile group expressed  
disappointment with the Coast Guard report. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that any of us who saw the incident on TV could  
have seen that whatever they (Cubans) were doing posed a threat to 
the Coast Guard,'' said Ninoska Perez of the Miami-based Cuban 
American National Foundation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
