<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nissan Plans Low Emissions Sedan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Nissan North America Inc. said Tuesday that it is  
seeking final approval for a gasoline-powered 2000-model vehicle 
that meets California's super ultra low emission rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The vehicle has a 1.8 liter engine and is a version of the new  
Sentra compact sedan, Nissan said. The automaker said it will be 
unveiled at the North American International Auto Show in Detroit 
in January. 
</P>
<P>
	The low-pollution Sentra is expected to emit about 25 percent of  
the unburned hydrocarbons and 10 percent of the nitrogen oxides of 
the cleanest gasoline-powered car now sold in California, Nissan 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan also said the new vehicle will eliminate all emissions  
from evaporation of raw hydrocarbon gasoline vapors from the fuel 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	``A person will be able to drive this new 2000 model Sentra with  
the 1.8 liter engine 10 miles to work, return home and have the 
vehicle emit less than a typical new car parked in a driveway all 
day with its engine shut off,'' said Robert Strassburger, Nissan 
North America's director for government and technical affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Production is set to begin in February, Nissan said.  
</P>
<P>
	The company said full details about the engine technology would  
be released once the California Air Resources Board gives it final 
certification. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
