<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 15:30:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Competition Fierce for Favre Backup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- If Brett Favre starts the Green Bay  
Packers' first eight games this season, he will pass Ron Jaworski 
and become the most durable quarterback in NFL history. 
</P>
<P>
	Favre has started 109 straight games, a streak that doesn't even  
include 14 straight playoff starts. His backup last season, Doug 
Pederson, threw 24 passes all year and went to Philadelphia as a 
free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	Being Favre's backup during the 1990s has been one of the most  
pressure-free jobs in football, but the three quarterbacks 
competing for two spots on the Packers' roster want the chance 
anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just an honor to work behind one of the greatest that's  
ever played the game,'' said Matt Hasselbeck, who spent last year 
on the Packers' practice squad and turned down a chance to sign 
with Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Veteran Rick Mirer and rookie Aaron Brooks are the other  
competitors for the jobs. The Packers stand a good chance of losing 
one of the three, but offensive coordinator Sherman Lewis said both 
backup spots are wide open as the team enters its exhibition 
schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each one of those guys has pluses and minuses, but all three  
are more than qualified to make this team,'' Lewis said. ``It's not 
going to be an easy decision, but it's going to be decided in our 
preseason games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mirer is the only candidate with NFL experience. The former  
Seattle and Chicago underachiever signed with Green Bay near the 
end of last season's training camp and spent the year as the 
Packers' No. 3 quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's finally hit a level of comfort where he's able to go out  
and play and not think as much,'' quarterbacks coach Mike McCarthy 
said. ``This is his first full year in the offense, so he's had a 
chance to really learn it and apply it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mirer looked solid in the Packers' intrasquad scrimmage last  
Saturday, completing 8-of-11 passes for 81 yards, but he has 
struggled at times during training camp drills. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm getting there with the offense, and I think my  
conditioning is good,'' said Mirer, who didn't play a down last 
year. ``This is a great situation for quarterbacks with a guy like 
Sherm calling the plays. I just want to be a part of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Mirer has the best credentials of the three, he also makes  
more money than Brooks and Hasselbeck, and Mirer's contract calls 
for a sharp increase in pay next season. With Favre still in the 
prime of his career, Mirer is unlikely to be in Green Bay beyond 
this season and could be valuable trade bait. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why the Packers would like to hang on to both Hasselbeck  
and Brooks. Lewis and McCarthy feel that both have the potential to 
be starters in the league with the right seasoning and coaching. 
</P>
<P>
	The quarterback most certain to make the roster is Brooks, the  
Packers' fourth-round draft pick who was a two-year starter at 
Virginia. With his cannon of an arm and underrated field smarts, 
Green Bay's coaches have been amazed by their good fortune in 
selecting him. 
</P>
<P>
	He has even been compared to Don Majkowski, who came to the  
Packers from Virginia and impressed coaches immediately -- just like 
Brooks. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis smiled when asked to compare Brooks with the five  
quarterbacks selected during the first 12 picks of the last draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``He will be better than a couple of those guys,'' said Lewis,  
who helped turn late draft picks Mark Brunell and Ty Detmer into 
quality quarterbacks. ``There's going to be some Hall-of-Famers in 
that group. ... but Aaron's going to be better. He's that good. 
He's going to have a great career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The longest shot in the group is Hasselbeck, a Boston College  
star who spent last season learning the Packers' offense on the 
practice squad. He has shown promise during training camp, and 
completed both passes he threw in the intrasquad scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mark has really learned how to direct the team, and that's a  
great thing to see in a young quarterback,'' Lewis said. ``He looks 
very confident out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ideally, the Packers would like to make Mirer the main backup  
and put either Brooks or Hasselbeck on the practice squad. But both 
young quarterbacks have been so impressive that other teams would 
almost certainly pick up one of them with an offer of a full-time 
roster spots. 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers are particularly concerned about losing the  
potential of Brooks, which means they may ask Hasselbeck to spend 
another year inactive. When asked if he would be open to that 
strategy, Hasselbeck was noncommittal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still think I have a really good shot to make this team,''  
he said. ``I had an opportunity to leave last year (when the Bears 
offered him their No. 3 roster spot), but I wanted to be here, and 
the team wanted me here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Auditions for the jobs begin Saturday, when the Packers play  
host to the New York Jets. Coach Ray Rhodes said Favre will start 
the game but play only briefly, and all three potential backups 
will get ample opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm kind of curious to see what happens myself,'' Rhodes said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 15:30:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Browns Consider Starting QB Couch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEREA, Ohio (AP) -- After just one performance to rave national  
reviews, the Tim Couch Show may be ready to open in Cleveland for 
an extended run. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns wanted to bring their prized rookie quarterback along  
slowly in his first NFL season, allowing Couch to develop behind 
starter Ty Detmer before making him the No. 1 QB. 
</P>
<P>
	Couch was their future, the Browns insisted.  
</P>
<P>
	But following Couch's stellar debut Monday night as the Browns  
returned to the NFL with a 20-17 overtime exhibition victory over 
Dallas, that future could be in two hours, two days or two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, there is a hype,'' said Browns coach Chris Palmer,  
who indicated Couch's ascension could be closer than anyone, 
including Palmer, anticipated. ``To say it's going to happen at the 
end of training camp, I don't know whether I could say that. It 
could happen two weeks from now or it could happen at the end of 
the season. I will say this, I'm very pleased with what he did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his first pro game, Couch showed why the Browns drafted him  
No. 1 overall and gave him a seven-year, $59 million contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Replacing Detmer early in the second quarter, Couch threw an  
incomplete pass on his first attempt before connecting on 10 
straight passes -- one a 24-yard TD to rookie wideout Kevin Johnson, 
a combination Cleveland fans hope to see hook up many times in the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time he was finished, Couch had completed 11 of 17 passes  
for 137 yards with one interception, rushed twice for 14 yards and 
convinced millions of TV viewers they were watching something 
special. 
</P>
<P>
	Granted, some of Couch's work came against Dallas' second- and  
third-unit defenses. But he showed poise in the pocket, took a 
couple of big hits and showed quickness escaping pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the knocks on Couch, who skipped his senior season at  
Kentucky, was a lack of speed. The other was arm strength, but with 
a few deep balls, Couch showed he has all the arm he needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer didn't get to bed following his first NFL game as a coach  
until after 3 a.m. He was up again at 5, but before leaving for 
work, he caught a graphic on ESPN which showed how Couch fared in 
his first game compared to Jeff George, Drew Bledsoe and Peyton 
Manning -- other No. 1 picks -- in their pro debuts. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were not as good as his,'' Palmer said of Couch. ``But  
it's just part of the process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer began noticing a big difference in Couch last week during  
training camp. He saw a more polished player, one becoming 
comfortable with the pro offense and more confident in his ability 
as a passer and leader. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday night, Palmer said Couch's teammates picked up on the  
same thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think one of the things that Tim did last night was that  
other players took notice,'' Palmer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer was particularly impressed with Couch's ability to run  
the offense no matter the line of scrimmage or down. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was pleased with the way Couch managed the game,'' Palmer  
said. ``I expected Ty to get us in to the right situations. I 
didn't know if Tim, under the lights, would be able to do that. He 
took a timeout and didn't let the clock run out. That shows 
tremendous awareness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer doesn't want a quarterback controversy to hinder the  
Browns this season. He says when the moment comes that Couch is 
ready to become an NFL starter, it will be evident to everyone. 
</P>
<P>
	``The media is trying to set a date,'' he said. ``Generally, our  
feeling was if we had him up and running by the middle of the 
season, management and everybody involved with the program would be 
very happy. But I'm not sure he isn't on a faster track than 
that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
