<HEADLINE> BP Amoco Expects To Cut More Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- BP Amoco PLC will cut 4,500 more jobs this year  
than originally planned, even though its second-quarter operating 
income rose by 14 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The company laid off 12,500 people by the end of July and said  
it expects to trim its work force by an additional 2,000 by the end 
of the year, chief executive John Browne told reporters today. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined reductions mark an increase from the company's  
original plan, outlined in February, to cut 10,000 jobs this year. 
The planned cuts would leave BP Amoco with 82,500 employees by the 
year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	A company official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
many of the remaining cuts would come in downstream operations like 
refining and chemicals, which have suffered pinched profit margins 
due to higher prices they must pay for oil. The official refused to 
name the countries where the remaining cuts would be made. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco also said today its operating profit rose to $1.23  
billion in the second quarter, compared to last year's level of 
$1.08 billion. Operating income in its line of business, 
exploration and production led the way, surging 54 percent over the 
year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, formed by British Petroleum PLC's purchase last  
year of Chicago-based Amoco Corp., has realized the financial 
benefits of its merger sooner than anticipated, chief executive 
John Browne said. It expects to save $2 billion per year as a 
result of the union. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco shares rose 1,234 pence ($19.74) in late trading, up  
0.9 percent from Monday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	The improvement in the company's upstream sector stemmed largely  
from higher oil prices, which boosted profits. Average oil prices 
during the three months ending June 30 were $14.49 per barrel, 
against $12.13 during the same quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco is currently in the process of absorbing Atlantic  
Richfield Corp. and is expected to approve the takeover in 
September. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
