<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dell, Motorola Embrace Linux System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Dell Computers and Motorola Inc. on Monday joined a growing list  
of companies moving to embrace the Linux computer operating system, 
upping the ante in a challenge to Microsoft's dominance. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell said it plans in the next few months to offer clients  
buying its popular Dimension desktop PCs and Inspiron notebook 
computer line the option of choosing the Linux operating system 
over Windows 95, 98 or NT. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorola's Computer Group announced it will work with  
Linux-based platforms to develop an array of products embedded in 
smaller computing devices such as the Palm personal digital 
assistants. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves represent the first significant show of faith in Linux  
from vendors who serve the consumer market, said Amy Wohl, an 
independent consultant with Wohl &AMP; Associates, which tracks the 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``This certainly ups the ante,'' Wohl said. ``It's a sign that  
mainstream vendors think there is a market for Linux. They don't do 
this for fun, they do this because they have customers saying 'We 
would buy this if you have it,' which makes for a greater challenge 
against Windows.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The announcements came as the second-ever LinuxWorld conference  
opened in San Jose, Calif., drawing dozens of vendors who were 
expected to throw their support toward the system. 
</P>
<P>
	Users praise the system's flexibility and propensity not to  
crash. But it often requires people to memorize and type in 
commands, similar to the DOS software that preceded Windows -- 
daunting to everyday users. And the number of Linux-compatible 
software applications, while growing, pales against the number of 
applications available for Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Linux is emerging as a threat to Microsoft in the  
lucrative consumer marketplace and has attracted such investors as 
Intel Corp., the biggest computer chip-maker, because it is free 
and is based on a so-called open-source platform that allows anyone 
to work to improve the software code. 
</P>
<P>
	Linux's basic operating system also is much smaller than Windows  
NT and other Unix competitors. That is attractive because it means 
there is less of a power drain on smaller computing devices. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it remains unclear just how much consumers might be  
willing to embrace alternatives to Windows, particularly with PCs. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell spokesman Tad Druart said customers who buy high-end  
systems have expressed interest in buying computers with Linux 
operating systems, driving the company's decision to offer the 
option. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not that we expect to make this widely available to the  
masses,'' Druart said from Dell's Round Rock, Texas, headquarters. 
``It's for those customers who have an interest in using Linux and 
want to do so on a Dell Dimension.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Red Hat Inc. -- a fast-growing seller of Linux software -- this  
week is expected to offer its shares to the public. Analysts say 
the interest will be another test of Linux's staying power. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
