<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Football Star Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Former Southern Mississippi football  
player Chris Buckhalter was sentenced to 20 years in prison after 
pleading guilty to a reduced charge of manslaughter in a 1997 
slaying. 
</P>
<P>
	Buckhalter, 26, avoided a possible death penalty with his plea  
before the start of his capital murder trial Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Buckhalter and three others were accused in the April 24, 1997,  
killing of Jason ``Puddin'' Langley, 22, and the shooting of 
Leonard McInnis at a Jackson apartment complex. McInnis was shot 
several times in the chest but recovered from the wounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Buckhalter, a four-year letterman at Southern Miss from 1992-95,  
surrendered in January 1998 after eluding authorities for nine 
months. He pleaded innocent last year but told Circuit Judge L. 
Breland Hilburn he was changing his plea in his own best interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were dealing with a capital murder charge, and you know  
what that can yield,'' Buckhalter's lawyer, Johnnie Walls Jr., 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to manslaughter, Buckhalter pleaded guilty to one  
count of aggravated assault. A 20-year sentence on that charge will 
run concurrent with the manslaughter penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant district attorney Bobby DeLaughter said the Langley  
family agreed to the plea. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the other three suspects, Anthony Sanders, accidentally  
shot himself to death while fleeing police in 1997. The other two 
unnamed suspects remain at large. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his success on the field, Buckhalter had a troubled  
career at Southern Miss in Hattiesburg. He later was on the 
Philadelphia Eagles practice squad from 1996-97. 
</P>
<P>
	On the field for Southern Miss, Buckhalter had 1,533 career  
rushing yards, and led the Eagles in rushing in both 1994 and 1995. 
But in the 1999 Southern Miss football media guide released earlier 
this month, references to Buckhalter and those accomplishments were 
erased. 
</P>
<P>
	His name was even removed from the list of lettermen in the 1999  
edition of the media guide. Buckhalter's name had appeared in the 
1998 book and those before it. 
</P>
<P>
	Buckhalter was dismissed from the team and suspended from the  
university in spring 1993 after being charged with aggravated 
assault. The arrest stemmed from a fight during a dance on the 
campus. He spent five days in jail, and later was reinstated to the 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Buckhalter was arrested on felony marijuana and cocaine  
possession charges in July 1995. Both charges were dropped, but he 
was still suspended from the team for two games. Even after missing 
the first two games, he was the team's leading rusher for the 
second straight season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
