<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grand Jury Investigating Lockheed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A federal grand jury is investigating  
possible sales kickbacks by a unit of aerospace giant Lockheed 
Martin Corp., the company told federal regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission,  
Lockheed said it received a federal subpoena on July 15 seeking 
documents relating to the 1990 sales of radar systems by its New 
Hampshire-based Sanders unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Patricia Beaman and Lockheed refused to  
elaborate on the disclosure Monday. But the Los Angeles Times, 
quoting an anonymous source, reported today that the grand jury is 
seeking information involving sales that may have begun before 
Lockheed purchased Sanders in 1986 and continued long past 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal, which also reported the probe, said  
investigators are focused on the Lockheed unit's efforts to land 
military contracts from Taiwan. It involves alleged improper 
payments to consultant Richard Hei, who was accused of receiving 
millions of dollars in illegal commissions from two other large 
U.S. contractors, the newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee Whitney, spokesman for Bethesda, Md.-based Lockheed Martin,  
said company officials ``do not believe we have violated any laws 
or regulations and we continue to cooperate fully with the U.S. 
Attorney's office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hei was a consultant with ties to Taiwan's military and  
government officials and he also worked for units of Litton and 
former Teledyne Inc. Those companies previously pleaded guilty to 
criminal charges stemming from improper payments to Hei and 
admitted trying to hide the payments from federal auditors. 
</P>
<P>
	Journal sources said the current federal grand jury probe of the  
Lockheed unit is an offshoot of those earlier investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	The grand jury subpoena sought documents relating to the 1990  
international sale of area defense radar systems by the predecessor 
of Lockheed Martin Sanders and the compensation of an international 
sales consultant in connection with that sale, Lockheed said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Journal source said the focus is on a $44.5 million radar  
contract Sanders won from Taiwan to detect low-flying aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockheed Martin Sanders Inc., a wholly owned subsidiary of  
Lockheed Martin, is the result of the January 1990 merger of 
Lockheed Electronics Co. and Sanders Associates Inc. Sanders is no 
longer in the radar business. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
