<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Rudeness at Work on the Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Rude behavior is on the rise in the workplace and  
men are the ones to blame, a new study says. 
</P>
<P>
	Although men and women are targets of disrespect and rudeness in  
equal numbers, researchers say men instigate the rudeness 70 
percent of the time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to make organizations aware of this,'' said study  
co-author Christine M. Pearson, a management professor at the 
University of North Carolina business school. ``You can calculate 
the costs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve percent of the people who experience rude behavior quit  
their jobs to avoid the perpetrator, the researchers found. 
Fifty-two percent reported losing work time worrying and 22 percent 
deliberately decreased their work effort. 
</P>
<P>
	The study, ``Workplace Incivility: The Target's Eye View,'' was  
presented Tuesday at the Academy of Management's annual convention. 
The authors interviewed and surveyed 1,400 workers and generated a 
list of suggestions to improve the workplace culture. 
</P>
<P>
	The majority of those interviewed, 78 percent, said incivility  
has worsened in the past 10 years. The authors also found that rude 
people are three times more likely to be in higher positions than 
their targets. 
</P>
<P>
	And, men are the worst offenders, Pearson said. They are seven  
times more likely be rude or insensitive to underlings than to 
superiors. Women are equally rude to superiors and subordinates, 
the researchers found. 
</P>
<P>
	Fay Taylor, 49, a marketing director in Chicago, said she is not  
surprised. 
</P>
<P>
	``Men are more like bulls in a china shop when they are trying  
to get a job done,'' Taylor said. ``Women tend to couch things more 
carefully.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, she added, ``If a woman is going to be rude, she's going to  
be rude. She'll butt in at the highest levels and the lowest 
levels.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another study, to be presented to the convention Wednesday,  
found that nearly 25 percent of respondents were ``generally at 
least somewhat angry at work.'' The 1996 Gallup telephone survey 
questioned 1,000 adults age 18 or older who work full- or 
part-time. 
</P>
<P>
	Authors of the study say the statistic may help explain recent  
outbursts of workplace violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``In an environment where you think people are satisfied with  
their jobs, there is a sort of undercurrent of anger and resentment 
aimed at the workplace that could potentially lead to the kinds of 
explosions of rage we have seen,'' said Donald Gibson, a professor 
at the Yale University School of Management and a co-author the 
study. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say workplace rage was a factor in the July 29  
shooting spree in which Mark O. Barton killed nine people and 
injured 12 others in two Atlanta office buildings where he worked 
as a day trader. A week later, Alan Eugene Miller killed three 
people at two Pelham, Ala., companies where he had worked, 
prosecutors say. 
</P>
<P>
	The study was sponsored by Marlin Co., a Connecticut-based  
management consulting firm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 14:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grand Jury Investigates Lockheed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A federal grand jury is investigating whether  
Lockheed Martin Corp. paid kickbacks to win contracts for the sale 
of military radar systems to Taiwan, the largest U.S. defense 
contractor disclosed in documents filed with the Securities and 
Exchange Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Lockheed deals also were under scrutiny, a source familiar  
with the investigation told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation centers on payments made to Richard Hei, a  
former Taiwanese air force officer and arms consultant who helped 
secure contracts for radar sold by Lockheed Martin Sanders, a 
wholly owned subsidiary, in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement issued Tuesday, Lockheed denied wrongdoing and  
said it was cooperating with investigators. A spokesman declined to 
comment further. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials with the U.S. Attorney's Office would not comment on  
the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The grand jury also is looking at other Lockheed sales for  
possible wrongdoing, the source said on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking for material involving any number of sales which  
may or may not have violated the law. We have evidence pointing to 
at least one sale,'' the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense industry has become more careful about the use of  
foreign intermediaries since bribery scandals of the late 1980s and 
early 1990s, when overseas sales were booming and oversight was 
less stringent, said Jon Kutler, president of Quarterdeck 
Investment Partners, an investment bank that focuses on aerospace 
deals. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a little bit of a flashback,'' he said. ``A decade ago  
I think it was more a case of companies not wanting to know what 
was going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an SEC filing Monday, Lockheed disclosed the investigation  
was under way, but provided few details about the probe. 
</P>
<P>
	The document said Lockheed received a subpoena on July 15 for  
records ``relating to the 1990 international sale of area defense 
radar systems by the predecessor of Lockheed Martin Sanders and the 
compensation of an international sales consultant in connection 
with that sale.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lockheed Martin shares were little changed Tuesday, edging up 6 1/4  
cents to $35.25 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The probe isn't the first involving Hei, who set up a small  
consulting firm after leaving the air force and was hired by 
several big U.S. defense firms to help broker sales of military 
equipment to Taiwan. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, Litton Industries Inc. agreed to pay $18.5 million to  
settle a criminal investigation of Taiwan sales involving payments 
to Hei. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, the former Teledyne Inc. pleaded guilty to federal  
fraud charges alleging that it paid Hei $3.2 million in illegal 
commissions between 1986 and 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire-based Sanders is no longer in the radar business.  
The company still manufactures other types of electronic warfare 
equipment for the U.S. military and foreign governments as well as 
electronics for commercial space ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, previously known as Sanders Associates Inc., was  
acquired by the former Lockheed Corp. in January 1990. It became a 
part of Lockheed Martin when Lockheed merged with Martin Marietta 
Corp. in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The grand jury's investigation is similar to the earlier probes  
involving Hei, but originated independently of them, the source 
said. While other Lockheed deals are being looked at, no other 
companies are involved in this probe, the source said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 03:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Lukas, Baze Join Horse Racing Hall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- A plaque honoring D. Wayne Lukas  
now hangs on the wall at the National Racing Museum's Hall of Fame. 
That doesn't mean he's going anywhere. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel even better about the next eight to 10 years than I do  
about the last 10 years,'' Lukas said Monday. ``We're putting 
together an even stronger group, and some serious things are going 
to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas has conditioned more champions than any other thoroughbred  
trainer, won a record 13 Breeders Cup races and amassed more than 
$200 million in career purse earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	And it took more than just luck to get him there.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe in the luck factor,'' Lukas said. ``If you  
have to depend on luck in this game, you're gonna get beat a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also inducted Monday were jockey Russell Baze and thoroughbred  
racehorses Exceller, Miesque and Gun Bow. 
</P>
<P>
	The list of Lukas' achievements is long enough to line a  
racetrack. Highlights include receiving the Eclipse Award as the 
nation's top trainer four times, winning the Belmont Stakes three 
times and winning 12 Triple Crown races. His most recent Triple 
Crown victories came this year, when Charismatic won the Derby and 
the Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas has led the nation in earnings 14 of the last 16 years,  
and his 1998 mark of $17.8 million is a record that still stands. 
</P>
<P>
	With the ceremony spotlight centered squarely on him, Lukas, 63,  
chose to share the glory with a half-dozen assistants who gathered 
around him onstage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those records would never have happened without these guys,''  
Lukas said, his voice quivering. ``You guys have propped me up, 
carried me. And I know I wasn't easy to work for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a tradeout here, and I got the best in the trade --  
just like I do every time I trade (horses) with you guys,'' he 
said, grinning at the other trainers in the audience. 
</P>
<P>
	His assistants joked about Lukas' short temper and  
``expletive-laced tirades,'' but they were heavy in their praise. 
</P>
<P>
	``So many things have changed in our industry because of Wayne  
Lukas,'' former Lukas assistant Mark Hennig said. ``So many 
trainers never run multiple divisions, and he's shown us the 
reality that any race is just one flight away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even with his success, Lukas said it ``hasn't always been blue  
skies and clear sailing in my career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been solidly criticized by certain people in the industry  
and the media who don't always agree with what we do. But I make no 
apologies for what we've tried to do,'' Lukas said. 
</P>
<P>
	In his 25-year career, Baze has ridden 6,662 winners and earned  
more than $94.5 million in purses. He has also been the only rider 
to record 400 or more wins in each of the last seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past four years, Baze has been awarded the Isaac Murphy  
Award, presented by the National Turf Writers Association to the 
jockey with the highest winning percentage. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason I have been able to set those numbers that I have  
for the last couple of years is because I've been able to go out 
every day and do it,'' Baze said. ``I've been blessed that I 
haven't been injured.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Exceller, who raced from 1975 to 1979, came from 22 lengths back  
to beat two Triple Crown winners in the 1 1/2-mile Jockey Club Gold 
Cup in 1978. Exceller won by a nose over Triple Crown winner 
Seattle Slew and Affirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Miesque, who was based in Europe for her entire racing career,  
made two starts in the United States, won two Grade I races, and 
was voted two Eclipse Awards. She also won a total of eight Group I 
races in France and England. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun Bow raised eyebrows in 1964 when he defeated Kelso by 12  
lengths at the Brooklyn Handicap. That autumn, they split in two 
dramatic duels in the Aqueduct and Woodward Stakes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 03:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
