<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 19:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Five Shot at L.A. Jewish Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A man with a high-powered gun burst into a  
Jewish community center Tuesday and sprayed the lobby with 20 to 30 
shots, wounding five people, including three boys attending day 
camp, and then walked out. 
</P>
<P>
	Police failed to find the suspect -- a balding white man about 40  
years old -- in a street-by-street search near the center, but late 
in the day officers found a green Toyota Corolla taken in a nearby 
carjacking that was under investigation for a possible connection. 
</P>
<P>
	The motive for the attack was not known. ``Every possibility,  
including if it's a hate crime, we'll look into it,'' said Officer 
Guillermo Campos. 
</P>
<P>
	The most seriously injured was a 5-year-old boy who was shot in  
the stomach and leg and underwent surgery. He was in critical but 
stable condition. Two 6-year-old boys, a 16-year-old girl and a 
68-year-old woman who worked at the center were in stable 
condition, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	A teacher who spoke on condition of anonymity said the injured  
woman, a receptionist, burst into her room with a wounded arm. The 
teacher said she gathered up her students, who joined hands and 
evacuated from the building. 
</P>
<P>
	The violence was the latest in a series of shootings at  
workplaces and schools, and as the search for the gunman continued, 
President Clinton and others spoke out. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once again, our nation has been shaken and our hearts torn by  
gun violence,'' Clinton said in Washington. ``It calls on all of us 
not only to give our thoughts and prayers to the victims and their 
families, but intensify our resolve to make America a safer 
place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Gray Davis said he was forming a task force of state  
agencies to advise churches, child care centers and other 
operations that care for children on how to upgrade their security 
systems. 
</P>
<P>
	About two dozen children were in the center when the gunman  
burst into the North Valley Jewish Community Center and began 
spraying the lobby with bullets about 10:50 a.m., said Capt. Steve 
Ruda of the Los Angeles Fire Department. He fired up to 30 shots 
before walking down a hallway and out of the building, Ruda said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruda said he believed the shooter used a 9mm Uzi. Police Chief  
Bernard Parks however, would only identify the gun as a 
high-powered weapon with a large magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was nothing said by the suspect before the shooting,''  
Parks said. ``It was indiscriminate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after the shooting, officers raced to a spot nearby  
where a woman reported that a man resembling the suspect's 
description carjacked her Toyota, leaving a red-and-white van 
behind. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers searched the van, which had Washington state plates,  
and found a large amount of ammunition, bulletproof vests and 
devices that may be smoke grenades, but no weapons, said police 
Cmdr. Dave Kalish. Contents of the van included metal boxes packed 
with ammunition, magazines for an assault rifle, a booklet titled 
Ranger Handbook and freeze-dried food. 
</P>
<P>
	Kalish said it wasn't certain the carjacker and gunman were the  
same person. When officers found the Toyota in a hotel parking lot 
a few miles from the community, a SWAT team was summoned to the 
hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	The van was bought Saturday from the Tacoma (Wash.) Kar Korner,  
said the manager of the lot, who refused to be identified. He said 
police had ordered him not to give out any information on the 
buyer. 
</P>
<P>
	While SWAT teams were swarming around the community center and  
news and police helicopters buzzed overhead, about 20 small 
children were led unhurt from the building hand in hand and taken 
to a Jewish temple nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	Parents rushed to the center and jammed against police lines  
trying to find out if their children were all right. Some parents 
wept and hugged one another. One man was handcuffed by officers 
after slipping under yellow police tape, but he was later released. 
Authorities used a fire department loudspeaker to announce the 
whereabouts of children. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to cry when I saw him,'' said Karen Macofsky, who was  
reunited with her 11-year-old son and 8-year-old daughter. ``But I 
held back and just hugged him tightly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Macalas prayed and recited psalms as he rushed to check  
on his children, ages 2 and 3. ``My feeling about it is it's 
another case of someone acting out in rage,'' he said. ``I don't 
want to believe this is an act of anti-Semitism here in 1999.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities were searching for the gunman throughout the  
neighborhood of mostly single-family homes in the San Fernando 
Valley suburbs 30 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Rabbi Marvin Hier, dean of the Simon Wiesenthal Center, said  
about 20 older children from the Jewish center were touring the 
Wiesenthal center's Museum of Tolerance at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's ironic that the 20 children were here learning about  
man's inhumanity to man, when their own day camp became a target of 
such hatred,'' Hier said. 
</P>
<P>
	The program director at the North Valley center told Hier that  
most of the children had been playing outside when the gunman 
stormed in, Hier said. 
</P>
<P>
	The community center provides nursery programs, child care and  
camp activities. It has a large main building, a smaller houselike 
structure, a pool and tennis courts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 15:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't To Pay for Indian Suit Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge ordered the government Tuesday  
to pay more than $600,000 for failing to produce documents promptly 
in a lawsuit concerning the trouble-plagued Indian trust fund. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth said the payment is to cover  
``all expenses and reasonable attorney fees'' incurred by Indian 
plaintiffs because of government delay and misconduct in not 
providing records that detail trust fund mismanagement. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamberth said that he was dismayed that taxpayers ``will be  
forced to pay for the misconduct of their government's officials 
and attorneys.'' He said in his 45-page opinion he wished he could 
hold individual government attorneys liable but is precluded from 
doing so. 
</P>
<P>
	The order does not address the merits of the class-action  
lawsuit brought by the Indians, who demand the court take over the 
trouble-plagued trust fund, overhaul its error-filled accounting 
system and make restitutions to Indians who lost money. 
</P>
<P>
	The award of fees stems from a two-year period in which lawyers  
for the Indians were blocked repeatedly from obtaining documents on 
individual Indian accounts. The legal fees and other expenses, 
totaling $624,643.50 to be awarded to seven attorneys, cover from 
November, 1996, to January this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is gratifying that the judge is holding the government  
accountable,'' said Jim McCarthy, spokesman for the Indians. ``The 
Department of Interior's tactics of delay and denial and cover-up 
against American Indians will no longer be tolerated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We think this is a reasonable decision,'' said Interior  
Department spokesman Tim Ahearn. 
</P>
<P>
	The Interior Department was ordered in late 1996 to turn over  
statements, checks and other documents concerning trust-fund 
accounts held by five Indians who are lead plaintiffs in the 
lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Government lawyers and officials ``almost immediately disobeyed  
(the order) and successfully covered up their disobedience through 
semantics and strained, unilateral, self-serving interpretations of 
their own duties,'' wrote Lamberth in assessing the legal fees, 
</P>
<P>
	In late February, Lamberth found Interior Secretary Bruce  
Babbitt and then-Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin in contempt 
because they failed to produce documents sought by the Indians in 
connection with the suit. He accused Interior officials of 
foot-dragging and making ``outright false statements'' to keep from 
turning over the records. 
</P>
<P>
	The government argued that many records involving more than  
300,000 Indian accounts were missing, others were stored 
haphazardly including some in a warehouse that for a time had been 
infected by virus-carrying rodents. Many of the records still have 
not been found, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The government admits it cannot accurately document the $550  
million fund that belongs to individual Indians from land holdings, 
royalty payments and other assets dating back generations. Another 
$2.5 billion in the fund belongs to Indian tribes but is not part 
of the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians had sought more than $2.3 million in reimbursements  
for legal fees and expenses, but Lamberth denied some fees as well 
as about $1.2 million paid to an accounting firm to try to assess 
how much money should be in the trust accounts by using a sampling 
of accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	The court-ordered payments totaled $329,237 to Dennis Gingold  
and $19,312 to Thaddeus Holt, both banking attorneys hired by the 
Indians; $252,147 to five attorneys working for the Native American 
Rights Fund, which is financing the lawsuit; and $23,948 for 
various expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Lamberth has received final arguments in the suit and  
could rule this month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 16:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> United To Loosen Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELK GROVE VILLAGE, Ill. (AP) -- Following the example of other  
major air carriers, United Airlines announced Tuesday that it is 
eliminating many of the restrictions on its frequent flier program. 
</P>
<P>
	The suburban Chicago-based airline said its Mileage Plus program  
members' frequent flier miles will last indefinitely as long as 
passengers use their accounts every 36 months. That means the 37 
million people enrolled in the program may not ever see mileage 
expire as long as they continue to accrue or use points. 
</P>
<P>
	United said it will also reinstate 1998 expired miles to members  
who register and take either two paid domestic round trips or one 
paid international round trip on flights operated by United, United 
Shuttle or United Express. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year was the first year that Mileage Plus members' frequent  
flier miles were subject to expiration, said United spokesman 
Graham Atkinson. Members who had at least 20,000 miles, however, 
were able to roll their miles over into 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	To keep their accounts active in the future, members can accrue  
miles by using services affiliated with the program, such as credit 
card purchases, long distance phone calls, car rentals, hotel stays 
and cruises. 
</P>
<P>
	United's decision follows American Airline's similar  
announcement earlier this month. Northwest Airlines eased its 
restrictions in January, and Delta Air Lines had dropped most of 
its expiration requirements three years ago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 13:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How Do I Get My Own Web Site? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Q: Many online services give subscribers a free page on a shared  
Web site with a shared domain name. But how can I get a 
personalized domain name for my own Web site? 

</P>
<P>
	A: Registering a domain name with an address ending in ``.com,  
``.net'' and ``.org'' is relatively simple and inexpensive. The 
hard part is finding a domain name that's not taken. 
</P>
<P>
	There are already more than 5 million domain names ending with  
those three tags, and the total could double within a year. 
</P>
<P>
	In theory, since a domain name can be up to 22 characters long,  
there are 80 billion possible combinations of letters and numbers 
that can be registered under ``.com'' or any other suffix. But most 
of the simplest names are long gone and most of the remaining 
variations would look like gibberish. 
</P>
<P>
	New suffixes like ``.web'' or ``.store'' have been proposed, but  
there's no sign they'll be adopted any time soon. So for most 
people, ``.com'' is still the most likely choice. 
</P>
<P>
	To find out if a domain name is still available, use the search  
engine provided by Internet services like Earthlink and Mindspring, 
or go directly to one of the companies authorized to register new 
names, including www.networksolutions.com and www.register.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Type in the desired name (i.e. ``www.yourname.com'') and the  
search engine will tell you if it's available. If it is, you'll be 
given an option to reserve the name and steered through a simple 
registration process. 
</P>
<P>
	Generally, you'll be asked for basic information such as your  
name and e-mail address, and a credit card number to pay a $70 fee 
that gives you a renewable two-year lease on the domain name. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the registration services charge an additional $40 to  
$50 to set up a domain name and perform simple functions like 
putting a welcome page at the new address to identify you or your 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	The next step, if your ready to set up a more elaborate Web page  
or pages, is to choose a company that can ``host'' the site on its 
computer servers. That way, other computers will know where to look 
when friends, family, customers and other would-be visitors try to 
check out or use your site. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the companies that provide dial-up Internet access also  
sell Web hosting services, which include handling the flow of 
e-mail to and from the site. 
</P>
<P>
	Basic hosting packages, which usually come with simple tools to  
build a Web site, generally cost $20 to $30 a month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990810.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 23:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Band Nominated for Bluegrass Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Members of The Del McCoury Band topped  
the nominations for the International Bluegrass Music Awards. 
</P>
<P>
	Winners will be revealed Oct. 21 at the Palace Theater in  
Louisville, Ky. At the ceremony, fiddler Kenny Baker will be 
inducted into the International Bluegrass Music Association Hall of 
Honor. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of The Del McCoury Band, who last year won the top award  
of best entertainer, were nominated Tuesday in 11 categories, 
including best entertainer. 
</P>
<P>
	Competitors in that category were Lonesome River Band, Blue  
Highway, Ricky Skaggs and Kentucky Thunder, and IIIrd Tyme Out. 
</P>
<P>
	Other nominees in 17 categories included Ralph Stanley, pop  
music star Bob Dylan, Sam Bush and Alison Krauss. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
